{"title_page": "Contango", "text_new": "[[File:Contangobackwardation.png|thumb|upright=1.5|This graph depicts how the price of a single [[forward contract]] will typically behave through time in relation to the expected future price at any point in time. A futures contract in contango will normally decrease in value until it equals the spot price of the underlying at maturity.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} Note that this graph does not show the [[forward curve]] (which plots against maturities on the horizontal).]]\n\n'''Contango''', also sometimes called '''forwardation''', is a situation where the [[futures contract|futures price]] (or [[forward contract|forward price]]) of a commodity is higher than the [[spot price]] of the contract today.<ref name=OxfordDictEcon2008>{{cite dictionary|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780199237043.001.0001/acref-9780199237043-e-3523?rskey=KFzJUD&result=531|series=A Dictionary of Economics|edition=3|title=Contango|editor1=John Black|editor2=Nigar Hashimzade|editor3=Gareth Myles|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=2009|isbn=9780199237043}}</ref><ref name=\"investopedia_contango\">{{cite web|url=http://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/contango.asp |publisher=[[Investopedia]]|title=Contango|accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref> In a contango situation, arbitrageurs or speculators,<ref name=\"CEC2008\">{{cite report|url=http://ec.europa.eu/economy_finance/publications/publication13765_en.pdf|title=Is There a Speculative Bubble in Commodity Markets?|date=21 November 2008|publisher=Commission of the European Communities|location=Brussels|format=PDF|number=SEC(2008)2971|work=Task force on the role of speculation in agricultural commodities price movements}}</ref> are \"willing to pay more [now] for a commodity [to be received] at some point in the future than the actual expected price of the commodity [at that future point]. This may be due to people's desire to pay a premium to have the commodity in the future rather than paying the costs of storage and carry costs of buying the commodity today.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} On the other side of the trade, hedgers (commodity producers and commodity holders) are happy to sell futures contracts and accept the higher-than-expected returns. A contango market is also known as a normal market, or carrying-cost market.\n\nThe opposite market condition to contango is known as [[backwardation]]. \"A market is 'in backwardation' when the futures price is below the spot price for a particular commodity. This is favorable for investors who have long positions since they want the futures price to rise to the level of the current spot price\".<ref name=\"investopedia_contango\" />\n\nThe futures or [[forward curve]] would ''typically'' be upward sloping (i.e. \"normal\"), since contracts for further dates would typically trade at even higher prices. (The curves in question plot market prices for various contracts at different maturities \u2014 cf. [[term structure of interest rates]]) \"In broad terms, backwardation reflects the majority market view that spot prices will move down, and contango that they will move up. Both situations allow speculators (non-commercial traders)<ref>\"A non-commercial trader is a trader that is not commercially engaged in business activities hedged by the use of the futures or option markets (CFTC classification). The non-commercial classification does not include swap dealers and commodity index trading is generally considered as commercial\"</ref> to earn a profit.\".<ref name=\"CEC2008\" />\n\nA contango is normal for a non-perishable commodity that has a [[cost of carry]]. Such costs include [[warehousing]] fees and [[interest]] forgone on money tied up (or the time-value-of money, etc.), less income from [[leasing]] out the commodity if possible (''e.g.'' [[gold]]).<ref>{{cite web | first = Izabella | last = Kaminska | title = It's the BIS| url = http://ftalphaville.ft.com/blog/2010/07/08/281601/the-bis/ | work = [[FT Alphaville]] | date = 8 July 2010 | accessdate = 2010-09-01 }}</ref> For perishable commodities, price differences between near and far delivery are not a contango.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} Different delivery dates are in effect entirely different commodities in this case, since fresh [[Egg (food)|eggs]] today will not still be fresh in 6 months' time, 90-day [[Government bond|treasury bills]] will have matured, etc.\n\n== Description ==\nA normal [[forward curve]] depicting the prices of multiple contracts, all for the same good, but of different maturities, slopes upward. For example, a forward oil contract for twelve months in the future is selling for $100 today, while today's spot price is $75. The expected spot price twelve months in the future may actually still be $75. To purchase a contract at more than $75 supposes a loss (the \"loss\" would be $25 if the contract were purchased for $100) to the agent who \"bought forward\" as opposed to waiting a year to buy at the spot price when oil is actually needed. But even so, there is utility for the forward buyer in the deal. Experience tells major end users of commodities (such as gasoline refineries, or cereal companies that use great quantities of grain) that spot prices are unpredictable. Locking in a future price puts the purchaser \"first in line\" for delivery even though the contract will, as it matures, converge on the spot price as shown in the graph. In uncertain markets where end users must constantly have a certain input of a stock of goods, a combination of forward (future) and spot buying reduces uncertainty. An oil refiner might purchase 50% spot and 50% forward, getting an average price of $87.50 averaged for one barrel spot ($75) and the one barrel bought forward ($100). This strategy also results in unanticipated, or \"windfall\" profits: If the contract is purchased forward twelve months at $100 and the actual price is $150, the refiner will take delivery of one barrel of oil at $100 and the other at a spot price of $150, or $125 averaged for two barrels: a gain of $25 per barrel relative to spot prices.\n\nSellers like to \"sell forward\" because it locks in an income stream. Farmers are the classic example: by selling their crop forward when it is still in the ground they can lock in a price, and therefore an income, which helps them qualify, in the present, for credit.\n\nThe graph of the \"life of a single futures contract\" (as shown above on the right) will show it converging towards the spot price. The contango contract for future delivery, selling today, is at a price premium relative to buying the commodity today and taking delivery. The backwardation contract selling today is lower than the spot price, and its trajectory will take it upward to the spot price when the contract closes. Paper assets are no different: for example, an insurance company has a constant stream of income from premiums and a constant stream of payments for claims. Income must be invested in new assets and existing assets must be sold to pay off claims. By investing in the purchase and sale of some bonds \"forward\" in addition to buying spot, an insurance company can smooth out changes in its portfolio and anticipated income.\n\nThe Oil Storage contango was introduced to the market in early 1990 by the Swedish-based oil storage company Scandinavian Tank Storage AB and its founder [[Lars Valentin Jacobsson]] by using huge military storage installations to bring down the \"calculation\" cost of storage to create a contango situation out of a \"flat\" market.\n\nContango is a potential trap for unwary investors. [[Exchange-traded fund]]s (ETFs) provide an opportunity for small investors to participate in commodity futures markets, which is tempting in periods of low interest rates. Between 2005 and 2010 the number of futures-based commodity ETFs rose from 2 to 95, and total assets rose from $3.9 billion to nearly $98 billion in the same period.<ref name=\"cuitripped\">Carolyn Cui, \"Getting Tripped Up by the Contango: A futures-market quirk can hurt commodities returns\u2014if investors aren't aware of it,\" ''The Wall Street Journal'', 17 December 2010, pp. C5, C8.</ref> Because the normal course of a futures contract in a market in contango is to decline in price, a fund composed of such contracts buys the contracts at the high price (going forward) and closes them out later at the usually lower spot price. The money raised from the low priced, closed out contracts will not buy the same number of new contracts going forward. Funds can and have lost money even in fairly stable markets. There are strategies to mitigate this problem, including allowing the ETF to create a stock of precious metals for the purpose of allowing investors to speculate on fluctuations in its value. But storage costs will be quite variable, an example being that copper ingots require considerably more storage space, and thus carrying cost, than gold, and command lower prices in world markets: it is unclear how well a model that works for gold will work with other commodities.<ref name=\"cuitripped\" /> Industrial scale buyers of major commodities, particularly when compared to small retail investors, retain an advantage in futures markets. The raw material cost of the commodity is only one of many factors that influence their final costs and prices. Contango pricing strategies that catch small investors by surprise are more familiar to the managers of a large firm, who must decide whether to take delivery of a product today, at today's spot price, and store it themselves, or pay more for a forward contract, and let someone else do the storage for them.<ref>Tatyana Shumsky and Carolyn Cui, \"Trader Holds $3 Billion of Copper in London,\" ''The Wall Street Journal'', 21 December 2010, quoting a trader: \"'Holding ready-for-delivery metals on an exchange isn't a cheap undertaking for traders, who are responsible for paying insurance, storage and financing costs.\" And 'the end game is to find somebody to buy something you have already bought for a higher price,' Mr. Threkeld says. 'The recent boom in metal prices has enabled traders to purchase the physical metal, sell a futures contract at a much higher price and still make a profit after paying for storage and insurance.'\"</ref>\n\nThe contango should not exceed the cost of carry, because producers and consumers can compare the [[futures contract]] price against the spot price plus storage, and choose the better one. Arbitrageurs can sell one and buy the other for a theoretically risk-free profit (see [[Rational pricing#Futures|rational pricing\u2014futures]]). The EU describes the two groups of players in the commodity futures market, hedgers (commodity producers and commodity users) or arbitrageurs/speculators (non-commercial investors).<ref name=\"CEC2008\" />\n\nIf there is a near-term shortage, the price comparison breaks down and contango may be reduced or perhaps even be reversed altogether into a state called [[backwardation]]. In that state, near prices become higher than far (i.e., future) prices because consumers prefer to have the product sooner rather than later (see [[convenience yield]]), and\nbecause there are few holders who can make an [[arbitrage]] profit by selling the spot and buying back the future. A market that is steeply backwardated\u2014''i.e.'', one where there is a very steep premium for material available for immediate delivery\u2014often indicates a perception of a current ''shortage'' in the underlying commodity. By the same token, a market that is deeply in contango may indicate a perception of a current supply ''surplus'' in the commodity.\n\nIn 2005 and 2006 a perception of an impending supply shortage allowed traders to take advantages of the contango in the [[crude oil]] market. Traders simultaneously bought oil and sold futures forward. This led to large numbers of tankers loaded with oil sitting idle in ports acting as floating warehouses.<ref>{{cite web | last = Davidson| first = Adam| authorlink = Adam Davidson (journalist) | title = Analyst: Blame Investors for High Gas Prices| publisher = [[NPR News]] | date = August 24, 2006| url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5705263| accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref> (see: [[Oil-storage trade]]) It was estimated that perhaps a $10\u201320 per barrel premium was added to spot price of oil as a result of this.\n\nIf such was the case, the premium may have ended when global oil storage capacity became exhausted; the contango would have deepened as the lack of storage supply to soak up excess oil supply would have put further pressure on spot prices. However, as crude and gasoline prices continued to rise between 2007 and 2008 this practice became so contentious that in June 2008 the [[Commodity Futures Trading Commission]], the [[Federal Reserve]], and the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) decided to create task forces to investigate whether this took place.<ref>{{cite web | last = Mandaro| first = Laura| title = CFTC to probe energy speculation with Fed, SEC| publisher = The Wall Street Journal marketwatch.com| date = June 10, 2008| url = http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/cftc-probe-energy-speculation-fed/story.aspx?guid=%7B31AEE5F8-E83C-4719-B142-DAE42E0909F1%7D| accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref>\n\nA crude oil contango occurred again in January 2009, with arbitrageurs storing millions of barrels in tankers to profit from the contango (see [[oil-storage trade]]). But by the summer, that price curve had flattened considerably. The contango exhibited in crude oil in 2009 explained the discrepancy between the headline spot price increase (bottoming at $35 and topping $80 in the year) and the various tradeable instruments for crude oil (such as rolled contracts or longer-dated futures contracts) showing a much lower price increase.<ref>{{cite web | last = Liberty| first = Jez| authorlink = Jez liberty | title = Crude Oil, Contango and Roll Yield for Commodity Trading | url = http://www.automated-trading-system.com/crude-oil-contango-and-roll-yield-for-commodity-trading/ }}</ref> The [[United States Oil Fund|USO]] ETF also failed to replicate crude oil's spot price performance.\n\n== Interest rates ==\nIf short-term [[interest rates]] were expected to fall in a contango market, this would narrow the spread between a futures contract and an underlying asset in good supply. This is because the cost of carry will fall due to the lower interest rate, which in turn results in the difference between the price of the future and the underlying growing smaller (i.e. narrowing). An investor would be advised to buy the spread in these circumstances: this is a [[calendar spread]] trade where the trader buys the near-dated instrument and simultaneously sells the far-dated instrument (i.e. the future).<ref name=\"SII\">{{cite book|last=Morrissey |first=Bob |title=Derivatives: The Official Learning and Reference Manual |publisher=The Securities & Investment Institute |date=January 2009 |location=London, United Kingdom |pages=72\u201377 |url=http://www.sii.org.uk/ |isbn=978-1-906917-11-1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006153135/http://www.sii.org.uk/ |archivedate=October 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIf, on the other hand, the spread between a future traded on an underlying asset and the spot price of the underlying asset was set to widen, possibly due to a rise in short-term interest rates, then an investor would be advised to sell the spread (i.e. a [[calendar spread]] where the trader sells the near-dated instrument and simultaneously buys the future on the underlying).<ref name=\"SII\" />\n\n== 2007\u20132008 world food price crisis ==\nIn a 2010 article in ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', Frederick Kaufman argued the [[S&P GSCI|Goldman Sachs Commodity Index]] caused a [[demand shock]] in wheat and a contango market on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, contributing to the [[2007\u20132008 world food price crisis]].<ref>[http://www.harpers.org/archive/2010/07/0083022 The Food Bubble: How Wall Street Starved Millions and got away with it], by Frederick Kaufman, ''Harper's'', 2010 July</ref><ref>[http://www.pacificfreepress.com/news/1/6629-the-great-food-bubble-swindle-starving-the-multitudes-for-fun-and-profit.html Democracy Now (radio show)], Amy Goodman and Juan Gonzales, Interview with Frederick Kaufman, 2010 7 17</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pacificfreepress.com/news/1/6154-a-global-food-bubble.pdf |title=Global Food Bubble |date=6 May 2010 |publisher=Pacific Free Press |author=TRNN&nbsp;\u2014 Jayati Ghosh |accessdate=30 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn a June 2010 article in ''[[The Economist]]'', the argument is made that index-tracking funds (to which Goldman Sachs Commodity Index was linked) did not cause the bubble. It describes a report by the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] that used data from the [[Commodity Futures Trading Commission]] to make the case.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/research/articlesBySubject/displaystory.cfm?subjectid=2512631&story_id=16432870 Clearing the usual suspects], Buttonwood, ''The Economist'', 2010 6 24</ref>\n\n== Origin of term ==\nThe term originated in mid-19th century England<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/contango Contango] from [[Reference.com]]</ref> and is believed to be a corruption of \"continuation\", \"continue\"<ref>{{cite book| title=Significant Etymology (or Roots, Stems, and Branches of the English Language) | first=James | last=Mitchell | publisher=[[William Blackwood and Sons]]| year=1908 | page=[https://archive.org/details/significantetym00mitcgoog/page/n316 302] | quote=Contango, probably a corruption of continue, a Stock Exchange phrase, meaning a sum of money, or a percentage, paid for accommodating a buyer in carrying an engagement to pay money for speculative purchases of stock, over to next account day; contango day, the second day before settling day. | url= https://archive.org/details/significantetym00mitcgoog}}</ref> or \"contingent\". In the past on the [[London Stock Exchange]], contango was a fee paid by a buyer to a seller when the buyer wished to defer settlement of the trade they had agreed. The charge was based on the interest forgone by the seller not being paid.\n\nThe purpose was normally speculative. Settlement days were on a fixed schedule (such as fortnightly) and a speculative buyer did not have to take delivery and pay for stock until the following settlement day, and on that day could \"carry over\" their position to the next by paying the contango fee. This practice was common before 1930, but came to be used less and less, particularly after options were reintroduced in 1958. It was prevalent in some exchanges such as [[Bombay Stock Exchange]] (BSE) where it is still referred to as [[Badla (stock trading)|Badla]].<ref>[http://econpapers.repec.org/paper/iimiimawp/1253.htm] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427143332/http://econpapers.repec.org/paper/iimiimawp/1253.htm |date=April 27, 2010 }}</ref> Futures trading based on defined lot sizes and fixed settlement dates has taken over in BSE to replace the forward trade, which involved flexible contracts.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\nThis fee was similar in character to the present meaning of contango, ''i.e.'', future delivery costing more than immediate delivery, and the charge representing cost of carry to the holder.\n\nThe [[Commission of the European Communities]], in a report on agricultural commodity speculation, defined backwardation and contango in relation to spot prices: \"The futures price may be either higher or lower than the spot price. When the spot price is higher than the futures price, the market is said to be in backwardation. It is often called 'normal backwardation' as the futures buyer is rewarded for risk he takes off the producer. If the spot price is lower than the futures price, the market is in contango\".<ref name=\"CEC2008\" />\n\n== Economic theory ==\nEconomic theory regarding backwardation and contango is associated with [[John Maynard Keynes]] and [[John Hicks]].\n\nKeynes in ''[[A Treatise on Money]]''<ref name=keynes1930>{{cite book|last=Keynes|first=John M.|year=1930|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt/search?q1=backwardation;id=uc1.32106012042997;view=1up;seq=9;start=1;size=10;page=search;orient=0 |title=A Treatise on Money|volume=2|publisher=Macmillan|location=London}}</ref> assumed there are two types of participants in futures markets: speculators and hedgers. Keynes argued that if hedgers are net short, speculators must be net long. Speculators will not go net long unless the futures price is expected to rise. Keynes called the situation where the futures price is less than the expected spot price at delivery (and hence the futures price is expected to rise) normal backwardation.<ref name=Kolb2010>{{cite book|title=Financial Derivatives: Pricing and Risk Management|editor1=Robert Kolb|editor2=James A. Overdahl|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pV3aMRUKi10C&lpg=PR5&dq=Financial%20Derivatives%3A%20Pricing%20and%20Risk%20Management&pg=PR5#v=onepage&q=Financial%20Derivatives:%20Pricing%20and%20Risk%20Management&f=false|publisher=Wiley|year=2010|location=New Jersey|isbn=9780470541746}}</ref> Industrial hedgers' preference for long rather than short forward positions results in a situation of normal backwardation. Speculators fill the gap by taking profitable short positions, with the risk offset by higher current spot prices.<ref name=Bowden>{{cite web|title=Contango versus backwardation: disequilibrium states and the spot-forward balance in commodity markets|author1=Roger J. Bowden|author2=Peter N. Posch|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82028295.pdf}}</ref>\n\nHicks<ref name=Hicks1939>{{cite book|author=J. R. Hicks|title=Value and Capital|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.187380|year=1939}}</ref> \"reversed Keynes's theory by pointing out that there are situations where hedgers are net long. In this situation, called contango, speculators must be net short. Speculators will not go net short unless futures prices are expected to fall. When markets are in contango, futures prices are expected to decline.\" In 1972 Hicks won the [[Nobel Prize]] for economics on the basis of [[Value and Capital]], on the economic equilibrium theory, in particular the issue of the stability of equilibrium in an economic system exposed to external shocks.\n\nBouchouev argued that traditionally there was always more producer hedging than consumer hedging in oil markets. The oil market now attracts investor money which currently far exceeds the gap between producer and consumer. Contango used to be the 'normal' for the oil market. Since c. 2008-9, investors are hedging against \"inflation, US dollar weakness and possible geopolitical events,\" instead of investing in the front end of the oil market. Bouchouev applied the changes in investor behaviour to \"the classical Keynes-Hicks theory of normal backwardation, and the Kaldor-Working-Brennan [[theory of storage]], and looked at how calendar spread options (CSOs) became an increasingly popular risk management tool.\"<ref name=Bouchoueva2012>{{cite journal|journal=Quantitative Finance|volume=12|number=12|year=2012|series=Commodities|title=Inconvenience yield, or the theory of normal contango|doi=10.1080/14697688.2012.723463|author=Ilia Bouchouev|pages=1773\u20131777}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Backwardation]]\n* [[Oil-storage trade]]\n* [[Theory of storage]]\n* [[Commodity index fund]]\n\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.khanacademy.org/science/core-finance/derivative-securities/forward-futures-contracts/v/contango-and-backwardation-review|title=Contango and Backwardation Review|publisher=Khan Academy}} Review of the difference uses of the words contango, backwardation, contango theory and theory of normal backwardation.\n* <ref name=Kolb2010>{{cite book|title=Financial Derivatives: Pricing and Risk Management|editor1=Robert Kolb|editor2=James A. Overdahl|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pV3aMRUKi10C&lpg=PR5&dq=Financial%20Derivatives%3A%20Pricing%20and%20Risk%20Management&pg=PR5#v=onepage&q=Financial%20Derivatives:%20Pricing%20and%20Risk%20Management&f=false|publisher=Wiley|year=2010|location=New Jersey|isbn=9780470541746}}</ref>{{harv|Kolb|2010|363}}\n\n== References ==\n{{More footnotes|date=August 2009}}\n\n===Specific references===\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===General references===\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98410267 NPR ''All Things Considered'' story: Contango in Oil Markets Explained, 2008-12-17]\n* ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', [[1911 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|eleventh edition (1911)]] and fifteenth edition (1974), articles ''Contango and Backwardation'' and ''Stock Market''.\n\n<!-- *{{Wikisource1911Enc Citation|Contango and Backwardation}} -->\n<!-- *{{Wikisource1911Enc Citation|Stock Market}} -->\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Derivatives market}}\n\n[[Category:Derivatives (finance)]]\n[[Category:Arbitrage]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Contangobackwardation.png|thumb|upright=1.5|This graph depicts how the price of a single [[forward contract]] will typically behave through time in relation to the expected future price at any point in time. A futures contract in contango will normally decrease in value until it equals the spot price of the underlying at maturity.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} Note that this graph does not show the [[forward curve]] (which plots against maturities on the horizontal).]]\n\n'''Contango''', also sometimes called '''forwardation''', is a situation where the [[futures contract|futures price]] (or [[forward contract|forward price]]) of a commodity is higher than the [[spot price]] of the contract today.<ref name=OxfordDictEcon2008>{{cite dictionary|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780199237043.001.0001/acref-9780199237043-e-3523?rskey=KFzJUD&result=531|series=A Dictionary of Economics|edition=3|title=Contango|editor1=John Black|editor2=Nigar Hashimzade|editor3=Gareth Myles|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=2009|isbn=9780199237043}}</ref><ref name=\"investopedia_contango\">{{cite web|url=http://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/contango.asp |publisher=[[Investopedia]]|title=Contango|accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref> In a contango situation, arbitrageurs or speculators,<ref name=\"CEC2008\">{{cite report|url=http://ec.europa.eu/economy_finance/publications/publication13765_en.pdf|title=Is There a Speculative Bubble in Commodity Markets?|date=21 November 2008|publisher=Commission of the European Communities|location=Brussels|format=PDF|number=SEC(2008)2971|work=Task force on the role of speculation in agricultural commodities price movements}}</ref> are \"willing to pay more [now] for a commodity [to be received] at some point in the future than the actual expected price of the commodity [at that future point]. This may be due to people's desire to pay a premium to have the commodity in the future rather than paying the costs of storage and carry costs of buying the commodity today.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} On the other side of the trade, hedgers (commodity producers and commodity holders) are happy to sell futures contracts and accept the higher-than-expected returns. A contango market is also known as a normal market, or carrying-cost market.\n\nThe opposite market condition to contango is known as [[backwardation]]. \"A market is 'in backwardation' when the futures price is below the spot price for a particular commodity. This is favorable for investors who have long positions since they want the futures price to rise to the level of the current spot price\".<ref name=\"investopedia_contango\" />\n\nThe futures or [[forward curve]] would ''typically'' be upward sloping (i.e. \"normal\"), since contracts for further dates would typically trade at even higher prices. (The curves in question plot market prices for various contracts at different maturities \u2014 cf. [[term structure of interest rates]]) \"In broad terms, backwardation reflects the majority market view that spot prices will move down, and contango that they will move up. Both situations allow speculators (non-commercial traders)<ref>\"A non-commercial trader is a trader that is not commercially engaged in business activities hedged by the use of the futures or option markets (CFTC classification). The non-commercial classification does not include swap dealers and commodity index trading is generally considered as commercial\"</ref> to earn a profit.\".<ref name=\"CEC2008\" />\n\nA contango is normal for a non-perishable commodity that has a [[cost of carry]]. Such costs include [[warehousing]] fees and [[interest]] forgone on money tied up (or the time-value-of money, etc.), less income from [[leasing]] out the commodity if possible (''e.g.'' [[gold]]).<ref>{{cite web | first = Izabella | last = Kaminska | title = It's the BIS| url = http://ftalphaville.ft.com/blog/2010/07/08/281601/the-bis/ | work = [[FT Alphaville]] | date = 8 July 2010 | accessdate = 2010-09-01 }}</ref> For perishable commodities, price differences between near and far delivery are not a contango.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} Different delivery dates are in effect entirely different commodities in this case, since fresh [[Egg (food)|eggs]] today will not still be fresh in 6 months' time, 90-day [[Government bond|treasury bills]] will have matured, etc.\n\n== Description ==\nA normal [[forward curve]] depicting the prices of multiple contracts, all for the same good, but of different maturities, slopes upward. For example, a forward oil contract for twelve months in the future is selling for $100 today, while today's spot price is $75. The expected spot price twelve months in the future may actually still be $75. To purchase a contract at more than $75 supposes a loss (the \"loss\" would be $25 if the contract were purchased for $100) to the agent who \"bought forward\" as opposed to waiting a year to buy at the spot price when oil is actually needed. But even so, there is utility for the forward buyer in the deal. Experience tells major end users of commodities (such as gasoline refineries, or cereal companies that use great quantities of grain) that spot prices are unpredictable. Locking in a future price puts the purchaser \"first in line\" for delivery even though the contract will, as it matures, converge on the spot price as shown in the graph. In uncertain markets where end users must constantly have a certain input of a stock of goods, a combination of forward (future) and spot buying reduces uncertainty. An oil refiner might purchase 50% spot and 50% forward, getting an average price of $87.50 averaged for one barrel spot ($75) and the one barrel bought forward ($100). This strategy also results in unanticipated, or \"windfall\" profits: If the contract is purchased forward twelve months at $100 and the actual price is $150, the refiner will take delivery of one barrel of oil at $100 and the other at a spot price of $150, or $125 averaged for two barrels: a gain of $25 per barrel relative to spot prices.\n\nSellers like to \"sell forward\" because it locks in an income stream. Farmers are the classic example: by selling their crop forward when it is still in the ground they can lock in a price, and therefore an income, which helps them qualify, in the present, for credit.\n\nThe graph of the \"life of a single futures contract\" (as shown above on the right) will show it converging towards the spot price. The contango contract for future delivery, selling today, is at a price premium relative to buying the commodity today and taking delivery. The backwardation contract selling today is lower than the spot price, and its trajectory will take it upward to the spot price when the contract closes. Paper assets are no different: for example, an insurance company has a constant stream of income from premiums and a constant stream of payments for claims. Income must be invested in new assets and existing assets must be sold to pay off claims. By investing in the purchase and sale of some bonds \"forward\" in addition to buying spot, an insurance company can smooth out changes in its portfolio and anticipated income.\n\nThe Oil Storage contango was introduced to the market in early 1990 by the Swedish-based oil storage company Scandinavian Tank Storage AB and its founder [[Lars Jacobsson]] by using huge military storage installations to bring down the \"calculation\" cost of storage to create a contango situation out of a \"flat\" market.\n\nContango is a potential trap for unwary investors. [[Exchange-traded fund]]s (ETFs) provide an opportunity for small investors to participate in commodity futures markets, which is tempting in periods of low interest rates. Between 2005 and 2010 the number of futures-based commodity ETFs rose from 2 to 95, and total assets rose from $3.9 billion to nearly $98 billion in the same period.<ref name=\"cuitripped\">Carolyn Cui, \"Getting Tripped Up by the Contango: A futures-market quirk can hurt commodities returns\u2014if investors aren't aware of it,\" ''The Wall Street Journal'', 17 December 2010, pp. C5, C8.</ref> Because the normal course of a futures contract in a market in contango is to decline in price, a fund composed of such contracts buys the contracts at the high price (going forward) and closes them out later at the usually lower spot price. The money raised from the low priced, closed out contracts will not buy the same number of new contracts going forward. Funds can and have lost money even in fairly stable markets. There are strategies to mitigate this problem, including allowing the ETF to create a stock of precious metals for the purpose of allowing investors to speculate on fluctuations in its value. But storage costs will be quite variable, an example being that copper ingots require considerably more storage space, and thus carrying cost, than gold, and command lower prices in world markets: it is unclear how well a model that works for gold will work with other commodities.<ref name=\"cuitripped\" /> Industrial scale buyers of major commodities, particularly when compared to small retail investors, retain an advantage in futures markets. The raw material cost of the commodity is only one of many factors that influence their final costs and prices. Contango pricing strategies that catch small investors by surprise are more familiar to the managers of a large firm, who must decide whether to take delivery of a product today, at today's spot price, and store it themselves, or pay more for a forward contract, and let someone else do the storage for them.<ref>Tatyana Shumsky and Carolyn Cui, \"Trader Holds $3 Billion of Copper in London,\" ''The Wall Street Journal'', 21 December 2010, quoting a trader: \"'Holding ready-for-delivery metals on an exchange isn't a cheap undertaking for traders, who are responsible for paying insurance, storage and financing costs.\" And 'the end game is to find somebody to buy something you have already bought for a higher price,' Mr. Threkeld says. 'The recent boom in metal prices has enabled traders to purchase the physical metal, sell a futures contract at a much higher price and still make a profit after paying for storage and insurance.'\"</ref>\n\nThe contango should not exceed the cost of carry, because producers and consumers can compare the [[futures contract]] price against the spot price plus storage, and choose the better one. Arbitrageurs can sell one and buy the other for a theoretically risk-free profit (see [[Rational pricing#Futures|rational pricing\u2014futures]]). The EU describes the two groups of players in the commodity futures market, hedgers (commodity producers and commodity users) or arbitrageurs/speculators (non-commercial investors).<ref name=\"CEC2008\" />\n\nIf there is a near-term shortage, the price comparison breaks down and contango may be reduced or perhaps even be reversed altogether into a state called [[backwardation]]. In that state, near prices become higher than far (i.e., future) prices because consumers prefer to have the product sooner rather than later (see [[convenience yield]]), and\nbecause there are few holders who can make an [[arbitrage]] profit by selling the spot and buying back the future. A market that is steeply backwardated\u2014''i.e.'', one where there is a very steep premium for material available for immediate delivery\u2014often indicates a perception of a current ''shortage'' in the underlying commodity. By the same token, a market that is deeply in contango may indicate a perception of a current supply ''surplus'' in the commodity.\n\nIn 2005 and 2006 a perception of an impending supply shortage allowed traders to take advantages of the contango in the [[crude oil]] market. Traders simultaneously bought oil and sold futures forward. This led to large numbers of tankers loaded with oil sitting idle in ports acting as floating warehouses.<ref>{{cite web | last = Davidson| first = Adam| authorlink = Adam Davidson (journalist) | title = Analyst: Blame Investors for High Gas Prices| publisher = [[NPR News]] | date = August 24, 2006| url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5705263| accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref> (see: [[Oil-storage trade]]) It was estimated that perhaps a $10\u201320 per barrel premium was added to spot price of oil as a result of this.\n\nIf such was the case, the premium may have ended when global oil storage capacity became exhausted; the contango would have deepened as the lack of storage supply to soak up excess oil supply would have put further pressure on spot prices. However, as crude and gasoline prices continued to rise between 2007 and 2008 this practice became so contentious that in June 2008 the [[Commodity Futures Trading Commission]], the [[Federal Reserve]], and the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) decided to create task forces to investigate whether this took place.<ref>{{cite web | last = Mandaro| first = Laura| title = CFTC to probe energy speculation with Fed, SEC| publisher = The Wall Street Journal marketwatch.com| date = June 10, 2008| url = http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/cftc-probe-energy-speculation-fed/story.aspx?guid=%7B31AEE5F8-E83C-4719-B142-DAE42E0909F1%7D| accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref>\n\nA crude oil contango occurred again in January 2009, with arbitrageurs storing millions of barrels in tankers to profit from the contango (see [[oil-storage trade]]). But by the summer, that price curve had flattened considerably. The contango exhibited in crude oil in 2009 explained the discrepancy between the headline spot price increase (bottoming at $35 and topping $80 in the year) and the various tradeable instruments for crude oil (such as rolled contracts or longer-dated futures contracts) showing a much lower price increase.<ref>{{cite web | last = Liberty| first = Jez| authorlink = Jez liberty | title = Crude Oil, Contango and Roll Yield for Commodity Trading | url = http://www.automated-trading-system.com/crude-oil-contango-and-roll-yield-for-commodity-trading/ }}</ref> The [[United States Oil Fund|USO]] ETF also failed to replicate crude oil's spot price performance.\n\n== Interest rates ==\nIf short-term [[interest rates]] were expected to fall in a contango market, this would narrow the spread between a futures contract and an underlying asset in good supply. This is because the cost of carry will fall due to the lower interest rate, which in turn results in the difference between the price of the future and the underlying growing smaller (i.e. narrowing). An investor would be advised to buy the spread in these circumstances: this is a [[calendar spread]] trade where the trader buys the near-dated instrument and simultaneously sells the far-dated instrument (i.e. the future).<ref name=\"SII\">{{cite book|last=Morrissey |first=Bob |title=Derivatives: The Official Learning and Reference Manual |publisher=The Securities & Investment Institute |date=January 2009 |location=London, United Kingdom |pages=72\u201377 |url=http://www.sii.org.uk/ |isbn=978-1-906917-11-1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006153135/http://www.sii.org.uk/ |archivedate=October 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIf, on the other hand, the spread between a future traded on an underlying asset and the spot price of the underlying asset was set to widen, possibly due to a rise in short-term interest rates, then an investor would be advised to sell the spread (i.e. a [[calendar spread]] where the trader sells the near-dated instrument and simultaneously buys the future on the underlying).<ref name=\"SII\" />\n\n== 2007\u20132008 world food price crisis ==\nIn a 2010 article in ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', Frederick Kaufman argued the [[S&P GSCI|Goldman Sachs Commodity Index]] caused a [[demand shock]] in wheat and a contango market on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, contributing to the [[2007\u20132008 world food price crisis]].<ref>[http://www.harpers.org/archive/2010/07/0083022 The Food Bubble: How Wall Street Starved Millions and got away with it], by Frederick Kaufman, ''Harper's'', 2010 July</ref><ref>[http://www.pacificfreepress.com/news/1/6629-the-great-food-bubble-swindle-starving-the-multitudes-for-fun-and-profit.html Democracy Now (radio show)], Amy Goodman and Juan Gonzales, Interview with Frederick Kaufman, 2010 7 17</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pacificfreepress.com/news/1/6154-a-global-food-bubble.pdf |title=Global Food Bubble |date=6 May 2010 |publisher=Pacific Free Press |author=TRNN&nbsp;\u2014 Jayati Ghosh |accessdate=30 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn a June 2010 article in ''[[The Economist]]'', the argument is made that index-tracking funds (to which Goldman Sachs Commodity Index was linked) did not cause the bubble. It describes a report by the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] that used data from the [[Commodity Futures Trading Commission]] to make the case.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/research/articlesBySubject/displaystory.cfm?subjectid=2512631&story_id=16432870 Clearing the usual suspects], Buttonwood, ''The Economist'', 2010 6 24</ref>\n\n== Origin of term ==\nThe term originated in mid-19th century England<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/contango Contango] from [[Reference.com]]</ref> and is believed to be a corruption of \"continuation\", \"continue\"<ref>{{cite book| title=Significant Etymology (or Roots, Stems, and Branches of the English Language) | first=James | last=Mitchell | publisher=[[William Blackwood and Sons]]| year=1908 | page=[https://archive.org/details/significantetym00mitcgoog/page/n316 302] | quote=Contango, probably a corruption of continue, a Stock Exchange phrase, meaning a sum of money, or a percentage, paid for accommodating a buyer in carrying an engagement to pay money for speculative purchases of stock, over to next account day; contango day, the second day before settling day. | url= https://archive.org/details/significantetym00mitcgoog}}</ref> or \"contingent\". In the past on the [[London Stock Exchange]], contango was a fee paid by a buyer to a seller when the buyer wished to defer settlement of the trade they had agreed. The charge was based on the interest forgone by the seller not being paid.\n\nThe purpose was normally speculative. Settlement days were on a fixed schedule (such as fortnightly) and a speculative buyer did not have to take delivery and pay for stock until the following settlement day, and on that day could \"carry over\" their position to the next by paying the contango fee. This practice was common before 1930, but came to be used less and less, particularly after options were reintroduced in 1958. It was prevalent in some exchanges such as [[Bombay Stock Exchange]] (BSE) where it is still referred to as [[Badla (stock trading)|Badla]].<ref>[http://econpapers.repec.org/paper/iimiimawp/1253.htm] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427143332/http://econpapers.repec.org/paper/iimiimawp/1253.htm |date=April 27, 2010 }}</ref> Futures trading based on defined lot sizes and fixed settlement dates has taken over in BSE to replace the forward trade, which involved flexible contracts.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\nThis fee was similar in character to the present meaning of contango, ''i.e.'', future delivery costing more than immediate delivery, and the charge representing cost of carry to the holder.\n\nThe [[Commission of the European Communities]], in a report on agricultural commodity speculation, defined backwardation and contango in relation to spot prices: \"The futures price may be either higher or lower than the spot price. When the spot price is higher than the futures price, the market is said to be in backwardation. It is often called 'normal backwardation' as the futures buyer is rewarded for risk he takes off the producer. If the spot price is lower than the futures price, the market is in contango\".<ref name=\"CEC2008\" />\n\n== Economic theory ==\nEconomic theory regarding backwardation and contango is associated with [[John Maynard Keynes]] and [[John Hicks]].\n\nKeynes in ''[[A Treatise on Money]]''<ref name=keynes1930>{{cite book|last=Keynes|first=John M.|year=1930|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt/search?q1=backwardation;id=uc1.32106012042997;view=1up;seq=9;start=1;size=10;page=search;orient=0 |title=A Treatise on Money|volume=2|publisher=Macmillan|location=London}}</ref> assumed there are two types of participants in futures markets: speculators and hedgers. Keynes argued that if hedgers are net short, speculators must be net long. Speculators will not go net long unless the futures price is expected to rise. Keynes called the situation where the futures price is less than the expected spot price at delivery (and hence the futures price is expected to rise) normal backwardation.<ref name=Kolb2010>{{cite book|title=Financial Derivatives: Pricing and Risk Management|editor1=Robert Kolb|editor2=James A. Overdahl|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pV3aMRUKi10C&lpg=PR5&dq=Financial%20Derivatives%3A%20Pricing%20and%20Risk%20Management&pg=PR5#v=onepage&q=Financial%20Derivatives:%20Pricing%20and%20Risk%20Management&f=false|publisher=Wiley|year=2010|location=New Jersey|isbn=9780470541746}}</ref> Industrial hedgers' preference for long rather than short forward positions results in a situation of normal backwardation. Speculators fill the gap by taking profitable short positions, with the risk offset by higher current spot prices.<ref name=Bowden>{{cite web|title=Contango versus backwardation: disequilibrium states and the spot-forward balance in commodity markets|author1=Roger J. Bowden|author2=Peter N. Posch|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82028295.pdf}}</ref>\n\nHicks<ref name=Hicks1939>{{cite book|author=J. R. Hicks|title=Value and Capital|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.187380|year=1939}}</ref> \"reversed Keynes's theory by pointing out that there are situations where hedgers are net long. In this situation, called contango, speculators must be net short. Speculators will not go net short unless futures prices are expected to fall. When markets are in contango, futures prices are expected to decline.\" In 1972 Hicks won the [[Nobel Prize]] for economics on the basis of [[Value and Capital]], on the economic equilibrium theory, in particular the issue of the stability of equilibrium in an economic system exposed to external shocks.\n\nBouchouev argued that traditionally there was always more producer hedging than consumer hedging in oil markets. The oil market now attracts investor money which currently far exceeds the gap between producer and consumer. Contango used to be the 'normal' for the oil market. Since c. 2008-9, investors are hedging against \"inflation, US dollar weakness and possible geopolitical events,\" instead of investing in the front end of the oil market. Bouchouev applied the changes in investor behaviour to \"the classical Keynes-Hicks theory of normal backwardation, and the Kaldor-Working-Brennan [[theory of storage]], and looked at how calendar spread options (CSOs) became an increasingly popular risk management tool.\"<ref name=Bouchoueva2012>{{cite journal|journal=Quantitative Finance|volume=12|number=12|year=2012|series=Commodities|title=Inconvenience yield, or the theory of normal contango|doi=10.1080/14697688.2012.723463|author=Ilia Bouchouev|pages=1773\u20131777}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Backwardation]]\n* [[Oil-storage trade]]\n* [[Theory of storage]]\n* [[Commodity index fund]]\n\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.khanacademy.org/science/core-finance/derivative-securities/forward-futures-contracts/v/contango-and-backwardation-review|title=Contango and Backwardation Review|publisher=Khan Academy}} Review of the difference uses of the words contango, backwardation, contango theory and theory of normal backwardation.\n* <ref name=Kolb2010>{{cite book|title=Financial Derivatives: Pricing and Risk Management|editor1=Robert Kolb|editor2=James A. Overdahl|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pV3aMRUKi10C&lpg=PR5&dq=Financial%20Derivatives%3A%20Pricing%20and%20Risk%20Management&pg=PR5#v=onepage&q=Financial%20Derivatives:%20Pricing%20and%20Risk%20Management&f=false|publisher=Wiley|year=2010|location=New Jersey|isbn=9780470541746}}</ref>{{harv|Kolb|2010|363}}\n\n== References ==\n{{More footnotes|date=August 2009}}\n\n===Specific references===\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===General references===\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98410267 NPR ''All Things Considered'' story: Contango in Oil Markets Explained, 2008-12-17]\n* ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', [[1911 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|eleventh edition (1911)]] and fifteenth edition (1974), articles ''Contango and Backwardation'' and ''Stock Market''.\n\n<!-- *{{Wikisource1911Enc Citation|Contango and Backwardation}} -->\n<!-- *{{Wikisource1911Enc Citation|Stock Market}} -->\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Derivatives market}}\n\n[[Category:Derivatives (finance)]]\n[[Category:Arbitrage]]\n", "name_user": "The Gnome", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription:corrected wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contango"}
{"title_page": "2020 Malaysia movement control order", "text_new": "{{short description|Quarantine in Malaysia}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title           = 2020 Malaysia movement control order\n| image           = Ops Covid19 Tentera Mula Operasi Bantu Pdrm Di Shah Alam.png\n| caption         = Police checkpoint in [[Shah Alam]], 22 March 2020.\n| causes          = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia|COVID-19 pandemic in Malaysia]]\n| side3           =\n| side2           =\n| side1           =\n| result          = Restrictions towards [[Malaysians]] in Malaysia\n| status          = In force\n| methods         =\n* Prohibition of movement and mass assembly nationwide, including all religious, sports, social and cultural activities.\n* All religious activities in mosques suspended, including Friday prayers\n* Malaysians barred from leaving the country, and restrictions placed on the entry of non-Malaysians into the country\n* All industries closed except for infrastructure services and supermarkets, wet markets, grocery stores and multi-functional stores selling daily necessities\n* All nurseries, government and private schools, including boarding schools, international schools, tahfiz centres, primary, secondary and pre-university education institutions, public and private universities, and vocational training centres closed\n| leadfigures1    =\n| goals           = Containment of the pandemic\n| place           = [[Malaysia]]\n| date            = {{start date|2020|03|18|df=y}} \u2013 present ({{Age in years, months and days|2020|03|18|2020|04|28|sc=y}}; tentatively scheduled to expire {{end date|2020|04|28|df=y}})\n| partof          = the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia]]\n| leadfigures3    =\n| arrests         = 4,189\n| charged         = 1,449\n}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar}}\n\nThe '''2020 Malaysia movement control order''' ({{lang-ms|Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan Malaysia 2020}}), commonly referred to as the '''MCO''', is a ''[[cordon sanitaire]]'' implemented as a preventive measure by the [[Government of Malaysia|federal government]] of [[Malaysia]] in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia|COVID-19 pandemic in the country]] on 18 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/16/pm-malaysia-in-lockdown-from-wed-until-march-31-all-shops-closed-except-for/1847204|title=PM: Malaysia under movement control order from Wed until April 14, all shops closed except for essential services|last=Bunyan|first=John|work=The Malay Mail|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316160541/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/16/pm-malaysia-in-lockdown-from-wed-until-march-31-all-shops-closed-except-for/1847204|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The order was commonly referred to in local and international media as a \"lockdown\" or \"partial lockdown\".<ref>{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075456/coronavirus-malaysias-prime-minister-muhyiddin-yassin|title=Coronavirus: Malaysia in partial lockdown from March 18 to limit outbreak|last=Sukumaran|first=Tashny|work=South China Morning Post|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316155922/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075456/coronavirus-malaysias-prime-minister-muhyiddin-yassin|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/breaking-news-malaysia-lockdown-mulai-18-maret-1t2QRx3R6UV|title=BREAKING NEWS: Malaysia Lockdown Mulai 18 Maret|trans-title=BREAKING NEWS: Malaysia Lockdown Starting 18 March|last1=Muhammad Daryono|first1=Adhi|last2=Wahyu Nugroho|first2=Kelik|language=Indonesian|work=Kumparan|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318003851/https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/breaking-news-malaysia-lockdown-mulai-18-maret-1t2QRx3R6UV|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/malaysia-bans-mass-gatherings-shuts-businesses-69620354|title=Malaysia closes borders, shuts most businesses in lockdown|work=Associated Press|via=ABC News|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318010119/https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/malaysia-bans-mass-gatherings-shuts-businesses-69620354|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/17/malaysia-imposes-two-week-nationwide-lockdown/|title=Malaysia imposes two-week nationwide lockdown|last=Artida|first=Rodney|work=The Filipino Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318014412/https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/17/malaysia-imposes-two-week-nationwide-lockdown/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/5810e1345a44-refiling-update1-malaysia-pm-announces-nationwide-lockdown-border-closure.html|title=Malaysia PM announces nationwide lockdown, border closure|work=Kyodo News|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318100202/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/5810e1345a44-refiling-update1-malaysia-pm-announces-nationwide-lockdown-border-closure.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Malaysia blockade isolation measures ==\nAt 10:00PM ([[UTC+8]]) on 16 March, Prime Minister of Malaysia [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] made a televised speech and officially promulgated the restricted activities order under the Prevention and Control of Infectious Diseases Act 1988 and the Police Act 1967.<ref name=\"lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/malaysia-announces-restricted-movement-measure-after-spike-in-covid-19-cases|title=Malaysia announces movement control order after spike in Covid-19 cases (updated)|last=Tang|first=Ashley|work=The Star|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318000522/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/malaysia-announces-restricted-movement-measure-after-spike-in-covid-19-cases|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Details of Movement Control Order 18 March 2020 \u2013 28 April 2020\n! # !! Content\n|-\n|1|| General prohibition of mass movements and gatherings across the country including religious, sports, social and cultural activities. To enforce this prohibition, all houses of worship and business premises should be closed, except for supermarkets, public markets, grocery stores and convenience stores selling everyday necessities. Specifically for Muslims, the adjournment of all religious activities in mosques and mosques including [[Friday prayer]]s is in line with decision made on 15 March 2020 by the Special Muzakarah Committee Meeting of the National Fatwa Council.<ref name=\"MCO contents\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575177/covid-19-movement-control-order-imposed-only-essential-sectors-operating|title=Covid-19: Movement Control Order imposed with only essential sectors operating|work=New Straits Times|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316224520/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575177/covid-19-movement-control-order-imposed-only-essential-sectors-operating|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|2||Sanctions cover all [[Malaysians]] travelling abroad. For those who have just returned from overseas, they are required to undergo a health check and to do a quarantine (or self quarantine) for 14 days.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|-\n|3||Restrictions on the entry of all tourists and foreign visitors into the country.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|-\n|4||Closure of all kindergartens, government and private schools including daily schools, boarding schools, international schools, tahfiz centres and other primary, secondary and pre-university institutions.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|-\n|5||Closure of all public and private higher education institutions (IPTs) and skills training institutes nationwide.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|-\n|6||Closure of all government and private premises except those involved in essential services (water, electricity, energy, telecommunications, postal, transportation, irrigation, oil, gas, fuel, lubricants, broadcasting, finance, banking, health, pharmacy, fire, prison, port, airport, safety, defence, cleaning, retail and food supply.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|}\n\nEffective by 18 March, Malaysia officially implemented the movement control order measure. On 25 March, Prime Minister [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] through a live national telecast announced that the control order is extended till 14 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1824718|title=MCO period extended to April 14 - PM|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|agency=Bernama}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/25/pm-covid-19-shutdown-extended-to-april-14/1850034|title=PM: Covid-19 shutdown extended to April 14|last=Tee|first=Kenneth|date=25 March 2020|work=The Malay Mail|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326002545/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/25/pm-covid-19-shutdown-extended-to-april-14/1850034|archive-date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nThere have, however, been considerations of a further lockdown until late April or May as the number of cases in Malaysia is expected to peak in mid-April, according to the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-03/malaysia-braces-for-coronavirus-infections-to-peak-in-mid-april|title=Malaysia Braces for Coronavirus Infections to Peak in Mid-April|last=Ho|first=Yudith|work=Bloomberg|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/cases-in-malaysia-likely-to-peak-soon|title=Cases in Malaysia 'likely to peak soon'|work=Reuters|via=The Straits Times|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405171749/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/cases-in-malaysia-likely-to-peak-soon|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 April, Malaysia's Health Director-General, [[Noor Hisham Abdullah]] told that the health ministry was having a discussion with the nation's cabinet regarding the possible extension of the MCO, with the decision of the MCO's duration to be announced no later than Friday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/519563|title=KKM akan kemuka 'pilihan' bagi bantu PM putuskan tempoh PKP|trans-title=Health Ministry to suggest 'choices' to aid the Prime Minister to decide on MCO's duration|first=Annabelle|last=Lee|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020|website=Malaysiakini|language=ms}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1829673|title=MCO will be extended or not will be known in 72 hours|website=Bernama|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, the Prime Minister announced the further extension of the MCO by another 14 days till 28 April, noting that his decision was to give space to the healthcare personnels battling the COVID-19 outbreak, apart from preventing the virus from spreading again and to avoid an another increase of cases if the MCO is lifted too early.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1830577|title=MCO extended until April 28 - PM Muhyiddin|website=Bernama|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Royal Malaysia Police]] (PDRM) initially warned that violators of the MCO's regulation may be subjected to various penalties under the [[Penal Code (Malaysia)|Penal Code]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/sesiapa-yang-langgar-perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-boleh-ditahan-kpn-234031|title=Sesiapa yang langgar Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan boleh ditahan - KPN|trans-title=Anyone who violates the Movement Control Order can be arrested - KPN|last=Azman|first=Fareez|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> However, on 18 March, the chamber of the [[Attorney General of Malaysia|Attorney General]] released a federal gazette specific to the control order, where violations may receive a penalty of up to [[Malaysian ringgit|RM]]1,000 ([[United States dollar|US$]]229) and/or up to six months in prison for anyone disobeying the order.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-digazet-hukuman-6-bulan-penjara-tambahan-sektor-penting-234108|title=Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan digazet, hukuman 6 bulan penjara, tambahan sektor penting|trans-title=Movement Control Order gazetted: punishment of 6 months in prison, additions regarding important sectors|last=Ahmad|first=Azyyati|work=Astro Awani|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318070505/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-digazet-hukuman-6-bulan-penjara-tambahan-sektor-penting-234108|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 April, Senior Minister Datuk Seri [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]] stated that compounds will no longer be issued by the police from the next day as the penalties were ineffective on reducing MCO violations, and offenders will be arrested and remanded instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/584206/no-more-compounds-only-remand-mco-violators-tomorrow|title=No more compounds, only remand for MCO violators from tomorrow|first=Nuradzimmah|last=Daim|first2=Rahmat|last2=Khairulrijal|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020|website=New Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nWith the exception of travel to [[Sarawak]], a written police permit with a valid reason was originally planned to be required for interstate travel during the MCO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1822162|title=COVID-19: Public to inform police for interstates travel|agency=Bernama|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318001146/https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1822162|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, large crowds were reported to have gathered at police stations for permits hours before the travel restriction was in effect. Concerned that the crowding will exacerbate the spread of COVID-19, PDRM called off the permit plan a few hours before the MCO, until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chinapress.com.my/20200317/%e2%97%a4%e8%a1%8c%e5%8a%a8%e7%ae%a1%e5%88%b614%e5%a4%a9%e2%97%a2-%e7%ae%a1%e5%88%b6%e4%bb%a4%e5%89%8d%e9%a6%96%e4%b8%aau-turn-%e8%b6%8a%e5%b7%9e%e9%80%9a%e8%a1%8c%e8%af%81%e5%96%8a%e5%81%9c%ef%bc%81/|title=\u25e4\u884c\u52a8\u7ba1\u523614\u5929\u25e2 \u7ba1\u5236\u4ee4\u524d\u9996\u4e2aU Turn \u8d8a\u5dde\u901a\u884c\u8bc1\u558a\u505c\uff01|trans-title=\u25e4 14 days of operation control\u25e2 The first U Turn cross-country pass before the control order is stopped!|language=Chinese|work=China Press|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318001146/https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1822162|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the MCO, PDRM conducted road blocks operations (dubbed \"Ops COVID-19\") along key points across the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/556019/polis-selangor-lancar-ops-covid-19|title=Polis Selangor lancar Ops Covid-19|trans-title=Selangor police launched Operation COVID-19|last=Md Zain|first=Ruwaida|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406143930/https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/556019/polis-selangor-lancar-ops-covid-19|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> to monitor travellers and warn them to stay home and abide by the order.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=http://www.astroawani.com/video-malaysia/trafik-kl-tingkat-operasi-kawal-pergerakan-1839083|title=Trafik KL tingkat operasi kawal pergerakan|trans-title=KL Traffic Board increases movement control operations|medium=1:13|language=Malay|via=Astro Awani|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|format=video}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=http://www.astroawani.com/video-malaysia/sekatan-jalan-raya-di-sibu-berjalan-lancar-1839205|title=Sekatan jalan raya di Sibu berjalan lancar|trans-title=Road blocks in Sibu ongoing well|medium=1:31|language=Malay|via=Astro Awani|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|format=video}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/mco-compliance-improving-in-kota-kinabalu|title=MCO compliance improving in Kota Kinabalu|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321063551/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/mco-compliance-improving-in-kota-kinabalu|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> From 22 March, [[Malaysian Armed Forces|Malaysia's military forces]] were mobilised to augment PDRM's MCO operations; as of April, approximately 7,000 military personnel were deployed to assist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/movement-control-order-services-military-be-mobilised-effective-sunday-234473|title=Movement Control Order: Services of military to be mobilised effective from Sunday|work=Bernama|via=Astro Awani|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320070442/http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/movement-control-order-services-military-be-mobilised-effective-sunday-234473|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/maf-deploys-7-000-personnel-assist-second-phase-mco-237239?_ga=2.184630057.1017768555.1584265268-1977020655.1523006168|title=MAF deploys 7,000 personnel to assist second phase of MCO|last=|first=|date=7 April 2020|website=Astro Awani|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407141818/http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/maf-deploys-7-000-personnel-assist-second-phase-mco-237239?_ga=2.184630057.1017768555.1584265268-1977020655.1523006168|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, the national government designated that all businesses such as supermarkets and restaurants, including [[Food delivery|food delivery services]] can only be operated from 8AM till 8PM starting from 1 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1826628|title=MCO: New business hours 8 Am-8 Pm, starting April 1 - Ismail Sabri|agency=Bernama|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> Sarawak, however, insisted on its operation time of 7AM till 7PM, citing that Sarawak's daylight is earlier than in West Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/pkp-perniagaan-di-sarawak-beroperasi-7-pagi-hingga-7-malam-dr-sim-236143|title=PKP: Perniagaan di Sarawak beroperasi 7 pagi hingga 7 malam - Dr Sim|trans-title=MCO: Businesses in Sarawak to operate from 7AM to 7PM|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407030008/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/pkp-perniagaan-di-sarawak-beroperasi-7-pagi-hingga-7-malam-dr-sim-236143|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Further measures were instilled starting from 1 April; a person must not be accompanied with other people during travel, a 10&nbsp;km travel radius for all travellers and the banning of all types of gatherings except for funerals, however the attendees must be kept to a minimum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1827627|title=MCO: Travel now restricted to 10-km radius|agency=Bernama|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> People who travel for medical purposes are exempted from companion rule and the travel radius.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1828284|title=Those seeking medical treatments can travel beyond 10 km|agency=Bernama|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll levels of supply chains regarding [[Agriculture in Malaysia|agricultural]] and fishing industries are allowed to be in operation throughout the order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/581532/agricultural-fisheries-sector-operate-normally-during-mco?utm_source=nst&utm_campaign=recsys&utm_medium=recsys|title=Agricultural, fisheries sector to operate normally during MCO|first=Hana|last=Naz Harun|work=New Straits Times|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, the Malaysian government gave permissions to certain businesses to operate during the order to ensure the sustainability of the country's economy, to prevent the loss of jobs among Malaysians and to ensure a continuous access to basic needs and critical products.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/583210/certain-businesses-given-green-light-operate-during-mco|title=Certain businesses given green light to operate during MCO|first=Tharanya|last=Arumugam|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|website=New Straits Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Enhanced Movement Control Order ===\n[[File:Joint inspection by police and army in Malaysia during MCO.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Joint inspection by the police and army during the enhanced movement control order, 15 April 2020.]]\nFrom 27 March, specific locations were subjected to a stricter order, dubbed the \"Enhanced Movement Control Order\" (EMCO or Enhanced MCO), for 14 days if a large cluster was detected within the area in order for the government to conduct a thorough COVID-19 test towards all residents, and to curb the spread of the virus out of the areas. The orders included:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* all residents and visitors within the area are forbidden from exiting their homes during the order;\n* non-residents and visitors outside the area cannot enter into the area subjected to the order;\n* all businesses are shut down;\n* adequate food supplies will be given by the authorities during the 14 day-order to all residents;\n* a medical base will be established within the area;\n* all roads into the area are blocked.\n\nOn 27 March, two areas in [[Simpang Renggam]], Johor were subjected to the order till 9 April as those areas alone contributed to a high 61 positive cases.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-diperketatkan-dikuatkuasakan-di-dua-kawasan-di-simpang-renggam-235454|title=COVID-19: Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan Diperketatkan dikuatkuasakan di dua kawasan di Simpang Renggam|trans-title=COVID-19: Enhanced Movement Control Order enforced in two areas in Simpang Renggam|last=Saiful Sham|first=Nursyazwani|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 30 March, this order is applied to a few hamlets in Sungai Lui, [[Hulu Langat District]], [[Selangor]] due to a detection of a cluster involving a [[madrasa]] with 71 positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1826430|title=Batu 21-24 in Hulu Langat under enhanced MCO, starting midnight - Ismail Sabri|agency=Bernama|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> City One, a residential complex in Jalan Munshi Abdullah, Kuala Lumpur which its residents are mainly foreign workers was subjected to the extended order on 31 March as 17 cases involving residents of the tower were detected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1826783|title=Menara City One on Jalan Munshi Abdullah under lockdown|agency=Bernama|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> Selangor Mansion and Malayan Mansion, apartment buildings located at Jalan Masjid India, Kuala Lumpur, were subjected to EMCOs on 7 April, as 15 positive cases were detected within the two buildings,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/selangor-mansion-malayan-mansion-buildings-locked-down-under-emco-237178|title=Selangor Mansion, Malayan Mansion buildings locked down under EMCO|last=Abdullah|first=Rahimah|date=7 April 2020|website=Astro Awani|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407102128/http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/selangor-mansion-malayan-mansion-buildings-locked-down-under-emco-237178|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> while Jalan Masjid India and its surrounding areas were subjected to EMCOs on 14 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/covid-19-emco-hulu-langat-ends-today-jalan-masjid-india-now-under-enhanced-order-238319|title=COVID-19: EMCO in Hulu Langat ends today, Jalan Masjid India now under enhanced order|first=Firdaus|last=Azil|website=Astro Awani|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Similarly, an EMCO order was placed for over 15,000 residents living around the Kuala Lumpur Wholesale Market in [[Selayang]] on 20 April until 3 May, following the detection of 20 cases and one death from the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/586027/15000-selayang-residents-be-tested-covid-19|title=15,000 Selayang residents to be tested for Covid-19|first=Ahmad Suhael Adnan|last=|website=New Straits Times|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Malaysia's Defence Minister, Datuk Seri [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]], suggested that the government is planning for a new standard operation procedure regarding the EMCO and the government tried to not impose an excessively wide radius towards areas subjected to the EMCO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1829097|title=MOH preparing new SOP for EMCO - Ismail Sabri|agency=Bernama|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Measures by state ===\n==== Pahang ====\nFrom 21\u201331 March, the state of [[Pahang]] has enact that all business stores in [[Kuantan District|Kuantan]], [[Pekan District|Pekan]], [[Bentong District|Bentong]], [[Jerantut District|Jerantut]] and [[Temerloh District|Temerloh]] ([[Cameron Highlands District|Cameron Highlands]] had already begun to implement the measure on 16 March) must only operate during the day up to 12 hours, and need to close after 7PM to 7AM According to the measurement, all shops that were originally allowed to operate during the period of the control order, including drive-thru restaurants, fast food restaurants, and petrol stations, are no longer allowed to operate between 7PM and 7AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2237208.html|title=\u5305\u62ec\u6cb9\u7ad9\u996e\u98df\u5e97\u00b7\u5f6d6\u53bf7PM\u540e\u7981\u8425\u4e1a|trans-title=Including petrol station and restaurants \u00b7 Pahang is closed after 7PM|language=Chinese|work=Sinchew+|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> From 1 April, PDRM's state division tightened state borders and set up roadblocks on the state's major highways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1827089|title=MCO: Pahang police to further tighten state borders from midnight tonight|agency=Bernama|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Perak ====\nWholesale market operating hours in [[Perak]] during the MCO were designated from 4AM to 10AM, however, from 6 April, wet food-related businesses such as poultry and seafood were designated from 4AM to 10AM, while businesses for vegetables and fruits were designated from 11AM to 4PM. The closure from 10AM till 11PM was dedicated for cleaning processes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1828882|title=MCO: New operating hours for Perak wholesale markets from tomorrow|agency=Bernama|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Terengganu ====\nThe Royal Malaysia Police in Terengganu planned to impose traffic control based on vehicle registration numbers, where vehicles with odd or even registration numbers are only allowed to travel during odd- or even-numbered days, respectively, starting 1 April. The plan was later postponed the day before the rollout to allow a detailed study of the proposed control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1827258|title=Rule on odd and even vehicle registration number postponed - T'ganu police|agency=Bernama|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Effects ==\n=== Economy ===\nWith the country is known as the world's top [[rubber glove]] maker, concerns have risen especially from the [[European Union]] (EU) over the impacts of the movement control to Malaysia's glove exports especially with the increasing glove shortages among [[Healthcare in Europe|European healthcare sectors]].<ref name=\"global glove shortages\">{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/malaysia-loosens-lockdown-rules-meet-soaring-global-glove|title=Malaysia Loosens Lockdown Rules to Meet Soaring Global Glove Demand|last=Peter|first=Zsombor|work=Voice of America|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411013845/https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/malaysia-loosens-lockdown-rules-meet-soaring-global-glove|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This subsequently led the EU to sent a letter on 25 March to the Malaysian counterpart for the relaxation of the movement control order on the glove sectors. Through a positive replied made by the [[Ministry of International Trade and Industry (Malaysia)|Malaysian Ministry of International Trade and Industry]] to allowing continuous operations, a letter was subsequently distributed by the Malaysia Rubber Glove Manufacturers Association on 27 March to glove manufacturers in the country to allowing their factories to remain open from 1 April.<ref name=\"global glove shortages\"/> The [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] (CBP) also had removed a ban on glove exports to the [[United States]] by a Malaysian glove company previously accused of using [[forced labour]] as part of the American government efforts to boost supplies of their [[Healthcare in the United States|healthcare sectors]] due to the increasing shortages of medical equipments caused by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/us-lifts-ban-on-rubber-glove-imports-from-malaysian-company-amid-shortage/|title=US lifts ban on rubber glove imports from Malaysian company amid shortage|last=Feuerherd|first=Ben|work=New York Post|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411020618/https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/us-lifts-ban-on-rubber-glove-imports-from-malaysian-company-amid-shortage/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nThe Prime Minister had instructed the [[Ministry of Education (Malaysia)|Ministry of Education]] to implement home-based learning initiatives throughout the duration of MCO as schools nationwide were closed during the period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/583180/education-ministry-organise-home-based-learning-during-mco-nsttv|title=Education Ministry to organise home-based learning during MCO [NSTTV]|last1=Povera|first1=Adib|last2=Yunus|first2=Arfa|work=New Straits Times|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Assessments and examinations for various national higher education programmes were cancelled as some institutes were converted into temporary surveillance and quarantine centres, and students' performance evaluations were replaced by continuous assessment scores.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/578596/no-final-exams-polytechnic-community-college-students|title=No final exams for polytechnic, community college students|date=27 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|website=News Straits Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Essential supplies ===\n{{multiple image\n| footer = The usually crowded [[Tun Dr Lim Chong Eu Expressway|Lim Chong Eu Expressway]] and its surroundings ([[Queensbay Mall]]) in [[Penang]] deserted throughout the movement control order as seen on 22 March 2020.\n| align = right\n| caption_align = center\n| image1 = MCO covid19 Penang Malaysia (49687038551).jpg\n| width1 = 195\n| caption1 = \n| image2 = MCO covid19 Penang Malaysia (49686505698).jpg\n| width2 = 195\n| caption2 = \n| image3 = MCO covid19 Penang Malaysia (49687039581).jpg\n| width3 = 195\n| caption3 = \n| direction = \n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n}}\nBefore Malaysia announced the movement control order, [[supermarket]]s across the country began to see a surge in [[panic buying]], and the supply of [[surgical mask]]s everywhere was out, causing prices to skyrocket. In response, the Prime Minister of Malaysia said in a televised speech on the 16th assured that supply of food, daily essentials and healthcare (including surgical masks), were sufficient nationwide, adding that the [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs]] would be monitoring the [[food supply]] and the daily demand of the market during the period of its closure.<ref name=\"lockdown\"/>\n\n=== Transportation ===\n[[File:Pavilion Kuala Lumpur during Corona virus lockdown 2.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Square in front of the [[Pavilion Kuala Lumpur]] shopping mall on 20 March 2020 during the movement control order.]]\nScores of Malaysians working in [[Singapore]] and foreigners rushed back to the immigration checkpoints in the hope to return to Singapore before the order became effective. Singapore-based public transport operators had arranged temporary accommodation at several hotels to accommodate the affected Malaysian Bus Captains.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/malaysia-lockdown-some-singaporeans-seek-return-home-quickly-even-though-they-can-leave|title=Malaysia lockdown: Some Singaporeans seek to return home quickly, even though they can leave the country anytime|last1=Chandra|first1=Alif|last2=Meah|first2=Natasha|work=Today|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=http://archive.today/fvnnD|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/sbs-transit-secures-hotel-accommodation-for-malaysian-bus-drivers-scheduled|title=Sufficient accommodation for all Malaysian bus drivers, bus services to be slightly affected: Khaw|last=Ting Wei|first=Toh|work=The Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406013203/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/sbs-transit-secures-hotel-accommodation-for-malaysian-bus-drivers-scheduled|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Scheduled bus services travelling between Singapore and [[Johor Bahru]] were suspended as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businterchange.net/johorbus/news/377-suspension-of-singapore-johor-bahru-cross-border-bus-services-from-18-march-2020-to-31-march-2020|title=Suspension of Singapore-Johor Bahru Cross-border Bus Services From 18 March 2020 to 31 March 2020|work=Bus Interchange.net|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318002329/https://businterchange.net/johorbus/news/377-suspension-of-singapore-johor-bahru-cross-border-bus-services-from-18-march-2020-to-31-march-2020|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The announcement of the movement control order reportedly caused some anxiety among Singaporean residents over their food supplies, of which a significant portion came from Malaysia. [[Panic buying]] briefly returning in Singapore as Singaporeans rushed to supermarkets to stock basic necessities,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coconuts.co/singapore/news/panic-buying-returns-to-singapore-after-malaysia-announces-lockdown-new-church-cluster-emerges-map/|title=Panic Buying Returns to Singapore After Malaysia Announces Lockdown; New Church Cluster Emerges (Map)|date=17 March 2020|work=Coconuts Singapore|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318005616/https://coconuts.co/singapore/news/panic-buying-returns-to-singapore-after-malaysia-announces-lockdown-new-church-cluster-emerges-map/|archive-date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> and Singapore's ministers and Prime Minister had to assure them that there would be enough supplies for the country, and that the flow of goods between the two countries would continue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/malaysia-lockdown-bagaimana-stok-makanan-singapura-1t2dWsa9qL7|title=Malaysia Lockdown, Bagaimana Stok Makanan Singapura?|trans-title=Malaysia Lockdown, How's Singapore Food Stock?|last1=Pasya|first1=Haikal|last2=Armandhanu|first2=Denny|language=Indonesian|work=Kumparan|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318004437/https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/malaysia-lockdown-bagaimana-stok-makanan-singapura-1t2dWsa9qL7|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/spore-not-in-danger-of-running-out-of-food-or-supplies-chan|title=S'pore not in danger of running out of food or supplies: Chan|last1=Lai|first1=Linette|last2=Koh|first2=Fabian|work=The Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318004836/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/spore-not-in-danger-of-running-out-of-food-or-supplies-chan|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/coronavirus-flow-of-goods-and-cargo-between-singapore-and-malaysia-including-food-supplies|title=Flow of goods and food supplies between S\u2019pore and Malaysia will continue despite lockdown over coronavirus: PM Lee|last=Royston|first=Sim|work=The Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323070753/https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/coronavirus-flow-of-goods-and-cargo-between-singapore-and-malaysia-including-food-supplies|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Moments after the order was announced in Malaysia, With the announcement of the movement control, various diplomatic missions such as the [[United States]] and [[France]] have ceased issuing [[travel visa|visa]]s, while [[India]] has prohibited Malaysian citizens from travelling to its country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575487/embassies-cease-issuing-visas-bar-malaysians-curb-spread-covid-19|title=Embassies cease issuing visas; bar Malaysians to curb spread of Covid-19|work=New Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318010703/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575487/embassies-cease-issuing-visas-bar-malaysians-curb-spread-covid-19|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Thai residents began to heading out of Malaysia in large numbers while the [[Indonesians in Malaysia|large community of Indonesians]] in Malaysia also prepared for the situation as reported by their embassy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/555514/warga-thailand-berpusu-keluar-malaysia-metrotv|title=Warga Thailand berpusu keluar Malaysia [METROTV]|trans-title=Thai nationals head out of Malaysia [METROTV]|last=Abdul Rahman|first=Dziyaul Afnan|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgronline.com/south/detail/9630000026717|title=\u0e41\u0e23\u0e07\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\u0e40\u0e14\u0e34\u0e19\u0e17\u0e32\u0e07\u0e01\u0e25\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19 \u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e17\u0e32\u0e07\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e21\u0e32\u0e40\u0e25\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e28 14 \u0e27\u0e31\u0e19 \u0e2b\u0e27\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e42\u0e04\u0e27\u0e34\u0e14-19 \u0e25\u0e38\u0e01\u0e25\u0e32\u0e21|trans-title=Thai workers return home after the Malaysian authorities ordered to close the country for 14 days, the dreaded Covid-19 became aggressive|language=Thai|work=MGR Online|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318013028/https://mgronline.com/south/detail/9630000026717|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/17/indonesians-in-malaysia-remain-calm-as-they-prepare-for-lockdown.html|title=Indonesians in Malaysia remain calm as they prepare for lockdown|last=Pinandita|first=Apriza|work=The Jakarta Post|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318011200/https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/17/indonesians-in-malaysia-remain-calm-as-they-prepare-for-lockdown.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other diplomatic missions closely monitoring the situation of the restrictive movement and awaiting further instructions both from their government and Malaysia's government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575376/international-community-monitoring-malaysias-restrictive-movement-order|title=International community monitoring Malaysia's restrictive movement order|work=New Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318073822/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575376/international-community-monitoring-malaysias-restrictive-movement-order|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs the number of passengers decreases significantly during the movement control order and to reduce the risk of infection of passengers and employees, Malaysia's bus operator of [[Rapid Bus]] readjust the frequency of all its buses starting from 20 March where it also encourage the people to plan their trips in advance. [[Rapid Ferry]] also has made adjustments by reducing to two ferries each day to operate starting from 20 March. Each shift will be changed from the original 20 minutes to 30 minutes. After 10PM, the frequency of the ferry service will be changed to 1 hour. As for the last ferry ride time, it will depend on the arrival time of the last bus in Penang Sentral.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2236982.html|title=\u69df\u5a01\u6e21\u8f6e\u6682\u8c03\u6574\u670d\u52a1\u73ed\u6b21\u00b720\u65e5\u81f331\u65e5\u6bcf\u5929\u4ec52\u8258\u5ddd\u884c|trans-title=Penang Ferry temporarily adjusts service schedules \u00b7 Only 2 river cruises per day from 20th to 31st|language=Chinese|work=Sinchew+|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April 2020, all [[Express Rail Link]] rail services were to be suspended until the end of the control period due to significant reductions in passenger flow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/03/mco-erl-to-suspend-its-services-from-april-4|title=MCO: ERL to suspend its services from April 4|work=Bernama|via=The Star|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405100752/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/03/mco-erl-to-suspend-its-services-from-april-4|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April 2020, [[Minister of Defence (Malaysia)|Defence Minister]] [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]] clarified that any form of mass movements and interstate travel would be prohibited during [[Ramadan]] as long as the Movement Control Order remains in force until 28 April. Many Muslim Malaysians visit their families and hometowns during the Ramadan period.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mohsen |first1=Amar Shah |title=Ramadan \u201cbalik kampung\u201d not allowed under MCO |url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/ramadan-balik-kampung-not-allowed-under-mco-KY2265185#pk_campaign=MASwpn&pk_kwd=Ramadan+%E2%80%9Cbalik+kampung%E2%80%9D+not+allowed+under+MCO |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]] |date=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416083811/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/ramadan-balik-kampung-not-allowed-under-mco-KY2265185 |archivedate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrests and crime ===\nOn 2 April 2020, [[Minister of Defence (Malaysia)|Minister of Defence]] [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]] reported that 4,189 individuals had been arrested over the past two weeks for flouting the movement control order. Of these, 1,449 individuals have been charged in court.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/4100-arrested-so-far-under-mco-YF2205991|title=4,100 arrested so far under MCO|last=Mohsen|first=Amar Shah|work=The Sun|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405101240/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/4100-arrested-so-far-under-mco-YF2205991|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The MCO has led to a decrease in the national crime rate by around 70%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/578036/70-cent-drop-crime-rate|title=70 per cent drop in crime rate|last=Pei Ying|first=Teoh|work=New Straits Times|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407021931/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/578036/70-cent-drop-crime-rate|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Data from the [[Ministry of Women, Family and Community Development]] suggested a slight increase of [[domestic violence]] nationwide during the MCO, however in control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/exclusive/2020/04/581233/mco-linked-domestic-violence-rises|title=MCO-linked domestic violence rises|last=Arumugam|first=Tharanya|work=New Straits Times|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407021934/https://www.nst.com.my/news/exclusive/2020/04/581233/mco-linked-domestic-violence-rises|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[2020 Hubei lockdowns]]\n* [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown]]\n* [[2020 Indonesia large-scale social restrictions]]\n* [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown]]\n* [[2020 Philippine community quarantines]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.pmo.gov.my/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/FAQ-Perintah-Sekatan-Pergerakan-Bilangan-1_Kemaskini.docx.pdf|title=Soalan Lazim Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan 18\u201331 Mac 2020|trans-title=Frequently Asked Questions of Movement Control Order 18\u201331 March 2020|language=Malay|work=Country Safety Council|via=Prime Minister's Office of Malaysia|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318003027/https://www.pmo.gov.my/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/FAQ-Perintah-Sekatan-Pergerakan-Bilangan-1_Kemaskini.docx.pdf|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.pmo.gov.my/2020/03/perutusan-khas-yab-perdana-menteri-mengenai-covid-19-16-mac-2020/ The Prime Minister's Special Message on Covid-19 (16 March 2020)] (in English)\n* [https://www.pmo.gov.my/ms/2020/03/perutusan-khas-yab-perdana-menteri-mengenai-covid-19-16-mac-2020-2/ Perutusan Khas YAB Perdana Menteri Mengenai Covid-19 (16 Mac 2020)] (in Malay)\n\n{{Disasters in Malaysia}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Law|Malaysia|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Malaysia]]\n[[Category:2020 in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Country lockdowns|Malaysia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Quarantine in Malaysia}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title           = 2020 Malaysia movement control order\n| image           = Ops Covid19 Tentera Mula Operasi Bantu Pdrm Di Shah Alam.png\n| caption         = Police checkpoint in [[Shah Alam]], 22 March 2020.\n| causes          = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia|COVID-19 pandemic in Malaysia]]\n| side3           =\n| side2           =\n| side1           =\n| result          = Restrictions towards [[Malaysians]] in Malaysia\n| status          = In force\n| methods         =\n* Prohibition of movement and mass assembly nationwide, including all religious, sports, social and cultural activities.\n* All religious activities in mosques suspended, including Friday prayers\n* Malaysians barred from leaving the country, and restrictions placed on the entry of non-Malaysians into the country\n* All industries closed except for infrastructure services and supermarkets, wet markets, grocery stores and multi-functional stores selling daily necessities\n* All nurseries, government and private schools, including boarding schools, international schools, tahfiz centres, primary, secondary and pre-university education institutions, public and private universities, and vocational training centres closed\n| leadfigures1    =\n| goals           = Containment of the pandemic\n| place           = [[Malaysia]]\n| date            = {{start date|2020|03|18|df=y}} \u2013 present ({{Age in years, months and days|2020|03|18|2020|04|28|sc=y}}; tentatively scheduled to expire {{end date|2020|04|28|df=y}})\n| partof          = the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia]]\n| leadfigures3    =\n| arrests         = 4,189\n| charged         = 1,449\n}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar}}\n\nThe '''2020 Malaysia movement control order''' ({{lang-ms|Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan Malaysia 2020}}), commonly referred to as the '''MCO''', is a ''[[cordon sanitaire]]'' implemented as a preventive measure by the [[Government of Malaysia|federal government]] of [[Malaysia]] in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia|COVID-19 pandemic in the country]] on 18 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/16/pm-malaysia-in-lockdown-from-wed-until-march-31-all-shops-closed-except-for/1847204|title=PM: Malaysia under movement control order from Wed until April 14, all shops closed except for essential services|last=Bunyan|first=John|work=The Malay Mail|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316160541/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/16/pm-malaysia-in-lockdown-from-wed-until-march-31-all-shops-closed-except-for/1847204|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The order was commonly referred to in local and international media as a \"lockdown\" or \"partial lockdown\".<ref>{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075456/coronavirus-malaysias-prime-minister-muhyiddin-yassin|title=Coronavirus: Malaysia in partial lockdown from March 18 to limit outbreak|last=Sukumaran|first=Tashny|work=South China Morning Post|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316155922/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075456/coronavirus-malaysias-prime-minister-muhyiddin-yassin|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/breaking-news-malaysia-lockdown-mulai-18-maret-1t2QRx3R6UV|title=BREAKING NEWS: Malaysia Lockdown Mulai 18 Maret|trans-title=BREAKING NEWS: Malaysia Lockdown Starting 18 March|last1=Muhammad Daryono|first1=Adhi|last2=Wahyu Nugroho|first2=Kelik|language=Indonesian|work=Kumparan|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318003851/https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/breaking-news-malaysia-lockdown-mulai-18-maret-1t2QRx3R6UV|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/malaysia-bans-mass-gatherings-shuts-businesses-69620354|title=Malaysia closes borders, shuts most businesses in lockdown|work=Associated Press|via=ABC News|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318010119/https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/malaysia-bans-mass-gatherings-shuts-businesses-69620354|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/17/malaysia-imposes-two-week-nationwide-lockdown/|title=Malaysia imposes two-week nationwide lockdown|last=Artida|first=Rodney|work=The Filipino Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318014412/https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/17/malaysia-imposes-two-week-nationwide-lockdown/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/5810e1345a44-refiling-update1-malaysia-pm-announces-nationwide-lockdown-border-closure.html|title=Malaysia PM announces nationwide lockdown, border closure|work=Kyodo News|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318100202/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/5810e1345a44-refiling-update1-malaysia-pm-announces-nationwide-lockdown-border-closure.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Malaysia blockade isolation measures ==\nAt 10:00PM ([[UTC+8]]) on 16 March, Prime Minister of Malaysia [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] made a televised speech and officially promulgated the restricted activities order under the Prevention and Control of Infectious Diseases Act 1988 and the Police Act 1967.<ref name=\"lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/malaysia-announces-restricted-movement-measure-after-spike-in-covid-19-cases|title=Malaysia announces movement control order after spike in Covid-19 cases (updated)|last=Tang|first=Ashley|work=The Star|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318000522/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/malaysia-announces-restricted-movement-measure-after-spike-in-covid-19-cases|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Details of Movement Control Order 18 March 2020 \u2013 28 April 2020\n! # !! Content\n|-\n|1|| General prohibition of mass movements and gatherings across the country including religious, sports, social and cultural activities. To enforce this prohibition, all houses of worship and business premises should be closed, except for supermarkets, public markets, grocery stores and convenience stores selling everyday necessities. Specifically for Muslims, the adjournment of all religious activities in mosques and mosques including [[Friday prayer]]s is in line with decision made on 15 March 2020 by the Special Muzakarah Committee Meeting of the National Fatwa Council.<ref name=\"MCO contents\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575177/covid-19-movement-control-order-imposed-only-essential-sectors-operating|title=Covid-19: Movement Control Order imposed with only essential sectors operating|work=New Straits Times|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316224520/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575177/covid-19-movement-control-order-imposed-only-essential-sectors-operating|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|2||Sanctions cover all [[Malaysians]] travelling abroad. For those who have just returned from overseas, they are required to undergo a health check and to do a quarantine (or self quarantine) for 14 days.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|-\n|3||Restrictions on the entry of all tourists and foreign visitors into the country.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|-\n|4||Closure of all kindergartens, government and private schools including daily schools, boarding schools, international schools, tahfiz centres and other primary, secondary and pre-university institutions.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|-\n|5||Closure of all public and private higher education institutions (IPTs) and skills training institutes nationwide.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|-\n|6||Closure of all government and private premises except those involved in essential services (water, electricity, energy, telecommunications, postal, transportation, irrigation, oil, gas, fuel, lubricants, broadcasting, finance, banking, health, pharmacy, fire, prison, port, airport, safety, defence, cleaning, retail and food supply.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n|}\n\nEffective by 18 March, Malaysia officially implemented the movement control order measure. On 25 March, Prime Minister [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] through a live national telecast announced that the control order is extended till 14 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1824718|title=MCO period extended to April 14 - PM|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|agency=Bernama}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/25/pm-covid-19-shutdown-extended-to-april-14/1850034|title=PM: Covid-19 shutdown extended to April 14|last=Tee|first=Kenneth|date=25 March 2020|work=The Malay Mail|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326002545/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/25/pm-covid-19-shutdown-extended-to-april-14/1850034|archive-date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nThere have, however, been considerations of a further lockdown until late April or May as the number of cases in Malaysia is expected to peak in mid-April, according to the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-03/malaysia-braces-for-coronavirus-infections-to-peak-in-mid-april|title=Malaysia Braces for Coronavirus Infections to Peak in Mid-April|last=Ho|first=Yudith|work=Bloomberg|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/cases-in-malaysia-likely-to-peak-soon|title=Cases in Malaysia 'likely to peak soon'|work=Reuters|via=The Straits Times|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405171749/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/cases-in-malaysia-likely-to-peak-soon|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 April, Malaysia's Health Director-General, [[Noor Hisham Abdullah]] told that the health ministry was having a discussion with the nation's cabinet regarding the possible extension of the MCO, with the decision of the MCO's duration to be announced no later than Friday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/519563|title=KKM akan kemuka 'pilihan' bagi bantu PM putuskan tempoh PKP|trans-title=Health Ministry to suggest 'choices' to aid the Prime Minister to decide on MCO's duration|first=Annabelle|last=Lee|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020|website=Malaysiakini|language=ms}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1829673|title=MCO will be extended or not will be known in 72 hours|website=Bernama|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, the Prime Minister announced the further extension of the MCO by another 14 days till 28 April, noting that his decision was to give space to the healthcare personnels battling the COVID-19 outbreak, apart from preventing the virus from spreading again and to avoid an another increase of cases if the MCO is lifted too early.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1830577|title=MCO extended until April 28 - PM Muhyiddin|website=Bernama|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Royal Malaysia Police]] (PDRM) initially warned that violators of the MCO's regulation may be subjected to various penalties under the [[Penal Code (Malaysia)|Penal Code]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/sesiapa-yang-langgar-perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-boleh-ditahan-kpn-234031|title=Sesiapa yang langgar Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan boleh ditahan - KPN|trans-title=Anyone who violates the Movement Control Order can be arrested - KPN|last=Azman|first=Fareez|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> However, on 18 March, the chamber of the [[Attorney General of Malaysia|Attorney General]] released a federal gazette specific to the control order, where violations may receive a penalty of up to [[Malaysian ringgit|RM]]1,000 ([[United States dollar|US$]]229) and/or up to six months in prison for anyone disobeying the order.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-digazet-hukuman-6-bulan-penjara-tambahan-sektor-penting-234108|title=Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan digazet, hukuman 6 bulan penjara, tambahan sektor penting|trans-title=Movement Control Order gazetted: punishment of 6 months in prison, additions regarding important sectors|last=Ahmad|first=Azyyati|work=Astro Awani|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318070505/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-digazet-hukuman-6-bulan-penjara-tambahan-sektor-penting-234108|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 April, Senior Minister Datuk Seri [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]] stated that compounds will no longer be issued by the police from the next day as the penalties were ineffective on reducing MCO violations, and offenders will be arrested and remanded instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/584206/no-more-compounds-only-remand-mco-violators-tomorrow|title=No more compounds, only remand for MCO violators from tomorrow|first=Nuradzimmah|last=Daim|first2=Rahmat|last2=Khairulrijal|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020|website=New Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nWith the exception of travel to [[Sarawak]], a written police permit with a valid reason was originally planned to be required for interstate travel during the MCO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1822162|title=COVID-19: Public to inform police for interstates travel|agency=Bernama|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318001146/https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1822162|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, large crowds were reported to have gathered at police stations for permits hours before the travel restriction was in effect. Concerned that the crowding will exacerbate the spread of COVID-19, PDRM called off the permit plan a few hours before the MCO, until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chinapress.com.my/20200317/%e2%97%a4%e8%a1%8c%e5%8a%a8%e7%ae%a1%e5%88%b614%e5%a4%a9%e2%97%a2-%e7%ae%a1%e5%88%b6%e4%bb%a4%e5%89%8d%e9%a6%96%e4%b8%aau-turn-%e8%b6%8a%e5%b7%9e%e9%80%9a%e8%a1%8c%e8%af%81%e5%96%8a%e5%81%9c%ef%bc%81/|title=\u25e4\u884c\u52a8\u7ba1\u523614\u5929\u25e2 \u7ba1\u5236\u4ee4\u524d\u9996\u4e2aU Turn \u8d8a\u5dde\u901a\u884c\u8bc1\u558a\u505c\uff01|trans-title=\u25e4 14 days of operation control\u25e2 The first U Turn cross-country pass before the control order is stopped!|language=Chinese|work=China Press|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318001146/https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1822162|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the MCO, PDRM conducted road blocks operations (dubbed \"Ops COVID-19\") along key points across the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/556019/polis-selangor-lancar-ops-covid-19|title=Polis Selangor lancar Ops Covid-19|trans-title=Selangor police launched Operation COVID-19|last=Md Zain|first=Ruwaida|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406143930/https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/556019/polis-selangor-lancar-ops-covid-19|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> to monitor travellers and warn them to stay home and abide by the order.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=http://www.astroawani.com/video-malaysia/trafik-kl-tingkat-operasi-kawal-pergerakan-1839083|title=Trafik KL tingkat operasi kawal pergerakan|trans-title=KL Traffic Board increases movement control operations|medium=1:13|language=Malay|via=Astro Awani|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|format=video}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=http://www.astroawani.com/video-malaysia/sekatan-jalan-raya-di-sibu-berjalan-lancar-1839205|title=Sekatan jalan raya di Sibu berjalan lancar|trans-title=Road blocks in Sibu ongoing well|medium=1:31|language=Malay|via=Astro Awani|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|format=video}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/mco-compliance-improving-in-kota-kinabalu|title=MCO compliance improving in Kota Kinabalu|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321063551/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/mco-compliance-improving-in-kota-kinabalu|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> From 22 March, [[Malaysian Armed Forces|Malaysia's military forces]] were mobilised to augment PDRM's MCO operations; as of April, approximately 7,000 military personnel were deployed to assist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/movement-control-order-services-military-be-mobilised-effective-sunday-234473|title=Movement Control Order: Services of military to be mobilised effective from Sunday|work=Bernama|via=Astro Awani|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320070442/http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/movement-control-order-services-military-be-mobilised-effective-sunday-234473|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/maf-deploys-7-000-personnel-assist-second-phase-mco-237239?_ga=2.184630057.1017768555.1584265268-1977020655.1523006168|title=MAF deploys 7,000 personnel to assist second phase of MCO|last=|first=|date=7 April 2020|website=Astro Awani|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407141818/http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/maf-deploys-7-000-personnel-assist-second-phase-mco-237239?_ga=2.184630057.1017768555.1584265268-1977020655.1523006168|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, the national government designated that all businesses such as supermarkets and restaurants, including [[Food delivery|food delivery services]] can only be operated from 8AM till 8PM starting from 1 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1826628|title=MCO: New business hours 8 Am-8 Pm, starting April 1 - Ismail Sabri|agency=Bernama|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> Sarawak, however, insisted on its operation time of 7AM till 7PM, citing that Sarawak's daylight is earlier than in West Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/pkp-perniagaan-di-sarawak-beroperasi-7-pagi-hingga-7-malam-dr-sim-236143|title=PKP: Perniagaan di Sarawak beroperasi 7 pagi hingga 7 malam - Dr Sim|trans-title=MCO: Businesses in Sarawak to operate from 7AM to 7PM|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407030008/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/pkp-perniagaan-di-sarawak-beroperasi-7-pagi-hingga-7-malam-dr-sim-236143|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Further measures were instilled starting from 1 April; a person must not be accompanied with other people during travel, a 10&nbsp;km travel radius for all travellers and the banning of all types of gatherings except for funerals, however the attendees must be kept to a minimum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1827627|title=MCO: Travel now restricted to 10-km radius|agency=Bernama|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> People who travel for medical purposes are exempted from companion rule and the travel radius.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1828284|title=Those seeking medical treatments can travel beyond 10 km|agency=Bernama|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll levels of supply chains regarding [[Agriculture in Malaysia|agricultural]] and fishing industries are allowed to be in operation throughout the order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/581532/agricultural-fisheries-sector-operate-normally-during-mco?utm_source=nst&utm_campaign=recsys&utm_medium=recsys|title=Agricultural, fisheries sector to operate normally during MCO|first=Hana|last=Naz Harun|work=New Straits Times|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, the Malaysian government gave permissions to certain businesses to operate during the order to ensure the sustainability of the country's economy, to prevent the loss of jobs among Malaysians and to ensure a continuous access to basic needs and critical products.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/583210/certain-businesses-given-green-light-operate-during-mco|title=Certain businesses given green light to operate during MCO|first=Tharanya|last=Arumugam|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|website=New Straits Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Enhanced Movement Control Order ===\n[[File:Joint inspection by police and army in Malaysia during MCO.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Joint inspection by the police and army during the enhanced movement control order, 15 April 2020.]]\nFrom 27 March, specific locations were subjected to a stricter order, dubbed the \"Enhanced Movement Control Order\" (EMCO or Enhanced MCO), for 14 days if a large cluster was detected within the area in order for the government to conduct a thorough COVID-19 test towards all residents, and to curb the spread of the virus out of the areas. The orders included:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* all residents and visitors within the area are forbidden from exiting their homes during the order;\n* non-residents and visitors outside the area cannot enter into the area subjected to the order;\n* all businesses are shut down;\n* adequate food supplies will be given by the authorities during the 14 day-order to all residents;\n* a medical base will be established within the area;\n* all roads into the area are blocked.\n\nOn 27 March, two areas in [[Simpang Renggam]], Johor were subjected to the order till 9 April as those areas alone contributed to a high 61 positive cases.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-diperketatkan-dikuatkuasakan-di-dua-kawasan-di-simpang-renggam-235454|title=COVID-19: Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan Diperketatkan dikuatkuasakan di dua kawasan di Simpang Renggam|trans-title=COVID-19: Enhanced Movement Control Order enforced in two areas in Simpang Renggam|last=Saiful Sham|first=Nursyazwani|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 30 March, this order is applied to a few hamlets in Sungai Lui, [[Hulu Langat District]], [[Selangor]] due to a detection of a cluster involving a [[madrasa]] with 71 positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1826430|title=Batu 21-24 in Hulu Langat under enhanced MCO, starting midnight - Ismail Sabri|agency=Bernama|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> City One, a residential complex in Jalan Munshi Abdullah, Kuala Lumpur which its residents are mainly foreign workers was subjected to the extended order on 31 March as 17 cases involving residents of the tower were detected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1826783|title=Menara City One on Jalan Munshi Abdullah under lockdown|agency=Bernama|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> Selangor Mansion and Malayan Mansion, apartment buildings located at Jalan Masjid India, Kuala Lumpur, were subjected to EMCOs on 7 April, as 15 positive cases were detected within the two buildings,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/selangor-mansion-malayan-mansion-buildings-locked-down-under-emco-237178|title=Selangor Mansion, Malayan Mansion buildings locked down under EMCO|last=Abdullah|first=Rahimah|date=7 April 2020|website=Astro Awani|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407102128/http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/selangor-mansion-malayan-mansion-buildings-locked-down-under-emco-237178|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> while Jalan Masjid India and its surrounding areas were subjected to EMCOs on 14 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.astroawani.com/malaysia-news/covid-19-emco-hulu-langat-ends-today-jalan-masjid-india-now-under-enhanced-order-238319|title=COVID-19: EMCO in Hulu Langat ends today, Jalan Masjid India now under enhanced order|first=Firdaus|last=Azil|website=Astro Awani|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Similarly, an EMCO order was placed for over 15,000 residents living around the Kuala Lumpur Wholesale Market in [[Selayang]] on 20 April until 3 May, following the detection of 20 cases and one death from the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/586027/15000-selayang-residents-be-tested-covid-19|title=15,000 Selayang residents to be tested for Covid-19|first=Ahmad Suhael Adnan|last=|website=New Straits Times|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Malaysia's Defence Minister, Datuk Seri [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]], suggested that the government is planning for a new standard operation procedure regarding the EMCO and the government tried to not impose an excessively wide radius towards areas subjected to the EMCO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1829097|title=MOH preparing new SOP for EMCO - Ismail Sabri|agency=Bernama|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Measures by state ===\n==== Pahang ====\nFrom 21\u201331 March, the state of [[Pahang]] has enact that all business stores in [[Kuantan District|Kuantan]], [[Pekan District|Pekan]], [[Bentong District|Bentong]], [[Jerantut District|Jerantut]] and [[Temerloh District|Temerloh]] ([[Cameron Highlands District|Cameron Highlands]] had already begun to implement the measure on 16 March) must only operate during the day up to 12 hours, and need to close after 7PM to 7AM According to the measurement, all shops that were originally allowed to operate during the period of the control order, including drive-thru restaurants, fast food restaurants, and petrol stations, are no longer allowed to operate between 7PM and 7AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2237208.html|title=\u5305\u62ec\u6cb9\u7ad9\u996e\u98df\u5e97\u00b7\u5f6d6\u53bf7PM\u540e\u7981\u8425\u4e1a|trans-title=Including petrol station and restaurants \u00b7 Pahang is closed after 7PM|language=Chinese|work=Sinchew+|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> From 1 April, PDRM's state division tightened state borders and set up roadblocks on the state's major highways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1827089|title=MCO: Pahang police to further tighten state borders from midnight tonight|agency=Bernama|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Perak ====\nWholesale market operating hours in [[Perak]] during the MCO were designated from 4AM to 10AM, however, from 6 April, wet food-related businesses such as poultry and seafood were designated from 4AM to 10AM, while businesses for vegetables and fruits were designated from 11AM to 4PM. The closure from 10AM till 11PM was dedicated for cleaning processes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1828882|title=MCO: New operating hours for Perak wholesale markets from tomorrow|agency=Bernama|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Terengganu ====\nThe Royal Malaysia Police in Terengganu planned to impose traffic control based on vehicle registration numbers, where vehicles with odd or even registration numbers are only allowed to travel during odd- or even-numbered days, respectively, starting 1 April. The plan was later postponed the day before the rollout to allow a detailed study of the proposed control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1827258|title=Rule on odd and even vehicle registration number postponed - T'ganu police|agency=Bernama|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Effects ==\n=== Economy ===\nWith the country is known as the world's top [[rubber glove]] maker, concerns have risen especially from the [[European Union]] (EU) over the impacts of the movement control to Malaysia's glove exports especially with the increasing glove shortages among [[Healthcare in Europe|European healthcare sectors]].<ref name=\"global glove shortages\">{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/malaysia-loosens-lockdown-rules-meet-soaring-global-glove|title=Malaysia Loosens Lockdown Rules to Meet Soaring Global Glove Demand|last=Peter|first=Zsombor|work=Voice of America|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411013845/https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/malaysia-loosens-lockdown-rules-meet-soaring-global-glove|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This subsequently led the EU to sent a letter on 25 March to the Malaysian counterpart for the relaxation of the movement control order on the glove sectors. Through a positive replied made by the [[Ministry of International Trade and Industry (Malaysia)|Malaysian Ministry of International Trade and Industry]] to allowing continuous operations, a letter was subsequently distributed by the Malaysia Rubber Glove Manufacturers Association on 27 March to glove manufacturers in the country to allowing their factories to remain open from 1 April.<ref name=\"global glove shortages\"/> The [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] (CBP) also had removed a ban on glove exports to the [[United States]] by a Malaysian glove company previously accused of using [[forced labour]] as part of the American government efforts to boost supplies of their [[Healthcare in the United States|healthcare sectors]] due to the increasing shortages of medical equipments caused by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/us-lifts-ban-on-rubber-glove-imports-from-malaysian-company-amid-shortage/|title=US lifts ban on rubber glove imports from Malaysian company amid shortage|last=Feuerherd|first=Ben|work=New York Post|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411020618/https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/us-lifts-ban-on-rubber-glove-imports-from-malaysian-company-amid-shortage/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nThe Prime Minister had instructed the [[Ministry of Education (Malaysia)|Ministry of Education]] to implement home-based learning initiatives throughout the duration of MCO as schools nationwide were closed during the period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/583180/education-ministry-organise-home-based-learning-during-mco-nsttv|title=Education Ministry to organise home-based learning during MCO [NSTTV]|last1=Povera|first1=Adib|last2=Yunus|first2=Arfa|work=New Straits Times|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Assessments and examinations for various national higher education programmes were cancelled as some institutes were converted into temporary surveillance and quarantine centres, and students' performance evaluations were replaced by continuous assessment scores.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/578596/no-final-exams-polytechnic-community-college-students|title=No final exams for polytechnic, community college students|date=27 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|website=News Straits Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Essential supplies ===\n{{multiple image\n| footer = The usually crowded [[Tun Dr Lim Chong Eu Expressway|Lim Chong Eu Expressway]] and its surroundings ([[Queensbay Mall]]) in [[Penang]] deserted throughout the movement control order as seen on 22 March 2020.\n| align = right\n| caption_align = center\n| image1 = MCO covid19 Penang Malaysia (49687038551).jpg\n| width1 = 195\n| caption1 = \n| image2 = MCO covid19 Penang Malaysia (49686505698).jpg\n| width2 = 195\n| caption2 = \n| image3 = MCO covid19 Penang Malaysia (49687039581).jpg\n| width3 = 195\n| caption3 = \n| direction = \n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n}}\nBefore Malaysia announced the movement control order, [[supermarket]]s across the country began to see a surge in [[panic buying]], and the supply of [[surgical mask]]s everywhere was out, causing prices to skyrocket. In response, the Prime Minister of Malaysia said in a televised speech on the 16th assured that supply of food, daily essentials and healthcare (including surgical masks), were sufficient nationwide, adding that the [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs]] would be monitoring the [[food supply]] and the daily demand of the market during the period of its closure.<ref name=\"lockdown\"/>\n\n=== Transportation ===\n[[File:Pavilion Kuala Lumpur during Corona virus lockdown 2.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Square in front of the [[Pavilion Kuala Lumpur]] shopping mall on 20 March 2020 during the movement control order.]]\nScores of Malaysians working in [[Singapore]] and foreigners rushed back to the immigration checkpoints in the hope to return to Singapore before the order became effective. Singapore-based public transport operators had arranged temporary accommodation at several hotels to accommodate the affected Malaysian Bus Captains.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/malaysia-lockdown-some-singaporeans-seek-return-home-quickly-even-though-they-can-leave|title=Malaysia lockdown: Some Singaporeans seek to return home quickly, even though they can leave the country anytime|last1=Chandra|first1=Alif|last2=Meah|first2=Natasha|work=Today|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=http://archive.today/fvnnD|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/sbs-transit-secures-hotel-accommodation-for-malaysian-bus-drivers-scheduled|title=Sufficient accommodation for all Malaysian bus drivers, bus services to be slightly affected: Khaw|last=Ting Wei|first=Toh|work=The Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406013203/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/sbs-transit-secures-hotel-accommodation-for-malaysian-bus-drivers-scheduled|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Scheduled bus services travelling between Singapore and [[Johor Bahru]] were suspended as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businterchange.net/johorbus/news/377-suspension-of-singapore-johor-bahru-cross-border-bus-services-from-18-march-2020-to-31-march-2020|title=Suspension of Singapore-Johor Bahru Cross-border Bus Services From 18 March 2020 to 31 March 2020|work=Bus Interchange.net|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318002329/https://businterchange.net/johorbus/news/377-suspension-of-singapore-johor-bahru-cross-border-bus-services-from-18-march-2020-to-31-march-2020|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The announcement of the movement control order reportedly caused some anxiety among Singaporean residents over their food supplies, of which a significant portion came from Malaysia. [[Panic buying]] briefly returning in Singapore as Singaporeans rushed to supermarkets to stock basic necessities,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coconuts.co/singapore/news/panic-buying-returns-to-singapore-after-malaysia-announces-lockdown-new-church-cluster-emerges-map/|title=Panic Buying Returns to Singapore After Malaysia Announces Lockdown; New Church Cluster Emerges (Map)|date=17 March 2020|work=Coconuts Singapore|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318005616/https://coconuts.co/singapore/news/panic-buying-returns-to-singapore-after-malaysia-announces-lockdown-new-church-cluster-emerges-map/|archive-date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> and Singapore's ministers and Prime Minister had to assure them that there would be enough supplies for the country, and that the flow of goods between the two countries would continue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/malaysia-lockdown-bagaimana-stok-makanan-singapura-1t2dWsa9qL7|title=Malaysia Lockdown, Bagaimana Stok Makanan Singapura?|trans-title=Malaysia Lockdown, How's Singapore Food Stock?|last1=Pasya|first1=Haikal|last2=Armandhanu|first2=Denny|language=Indonesian|work=Kumparan|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318004437/https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/malaysia-lockdown-bagaimana-stok-makanan-singapura-1t2dWsa9qL7|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/spore-not-in-danger-of-running-out-of-food-or-supplies-chan|title=S'pore not in danger of running out of food or supplies: Chan|last1=Lai|first1=Linette|last2=Koh|first2=Fabian|work=The Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318004836/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/spore-not-in-danger-of-running-out-of-food-or-supplies-chan|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/coronavirus-flow-of-goods-and-cargo-between-singapore-and-malaysia-including-food-supplies|title=Flow of goods and food supplies between S\u2019pore and Malaysia will continue despite lockdown over coronavirus: PM Lee|last=Royston|first=Sim|work=The Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323070753/https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/coronavirus-flow-of-goods-and-cargo-between-singapore-and-malaysia-including-food-supplies|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Moments after the order was announced in Malaysia, With the announcement of the movement control, various diplomatic missions such as the [[United States]] and [[France]] have ceased issuing [[travel visa|visa]]s, while [[India]] has prohibited Malaysian citizens from travelling to its country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575487/embassies-cease-issuing-visas-bar-malaysians-curb-spread-covid-19|title=Embassies cease issuing visas; bar Malaysians to curb spread of Covid-19|work=New Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318010703/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575487/embassies-cease-issuing-visas-bar-malaysians-curb-spread-covid-19|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Thai residents began to heading out of Malaysia in large numbers while the [[Indonesians in Malaysia|large community of Indonesians]] in Malaysia also prepared for the situation as reported by their embassy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/555514/warga-thailand-berpusu-keluar-malaysia-metrotv|title=Warga Thailand berpusu keluar Malaysia [METROTV]|trans-title=Thai nationals head out of Malaysia [METROTV]|last=Abdul Rahman|first=Dziyaul Afnan|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgronline.com/south/detail/9630000026717|title=\u0e41\u0e23\u0e07\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\u0e40\u0e14\u0e34\u0e19\u0e17\u0e32\u0e07\u0e01\u0e25\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19 \u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e17\u0e32\u0e07\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e21\u0e32\u0e40\u0e25\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e28 14 \u0e27\u0e31\u0e19 \u0e2b\u0e27\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e42\u0e04\u0e27\u0e34\u0e14-19 \u0e25\u0e38\u0e01\u0e25\u0e32\u0e21|trans-title=Thai workers return home after the Malaysian authorities ordered to close the country for 14 days, the dreaded Covid-19 became aggressive|language=Thai|work=MGR Online|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318013028/https://mgronline.com/south/detail/9630000026717|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/17/indonesians-in-malaysia-remain-calm-as-they-prepare-for-lockdown.html|title=Indonesians in Malaysia remain calm as they prepare for lockdown|last=Pinandita|first=Apriza|work=The Jakarta Post|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318011200/https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/17/indonesians-in-malaysia-remain-calm-as-they-prepare-for-lockdown.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other diplomatic missions closely monitoring the situation of the restrictive movement and awaiting further instructions both from their government and Malaysia's government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575376/international-community-monitoring-malaysias-restrictive-movement-order|title=International community monitoring Malaysia's restrictive movement order|work=New Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318073822/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575376/international-community-monitoring-malaysias-restrictive-movement-order|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs the number of passengers decreases significantly during the movement control order and to reduce the risk of infection of passengers and employees, Malaysia's bus operator of [[Rapid Bus]] readjust the frequency of all its buses starting from 20 March where it also encourage the people to plan their trips in advance. [[Rapid Ferry]] also has made adjustments by reducing to two ferries each day to operate starting from 20 March. Each shift will be changed from the original 20 minutes to 30 minutes. After 10PM, the frequency of the ferry service will be changed to 1 hour. As for the last ferry ride time, it will depend on the arrival time of the last bus in Penang Sentral.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2236982.html|title=\u69df\u5a01\u6e21\u8f6e\u6682\u8c03\u6574\u670d\u52a1\u73ed\u6b21\u00b720\u65e5\u81f331\u65e5\u6bcf\u5929\u4ec52\u8258\u5ddd\u884c|trans-title=Penang Ferry temporarily adjusts service schedules \u00b7 Only 2 river cruises per day from 20th to 31st|language=Chinese|work=Sinchew+|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April 2020, all [[Express Rail Link]] rail services were to be suspended until the end of the control period due to significant reductions in passenger flow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/03/mco-erl-to-suspend-its-services-from-april-4|title=MCO: ERL to suspend its services from April 4|work=Bernama|via=The Star|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405100752/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/03/mco-erl-to-suspend-its-services-from-april-4|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April 2020, [[Minister of Defence (Malaysia)|Defence Minister]] [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]] clarified that any form of mass movements and interstate travel would be prohibited during [[Ramadan]] as long as the Movement Control Order remains in force until 28 April. Many Muslim Malaysians visit their families and hometowns during the Ramadan period.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mohsen |first1=Amar Shah |title=Ramadan \u201cbalik kampung\u201d not allowed under MCO |url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/ramadan-balik-kampung-not-allowed-under-mco-KY2265185#pk_campaign=MASwpn&pk_kwd=Ramadan+%E2%80%9Cbalik+kampung%E2%80%9D+not+allowed+under+MCO |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]] |date=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416083811/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/ramadan-balik-kampung-not-allowed-under-mco-KY2265185 |archivedate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrests and crime ===\nOn 2 April 2020, [[Minister of Defence (Malaysia)|Minister of Defence]] [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]] reported that 4,189 individuals had been arrested over the past two weeks for flouting the movement control order. Of these, 1,449 individuals have been charged in court.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/4100-arrested-so-far-under-mco-YF2205991|title=4,100 arrested so far under MCO|last=Mohsen|first=Amar Shah|work=The Sun|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405101240/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/4100-arrested-so-far-under-mco-YF2205991|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The MCO has led to a decrease in the national crime rate by around 70%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/578036/70-cent-drop-crime-rate|title=70 per cent drop in crime rate|last=Pei Ying|first=Teoh|work=New Straits Times|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407021931/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/578036/70-cent-drop-crime-rate|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Data from the [[Ministry of Women, Family and Community Development]] suggested a slight increase of [[domestic violence]] nationwide during the MCO, however in control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/exclusive/2020/04/581233/mco-linked-domestic-violence-rises|title=MCO-linked domestic violence rises|last=Arumugam|first=Tharanya|work=New Straits Times|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407021934/https://www.nst.com.my/news/exclusive/2020/04/581233/mco-linked-domestic-violence-rises|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[2020 Hubei lockdowns]]\n* [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown]]\n* [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown]]\n* [[2020 Philippine community quarantines]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.pmo.gov.my/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/FAQ-Perintah-Sekatan-Pergerakan-Bilangan-1_Kemaskini.docx.pdf|title=Soalan Lazim Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan 18\u201331 Mac 2020|trans-title=Frequently Asked Questions of Movement Control Order 18\u201331 March 2020|language=Malay|work=Country Safety Council|via=Prime Minister's Office of Malaysia|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318003027/https://www.pmo.gov.my/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/FAQ-Perintah-Sekatan-Pergerakan-Bilangan-1_Kemaskini.docx.pdf|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.pmo.gov.my/2020/03/perutusan-khas-yab-perdana-menteri-mengenai-covid-19-16-mac-2020/ The Prime Minister's Special Message on Covid-19 (16 March 2020)] (in English)\n* [https://www.pmo.gov.my/ms/2020/03/perutusan-khas-yab-perdana-menteri-mengenai-covid-19-16-mac-2020-2/ Perutusan Khas YAB Perdana Menteri Mengenai Covid-19 (16 Mac 2020)] (in Malay)\n\n{{Disasters in Malaysia}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Law|Malaysia|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Malaysia]]\n[[Category:2020 in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Country lockdowns|Malaysia]]\n", "name_user": "BellaYunita", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Malaysia_movement_control_order"}
{"title_page": "Machon Lev", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Jerusalem_College_of_Technology#Branches]] {{R from alternate language|und|und}}\n[[Category:Jerusalem College of Technology]]\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Jerusalem College of Technology]] {{R from alternate language|und|und}}\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2190Changed redirect target fromJerusalem College of TechnologytoJerusalem College of Technology#Branches", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Machon_Lev&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Gospel Oak, Polstead", "text_new": "The '''Gospel Oak''' in [[Polstead]], Suffolk was a [[veteran tree|veteran oak tree]].  The tree is associated with [[Saint Cedd]], who reputedly planted it or preached beneath it.  The tree is thought to have been named for its association with an annual church service, reputedly held beneath it for more than a millennium.  The tree is said to have been the oldest in the county when it collapsed in November 1953.  A descendant grows nearby and has since been used as the site for the annual service.\n\n== Association with Saint Cedd ==\nThe tree is associated with [[Saint Cedd]] (died 664 AD), an East Anglian from the [[Lindisfarne]] monastery who preached the gospel in East Anglia, Mercia and Northumbria.<ref name=cedd>{{cite book |last1=Darch |first1=John H. |title=Common Worship: Saints on Earth: A Biographical Companion to Common Worship |date=2014 |publisher=Canterbury Press |isbn=978-0-7151-4338-4 |page=281 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5WemDwAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref>  The Gospel Oak is thought to date from around this time and legend holds that Cedd and his monks preached from beneath the tree in the years before the village's St Mary's Church was built.<ref name=halliday/>  Other legends state that the tree was planted by Cedd or one of his followers.<ref name=mitchell/>  The tree is one of two associated with Cedd, the other is the \"Great Oak\" at [[Great Yeldham]], Essex - which lay within Cedd's diocese as bishop of the East Saxons.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Blythe |first1=Ronald |title=Divine landscapes |date=1986 |publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich |page=41 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gB0gAQAAIAAJ |language=en}}</ref><ref name=cedd/>\n\nIt has been claimed that the Gospel Oak has been the venue for an annual service for more than a millennium.<ref name=book>{{cite book|first=Julian|last=Hight|title=Britain's Tree Story|location=London|publisher=National Trust|year=2011|isbn=978-1-907892-20-2|page=49}}</ref>  It is thought that this ceremony is a survival of the [[Rogation days|Rogationtide]] tradition of [[beating the bounds]] in which a procession, led by the parish priest, would mark the extent of the parish lands, and ask god for good weather and a bountiful harvest.  Such processions often paused under an ancient tree in the parish where the priest would read a sermon from the gospels.  As a result these trees became known as \"gospel trees\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Evans |first1=George Ewart |title=The Pattern Under the Plough |date=2012 |publisher=Faber & Faber |isbn=978-0-571-28687-4 |page=84 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NEZj1cwXzwcC |language=en}}</ref>  It is known that an annual service has been held at the tree in the first week of August since 3 August 1902 when it was held by the Reverend Francis John Eld.<ref name=halliday/>\n\n== Later history ==\nThe tree was described as the oldest in England in 1903, though this is unlikely given the [[List of oldest trees|ages of other known trees]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Copinger |first1=Walter Arthur|authorlink=Walter Arthur Copinger |last2=Copinger |first2=Harold Bernard |title=The Manors of Suffolk: The hundreds of Babergh and Blackbourn |date=1905 |publisher=T. F. Unwin |page=181 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6TtOAAAAYAAJ |language=en}}</ref>  It is, however, thought to have been the oldest tree in Suffolk at around 1,300 years old.<ref name=mitchell>{{cite book |last1=Mitchell |first1=Laurence |title=Slow Norfolk and Suffolk |date=2010 |publisher=Bradt Travel Guides |isbn=978-1-84162-321-4 |page=223 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=reDUVsxLKNwC |language=en}}</ref>  It was later incorporated into the grounds of [[Polstead Hall]], visible from the churchyard, and by 1900 stood at {{convert|36|ft|m}} in circumference.<ref name=halliday>{{cite book |last1=Halliday |first1=Robert |title=Suffolk Strange But True: Strange But True |date=2008 |publisher=History Press |isbn=978-0-7509-5333-7 |page=53 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7_s6AwAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref>  It collapsed in November 1953 and, as of 2010, its remains were visible near to the village war memorial.<ref name=halliday/><ref name=mitchell/>\n\nA naturally seeded sapling from the tree grows nearby and has been used as the venue for the annual service since the loss of the original tree.<ref name=halliday/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Individual oak trees]]\n[[Category:Individual trees in England]]\n[[Category:Polstead]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Gospel Oak''' in [[Polstead]], Suffolk was a [[veteran tree|veteran oak tree]].  The tree is associated with [[Saint Cedd]], who reputedly planted it or preached beneath it.  The tree is thought to have been named for its association with an annual church service, reputedly held beneath it for more than a millennium.  The tree is said to have been the oldest in the county when it collapsed in November 1953.  A descendant grows nearby and has since been used as the site for the annual service.\n\n== Association with Saint Cedd ==\nThe tree is associated with [[Saint Cedd]] (died 664 AD), an East Anglian from the [[Lindisfarne]] monastery who preached the gospel in East Anglia, Mercia and Northumbria.<ref name=cedd>{{cite book |last1=Darch |first1=John H. |title=Common Worship: Saints on Earth: A Biographical Companion to Common Worship |date=2014 |publisher=Canterbury Press |isbn=978-0-7151-4338-4 |page=281 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5WemDwAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref>  The Gospel Oak is thought to date from around this time and legend holds that Cedd and his monks preached from beneath the tree in the years before the village's St Mary's Church was built.<ref name=halliday/>  Other legends state that the tree was planted by Cedd or one of his followers.<ref name=mitchell/>  The tree is one of two associated with Cedd, the other is the \"Great Oak\" at [[Great Yeldham]], Essex - which lay within Cedd's diocese as bishop of the East Saxons.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Blythe |first1=Ronald |title=Divine landscapes |date=1986 |publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich |page=41 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gB0gAQAAIAAJ |language=en}}</ref><ref name=cedd/>\n\nIt has been claimed that the Gospel Oak has been the venue for an annual service for more than a millennium.<ref name=book>{{cite book|first=Julian|last=Hight|title=Britain's Tree Story|location=London|publisher=National Trust|year=2011|isbn=978-1-907892-20-2|page=49}}</ref>  It is thought that this ceremony is a survival of the [[Rogation days|Rogationtide]] tradition of [[beating the bounds]] in which a procession, led by the parish priest, would mark the extent of the parish lands, and ask god for good weather and a bountiful harvest.  Such processions often paused under an ancient tree in the parish where the priest would read a sermon from the gospels.  As a result these trees became known as \"gospel trees\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Evans |first1=George Ewart |title=The Pattern Under the Plough |date=2012 |publisher=Faber & Faber |isbn=978-0-571-28687-4 |page=84 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NEZj1cwXzwcC |language=en}}</ref>  It is known that an annual service has been held at the tree in the first week of August since 3 August 1902 when it was held by the Reverend Francis John Eld.<ref name=halliday/>\n\n== Later history ==\nThe tree was described as the oldest in England in 1903, though this is unlikely given the [[List of oldest trees|ages of other known trees]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Copinger |first1=Walter Arthur|authorlink=Walter Arthur Copinger |last2=Copinger |first2=Harold Bernard |title=The Manors of Suffolk: The hundreds of Babergh and Blackbourn |date=1905 |publisher=T. F. Unwin |page=181 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6TtOAAAAYAAJ |language=en}}</ref>  It is, however, thought to have been the oldest tree in Suffolk at around 1,300 years old.<ref name=mitchell>{{cite book |last1=Mitchell |first1=Laurence |title=Slow Norfolk and Suffolk |date=2010 |publisher=Bradt Travel Guides |isbn=978-1-84162-321-4 |page=223 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=reDUVsxLKNwC |language=en}}</ref>  It was later incorporated into the grounds of [[Polstead Hall]], visible from the churchyard, and by 1900 stood at {{convert|36|ft|m}} in circumference.<ref name=halliday>{{cite book |last1=Halliday |first1=Robert |title=Suffolk Strange But True: Strange But True |date=2008 |publisher=History Press |isbn=978-0-7509-5333-7 |page=53 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7_s6AwAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref>  It collapsed in November 1953 and, as of 2010, its remains were visible near to the village war memorial.<ref name=halliday/><ref name=mitchell/>\n\nA naturally seeded sapling from the tree grows nearby and has been used as the venue for the annual service since the loss of the original tree.<ref name=halliday/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Individual oak trees]]\n[[Category:Individual trees in England]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Category:Polstead", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gospel_Oak,_Polstead"}
{"title_page": "Occupational burnout", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Occupational burning}}\n{{short description|Type of psychological stress}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Occupational burn-out\n| synonyms        = Burn-out\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n| image           = File:Headache-1557872 960 720.jpg\n| image_size      = 300px\n| caption         = A person who is experiencing [[psychological stress]]\n}}\n\nAccording to the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO), '''occupational burnout''' is a [[syndrome]] resulting from chronic [[Occupational stress|work-related stress]], with symptoms characterized by \"feelings of energy depletion or exhaustion; increased mental distance from one\u2019s job, or feelings of negativism or cynicism related to one's job; and reduced professional efficacy.\"<ref name=\"WHO-2019\" /> While burnout influences [[health]] and may be a reason for people contacting [[health service]]s, it is not itself classified by the WHO as a [[medical condition]].<ref name=\"WHO-2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mental_health/evidence/burn-out/en/|title=Burn-out an \"occupational phenomenon\": International Classification of Diseases|website=WHO|date=28 May 2019|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, [[Herbert Freudenberger]] became the first researcher to publish in a psychology-related journal a paper that used the term \"burnout.\" The paper was based on his observations of the volunteer staff (including himself) at a free clinic for drug addicts.<ref name=\"staffburnout1\">{{cite journal|author=Freudenberger, H.J.|year=1974|title=Staff burnout|journal=Journal of Social Issues|volume= 30|pages=159\u2013165|doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1974.tb00706.x}}</ref> He characterized burnout by a set of symptoms that includes exhaustion resulting from work's excessive demands as well as physical symptoms such as headaches and sleeplessness, \"quickness to anger,\" and closed thinking. He observed that the burned-out worker \"looks, acts, and seems depressed.\" After the publication of Freudenberger's original paper, interest in occupational burnout grew. Because the phrase \"burnt-out\" was part of the title of a 1961 [[Graham Greene]] novel ''[[A Burnt-Out Case]]'', which dealt with a doctor working in the Belgian Congo with patients who had leprosy, the phrase may have been in use outside the psychology literature before Freudenberger employed it.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Burnt-Out Case|last=Greene|first=Graham|publisher=William Heinemann Ltd|year=1961|isbn=978-0140185393|pages=cover title}}</ref> (Wolfgang Kaskcha has written on the early documentation of the subject).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kaschka |first1=Wolfgang P |title=Burnout: A Fashionable Diagnosis |journal=Deutsch Arzteblatt International |date=Nov 2011 |volume=108 |issue=46 |pages=781\u2013787 |doi=10.3238/arztebl.2011.0781 |pmid=22163259 |pmc=3230825 }}</ref>\n\n[[Christina Maslach]] described burnout in terms of emotional exhaustion, depersonalization (treating clients/students and colleagues in a cynical way), and reduced feelings of work-related personal accomplishment.<ref name=\"Maslach\">{{cite web|author1=Maslach, C.|author2=Jackson, S.E|author3=Leiter, M.P.|year=1996|title=MBI: The Maslach Burnout Inventory: Manual|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/277816643|journal=|location=Palo Alto|publisher=Consulting Psychologists Press|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite journal|last1=Ruotsalainen|first1=JH|last2=Verbeek|first2=JH|last3=Marin\u00e9|first3=A|last4=Serra|first4=C|title=Preventing occupational stress in healthcare workers.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=7 April 2015|issue=4|pages=CD002892|pmid=25847433|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD002892.pub5|pmc=6718215}}</ref> In 1981, Maslach and Susan Jackson published the first widely used instrument for assessing burnout, the [[Maslach Burnout Inventory]].<ref name = \"Maslach2\"/> Originally focused on the human service professions (e.g., teachers, social workers),<ref name = \"Maslach2\"/> its application broadened to many other occupations.<ref name = \"Maslach\"/> The WHO adopted a conceptualization of burnout that is consistent with Maslach's.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n\n=== Classification ===\nBurnout is not recognized as a distinct disorder in the current revision (dating from 2013) of the [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]] (DSM-5).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vahia|first=Vihang N.|title=Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders 5: A quick glance|journal=Indian Journal of Psychiatry|volume=55|issue=3|pages=220\u2013223|doi=10.4103/0019-5545.117131|issn=0019-5545|pmc=3777342|pmid=24082241|year=2013}}</ref> It's definitions for [[Adjustment disorder|Adjustment Disorders]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Boudoukha |first1=A.H. |last2=Hautekeete |first2=M. |last3=Abdelaoui |first3=S. |last4=Groux |first4=W. |last5=Garay |first5=D. |title=Burnout et victimisations\u00a0: effets des agressions des personnes d\u00e9tenues envers les personnels de surveillance |journal=L'Enc\u00e9phale |date=September 2011 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=284\u2013292 |doi=10.1016/j.encep.2010.08.006 |pmid=21981889 |url=https://europepmc.org/article/med/21981889 |quote=\"Burnout doesn't appear per se in any international classification of mental disorders: clinicians often use the diagnosis of adjustment disorder\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=H\u00f6schl |first1=C. |title=2394 \u2013 Burnout is a myth |journal=European Psychiatry |date=January 2013 |volume=28 |issue=Supplement 1 |page=1 |doi=10.1016/S0924-9338(13)77215-8 }}</ref><ref name=\"Liu, P.M. 2003 pp. 433-457\">Liu, P.M., & Van Liew, D.A. (2003). Depression and burnout. In J.P. Kahn and A.M. Langlieb (Eds.), ''Mental health and productivity in the workplace: A handbook for organizations and clinician'' (pp. 433-457). San Francisco: Jossey-Bass.</ref> and [[Psychological trauma|Unspecified Trauma- and Stressor-Related Disorder]] cover many cases of the condition however.\n\nThe [[Royal Dutch Medical Association]] treats \"burnout\" as a defined subtype of [[adjustment disorder]],<ref name=\"jstor.org\">{{cite journal |last1=van der Klink |first1=Jac JL |last2=van Dijk |first2=Frank JH |title=Dutch practice guidelines for managing adjustment disorders in occupational and primary health care |journal=Scandinavian Journal of Work, Environment & Health |date=2003 |volume=29 |issue=6 |pages=478\u2013487 |doi=10.5271/sjweh.756 |jstor=40967326 |pmid=14712856 |issn=0355-3140|doi-access=free }}</ref> in The Netherlands it is included in handbooks and medical staff are trained in its diagnosis and treatment.<ref name=\"Burnout: 35 years of research and p\">{{cite journal |last1=Schaufeli |first1=W.B. |title=Burnout: 35 years of research and practice |journal=Career Development International |date=June 2009 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=204\u2013220 |doi=10.1108/13620430910966406 }}</ref>\n\nRegarding the [[International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems]] (ICD), the ICD-10 edition (current 1994-2021) classifies \"burn-out\" as a type of non-medical life-management difficulty under code Z73.0.<ref>ICD-10: International Classification of Diseases, Z73. Geneva: World Health Organization, 2015.</ref> It is considered to be one of the \"factors influencing health status and contact with health services\" and \"should not be used\" for \"primary mortality coding\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/XXI |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref> It is also considered one of the \"problems related to life-management difficulty\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/Z73 |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref> The condition is only further defined as being a \"state of [[emotional exhaustion|vital exhaustion]]\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/Z73.0 |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ICD-10 also contains a medical condition category of \"F43.8 Other reactions to severe stress\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/F43.8 |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref> (sometimes known as [[neurasthenia]]), which some (including the [[Swedish National Board of Health and Welfare]]) believe defines the more serious cases of burnout. Swedish sufferers of severe burnout are treated as having this medical condition.<ref name=\"Burnout: 35 years of research and p\"/> This category is in the same group as [[adjustment disorder]] and [[posttraumatic stress disorder]], other conditions caused by excessive stress that continue once the stressors have been removed.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/F43 |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref>\n\nA new version of the ICD, ICD-11, was released in June 2018, for first use in January 2022.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/18-06-2018-who-releases-new-international-classification-of-diseases-(icd-11) | title=WHO releases new International Classification of Diseases (ICD 11)}}</ref> It has an entry coded and titled \"QD85 Burn-out\". This describes the condition thusly:\n\n<blockquote>Burn-out is a syndrome conceptualized as resulting from chronic workplace stress that has not been successfully managed. It is characterized by three dimensions: 1) feelings of energy depletion or exhaustion; 2) increased mental distance from one\u2019s job, or feelings of negativism or cynicism related to one's job; and 3) reduced professional efficacy. Burn-out refers specifically to phenomena in the occupational context and should not be applied to describe experiences in other areas of life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://id.who.int/icd/entity/129180281 |title=QD85 Burn-out  |website=icd.who.int|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis condition is classified under \"Problems associated with employment or unemployment\" in the section on \"Factors influencing health status or contact with health services.\" The section is devoted to reasons other than recognized diseases or health conditions for which people contact health services.<ref name=WHO-2019/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://id.who.int/icd/entity/1249056269|title=24. Factors influencing health status or contact with health services |website=icd.who.int|access-date=2019-05-28|quote=Categories in this chapter are provided for occasions when circumstances other than a disease, injury or external cause classifiable elsewhere are recorded as \"diagnoses\" or \"problems.\" This can arise... When some circumstance or problem is present which influences the person's health status but is not in itself a current illness or injury. Such circumstance or problem may be elicited during population surveys, when the person may or may not be currently sick, or be recorded as additional information to be borne in mind when the person is receiving care for some illness or injury.}}</ref> In a statement made in May 2019, the WHO said \"Burn-out is included in the 11th Revision of the International Classification of Diseases (ICD-11) as an occupational phenomenon. It is not classified as a medical condition.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.who.int/mental_health/evidence/burn-out/en/ |title = WHO &#124; Burn-out an \"occupational phenomenon\": International Classification of Diseases}}</ref>\n\nThe ICD's browser and coding tool both attach the term \"caregiver burnout\" to category \"QF27 Difficulty or need for assistance at home and no other household member able to render care\".<ref>http://id.who.int/icd/entity/757911124</ref><ref>https://icd.who.int/ct11/icd11_mms/en/release and search for \"burnout\"</ref> This acknowledges that burnout can occur in this context.\n\nThe ICD-11 also has the medical condition \"6B4Y Other specified disorders specifically associated with stress\",<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse11/l-m/en#/http%3a%2f%2fid.who.int%2ficd%2fentity%2f991786158%2fmms%2fother |title = ICD-11 - Mortality and Morbidity Statistics}}</ref> which is the equivalent of the ICD-10's F43.8.\n\nThe [[American Psychiatric Association]] says \"it is estimated that 2 out of 5 psychiatrists have professional burnout,\" and believes that \"addressing this problem has become one of the most pressing issues for medicine.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Well-being and Burnout |url=https://www.psychiatry.org/psychiatrists/practice/well-being-and-burnout |website=www.psychiatry.org}}</ref>\n\n=== Instruments ===\nIn 1981, Maslach and Jackson developed the first widely used instrument for assessing burnout, namely, the [[Maslach Burnout Inventory]] (MBI).<ref name=\"Maslach2\">{{cite journal|author1=Maslach, C.|author2=Jackson, S.E.|year=1981|title=The measurement of experienced burnout|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/96095aa76b740b97bd958019b93b4c0d9ada0fea|journal=Journal of Occupational Behavior|volume=2|issue=2|pages=99\u2013113|doi=10.1002/job.4030020205|via=}}</ref> Consistent with Maslach's conceptualization, the MBI operationalizes burnout as a three-dimensional syndrome consisting of emotional exhaustion, depersonalization, and reduced personal accomplishment.<ref name = \"Maslach2\"/><ref name = \"Maslach\"/> Other researchers have argued that burnout should be limited to fatigue and exhaustion.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Kristensen|first1 = T.S.|last2 = Borritz|first2 = M.|last3 = Villadsen|first3 = E.|last4 = Christensen|first4 = K.B.|year = 2005|title = The Copenhagen Burnout Inventory: A new tool for the assessment of burnout|url = |journal = Work & Stress|volume = 19|issue = 3|pages = 192\u2013207|doi = 10.1080/02678370500297720}}</ref> Exhaustion is considered to be burnout's core.<ref name=\"Maslach01\"/><ref>Schonfeld, I.S., Verkuilen, J. & Bianchi, R. (2019). An exploratory structural equation modelling bi-factor analytic approach to uncovering what burnout, depression, and anxiety scales measure. ''Psychological Assessment''. https://doi.org/10.1037/pas0000721</ref>\n\nThere are, however, other conceptualizations of burnout that differ from the conceptualization adopted by the WHO. Shirom and Melamed with their Shirom-Melamed Burnout Measure conceptualize burnout in terms of physical exhaustion, cognitive weariness, and emotional exhaustion;<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Shirom, A.|author2=Melamed, S.|year=2006|title=A comparison of the construct validity of two burnout measures in two groups of professionals|url=|journal=International Journal of Stress Management|volume=13|issue=2|pages=176\u2013200|doi=10.1037/1072-5245.13.2.176}},</ref><ref>Toker, S., Melamed, S., Berliner, S., Zeltser, D., & Shapira, I. (2012). Burnout and risk of coronary heart disease: A prospective study of 8838 employees. Psychosomatic Medicine, 74, 840\u2013847. https://doi.org/10.1097/PSY.0b013e31826c3174</ref> however, an examination of Shirom and Melamed's emotional exhaustion subscale indicates that the subscale looks more like a measure of Maslach's<ref name=\"Maslach01\">{{cite journal|last1 = Maslach|first1 = C.|last2 = Schaufeli|first2 = W. B.|last3 = Leiter|first3 = M. P.|editor = S. T. Fiske |editor2=D. L. Schacter |editor3=C. Zahn-Waxler|year = 2001|title = Job burnout|journal = Annual Review of Psychology|volume = 52|pages = 397\u2013422|doi = 10.1146/annurev.psych.52.1.397|pmid = 11148311|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5fc3eecc1afad1365bc8469ab5c39477e8c26146}}</ref> concept of depersonalization.<ref>Toker, S., Melamed, S., Berliner, S., Zeltser, D., & Shapira, I. (2012). Burnout and risk of coronary heart disease: A prospective study of 8838 employees. ''Psychosomatic Medicine, 74'', 840\u2013847</ref> Demerouti and Bakker (with their Oldenburg Burnout Inventory) conceptualize burnout in terms of exhaustion and disengagement.<ref>Demerouti, E., Bakker, A.B., Vardakou, I., & Kantas, A. (2003). The convergent validity of two burnout instruments: A multitrait-multimethod analysis. ''European Journal of Psychological Assessment, 19'', 12-23</ref> There are other conceptualizations as well that are embodied in these instruments: the Copenhagen Burnout Inventory,<ref name=\"Kristensen\">Kristensen, T.S.; Borritz, M.; Villadsen, E.; Christensen, K.B. (2005). \"The Copenhagen Burnout Inventory: A new tool for the assessment of burnout\". Work & Stress. 19 (3): 192\u2013207. doi:10.1080/02678370500297720</ref> the Hamburg Burnout Inventory,<ref name=\"Wurm\">Wurm, W., Vogel, K., Holl, A., Ebner, C., Bayer, D., M\u00f6rkl, S., \u2026 Hofmann, P. (2016). Depression-Burnout Overlap in Physicians. ''Plos One, 11'', e0149913.</ref> Malach-Pines's Burnout Measure,<ref>Malach-Pines, A. (2005). The Burnout Measure, Short Version. ''International Journal of Stress Management, 12''(1), 78\u201388.</ref> and more. Kristensen et al.<ref name=\"Kristensen\" /> and Malach-Pines (who also published as Pines)<ref>Pines, A. M. (1987). Marriage burnout. ''Psychotherapy in Private Practice,''\n5'', 31\u201344.''</ref> advanced the view that burnout can also occur in non-work roles such as that of spouse.\n\nThe ''Utrecht Work Engagement Scale'' (UWES), was released by Wilmar Schaufeli and Arnold Bakker in 1999. It measures vigour, dedication and absorption; positive counterparts to the values measured by the BMI.<ref>https://www.wilmarschaufeli.nl/publications/Schaufeli/Test%20Manuals/Test_manual_UWES_English.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2010, researchers from [[Mayo Clinic]] used portions of the MBI, along with other comprehensive assessments, to develop the [[Well-Being Index]], a brief nine-item self-assessment tool designed to measure burnout and other dimensions of distress in health care workers specifically.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dyrbye|first=Liselotte N.|last2=Szydlo|first2=Daniel W.|last3=Downing|first3=Steven M.|last4=Sloan|first4=Jeff A.|last5=Shanafelt|first5=Tait D.|date=2010-01-27|title=Development and preliminary psychometric properties of a well-being index for medical students|journal=BMC Medical Education|volume=10|issue=1|pages=8|doi=10.1186/1472-6920-10-8|issn=1472-6920|pmc=2823603|pmid=20105312}}</ref>\n\nThe core of all of these conceptualizations, including that of Freudenberger, is exhaustion. Alternatively, burnout is also now seen as involving the full array of [[Depression (mood)|depressive]] symptoms (e.g., low [[Mood (psychology)|mood]], [[Cognitive psychology|cognitive]] alterations, [[Sleep disorder|sleep disturbance]]).<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Bianchi, R.|author2=Schonfeld, I.S.|author3=Laurent, E.|year=2015|title=Burnout-depression overlap: A review|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1318&context=cc_pubs|journal=Clinical Psychology Review|volume=36|pages=28\u201341|doi=10.1016/j.cpr.2015.01.004|pmid=25638755|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bianchi | first1 = R. | last2 = Schonfeld | first2 = I. S. | last3 = Vandel | first3 = P. | last4 = Laurent | first4 = E. | year = 2017 | title = On the depressive nature of the \"burnout syndrome\": A clarification | url = https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1537&context=gc_pubs| journal = European Psychiatry | volume = 41 | issue = | pages = 109\u2013110 | doi = 10.1016/j.eurpsy.2016.10.008 | pmid = 28135592 }}</ref> Marked differences in understanding of what constitutes burnout have highlighted the need for [[Definition#In medicine|consensus definition]].<ref name=Rotenstein2018/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Heinemann | first1 = L.V. | last2 = Heinemann | first2 = T. | year = 2017 | title = Burnout Research: Emergence and Scientific Investigation of a Contested Diagnosis | journal = Sage Open | volume = | issue = | pages = | doi = 10.1177/2158244017697154 | pmid = | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\n=== Subtypes ===\nIn 1991, Barry A. Farber proposed that there are three types of burnout:\n* \"wearout\" and \"brown-out\", where someone gives up having had too much stress and/or too little reward\n* \"classic/frenetic burnout\", where someone works harder and harder, trying to resolve the stressful situation and/or seek suitable reward for their work\n* \"underchallenged burnout\", where someone has low stress, but the work is unrewarding.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Farber |first1=Barry A. |title=Crisis in education: stress and burnout in the American teacher |date=1991 |publisher=Jossey-Bass |location=San Francisco}}</ref>\n\n====Caregiver burnout====\n{{Main|Caregiver stress}}\n\nBodies such as the US government's [[Centres for Disease Control and Prevention]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Dealing With Diabetes Burnout |url=https://www.cdc.gov/diabetes/library/spotlights/diabetes-burnout.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |language=en-us |date=12 August 2019}}</ref> the [[American Diabetes Association]]<ref>{{cite book |title=Diabetes burnout : what to do when you can't take it anymore |publisher=American Diabetes Association |isbn=1580400337 |date=1999}}</ref> and ''Diabetes Singapore''<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Diabetes Burnout? |url=https://www.moneyfm893.sg/whats-on/what-is-diabetes-burnout/ |website=MONEY FM 89.3 |date=5 December 2019}}</ref> identify and promote the phenomenon of \"diabetes burnout\". This relates to the self-care of people with diabetes, particularly those with type-2 diabetes. \"Diabetes burnout speaks to the physical and emotional exhaustion that people with diabetes experience when they have to deal with caring for themselves on a day-to-day basis. When you have to do so many things to stay in control then it does take a toll on your emotions... Once they get frustrated, some of them give up and stop (maintaining) a healthy diet, taking their medications regularly, going for exercises and this will result in poor diabetes control.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Diabetes Burnout? |url=https://www.moneyfm893.sg/whats-on/what-is-diabetes-burnout/ |website=MONEY FM 89.3 |date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Autistic burnout====\n\"Autistic burnout\" is a term used to describe burnout when it occurs in people with [[Autistic Spectrum Disorder]] (ASD).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://aaspire.org/projects/autistic-burnout/pilot-study-on-autistic-burnout-and-suicidal-behavior/ |title = Pilot study on autistic burnout and suicidal behavior \u2013 AASPIRE}}</ref> In this population, in addition to the typical symptoms it can cause \"autistic regression\", an increase of autistic symptoms. It is \"regression\" in the sense that the afflicted has typically had a similarly high level of symptoms in the distant past, and the burnout is perceived to be regressing them to this earlier state. Such burnout sometimes leads to permanent disability or suicidal behaviour. It need not be caused by workplace stress, but can also be caused by the stress of social interaction or other sources.<ref>https://www.seattlechildrens.org/globalassets/documents/health-and-safety/autism/autism_206_raymaker_slides.pdf, https://www.facebook.com/seattlechildrens/videos/vl.948687718589668/380037906042266/?type=1</ref><ref>https://www.goodtherapy/blog/autistic-burnout-an-often-misunderstood-element-of-autism-080620197</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1108/AIA-10-2018-0042| title=Helping autistic women thrive| year=2019| last1=Zener| first1=Dori| journal=Advances in Autism| volume=5| issue=3| pages=143\u2013156}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/s13229-020-0313-1|pmid = 31969977|title = Behavioral effects of multiple-dose oxytocin treatment in autism: A randomized, placebo-controlled trial with long-term follow-up|year = 2020|last1 = Bernaerts|first1 = Sylvie|last2 = Boets|first2 = Bart|last3 = Bosmans|first3 = Guy|last4 = Steyaert|first4 = Jean|last5 = Alaerts|first5 = Kaat|journal = Molecular Autism|volume = 11|pages = 6|pmc = 6964112}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DZwfujkNBGk</ref> [[Spoon theory]] is sometimes used to understand people in this situation.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Distinction Between Avoidance Behaviours, Social Fatigue and Burn out |url=http://functionallegacymindset.com.au/a-distinction-between-avoidance-behaviours-social-fatigue-and-burn-out/ |website=Functional Legacy Mindset}}</ref>\n\n=== Relationship with other conditions ===\nA growing body of evidence suggests that burnout is etiologically, clinically, and [[nosology|nosologically]] similar to [[Major depressive disorder|depression]].<ref>Bianchi, E., Schonfeld, I.S., & Laurent, E. (2018). Burnout syndrome and depression. Y.-K. Kim (Ed.), ''Understanding depression: Volume 2. Clinical manifestations, diagnosis and treatment'' (pp.187-202). Singapore: Springer. doi:10.1007/978-981-10-6577-4_14</ref><ref name = \"Ahola\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ahola | first1 = K. | last2 = Hakanen | first2 = J. | last3 = Perhoniemi | first3 = R. | last4 = Mutanen | first4 = P. | year = 2014 | title = Relationship between burnout and depressive symptoms: A study using the person-centred approach | url = | journal = Burnout Research | volume = 1 | issue = 1| pages = 29\u201337 | doi=10.1016/j.burn.2014.03.003| doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|author1=Bianchi, R.|author2=Laurent, E.|year=2015|title=Emotional information processing in depression and burnout: An eye-tracking study|url=|journal=European Archives of Psychiatry and Clinical Neuroscience|volume=265|issue=1|pages=27\u201334|doi=10.1007/s00406-014-0549-x|pmid=25297694}}</ref><ref name=\"Bianchi, R. 2014\">{{cite journal | last1 = Bianchi | first1 = R. | last2 = Schonfeld | first2 = I. S. | last3 = Laurent | first3 = E. | year = 2014 | title = Is burnout a depressive disorder? A re-examination with special focus on atypical depression | url = https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1316&context=cc_pubs| journal = International Journal of Stress Management | volume = 21 | issue = 4 | pages = 307\u2013324 | doi=10.1037/a0037906}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite journal|author1=Bianchi, R.|author2=Schonfeld, I. S.|author3=Laurent, E.|year=2014|title=Is burnout separable from depression in cluster analysis? A longitudinal study|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cc_pubs/323|journal=Social Psychiatry and Psychiatric Epidemiology|volume=50|issue=6|pages=1005\u20131111|doi=10.1007/s00127-014-0996-8|pmid=25527209|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Hintsa-et-al\">{{cite journal|author1=Hintsa, T.|author2=Elovainio, M.|author3=Jokela, M.|author4=Ahola, K.|author5=Virtanen, M.|author6=Pirkola, S.|year=2016|title=Is there an independent association between burnout and increased allostatic load? Testing the contribution of psychological distress and depression|url=|journal=Journal of Health Psychology|volume=16|issue=8|pages=576\u2013586|doi=10.1177/1359105314559619|pmid=25476575|hdl=10138/224473|hdl-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"Schonfeld\">{{cite journal|author1=Schonfeld, I.S.|author2=Bianchi, R.|year=2016|title=Burnout and depression: Two entities or one|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/gc_pubs/257|journal=Journal of Clinical Psychology|volume=72|issue=1|pages=22\u201337|doi=10.1002/jclp.22229|pmid=26451877|via=}}</ref> In a study that directly compared depressive symptoms in burned out workers and clinically depressed patients, no diagnostically significant differences were found between the two groups; burned out workers reported as many depressive symptoms as clinically depressed patients.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bianchi | first1 = R. | last2 = Boffy | first2 = C. | last3 = Hingray | first3 = C. | last4 = Truchot | first4 = D. | last5 = Laurent | first5 = E. | year = 2013 | title = Comparative symptomatology of burnout and depression | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7539920d9b6d84b27ad305101765447dd07390e6| journal = Journal of Health Psychology | volume = 18 | issue = 6| pages = 782\u2013787 | doi=10.1177/1359105313481079| pmid = 23520355 }}</ref> Moreover, a study by Bianchi, Schonfeld, and Laurent (2014) showed that about 90% of workers with full-blown burnout meet diagnostic criteria for depression.<ref name=\"Bianchi, R. 2014\"/> The view that burnout is a form of depression has found support in several recent studies.<ref name = \"Ahola\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"Hintsa-et-al\"/><ref name=\"Schonfeld\"/><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Wurm, W.|author2=Vogel, K.|author3=Holl, A.|author4=Ebner, C.|author5=Bayer, D.|author6=M\u00f6rkl, S.|author7=Hofmann, P.|year=2016|title=Depression-burnout overlap in physicians|url=|journal=PLOS One|volume=11|issue=e0149913|pages=e0149913|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1149913W|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0149913|pmc=4773131|pmid=26930395}}</ref> Some authors have recommended that the nosological concept of burnout be revised or even abandoned entirely given that it is not a distinct disorder and that there is no agreement on burnout diagnostic criteria.<ref name=Rotenstein2018>{{Cite journal|last=Rotenstein|first=Lisa S.|last2=Torre|first2=Matthew|last3=Ramos|first3=Marco A.|last4=Rosales|first4=Rachael C.|last5=Guille|first5=Constance|last6=Sen|first6=Srijan|last7=Mata|first7=Douglas A.|date=September 18, 2018|title=Prevalence of Burnout Among Physicians: A Systematic Review|journal=JAMA|volume=320|issue=11|pages=1131\u20131150|doi=10.1001/jama.2018.12777|issn=1538-3598|pmc=6233645|pmid=30326495}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schwenk|first=Thomas L.|last2=Gold|first2=Katherine J.|date=September 18, 2018|title=Physician Burnout-A Serious Symptom, But of What?|journal=JAMA|volume=320|issue=11|pages=1109\u20131110|doi=10.1001/jama.2018.11703|issn=1538-3598|pmid=30422283}}</ref>\n\n[[Postpartum depression]] is a form of depression recognised by the DSM that differs mainly from major depressive disorder in that it has a specific trigger.\n\nLiu and van Liew wrote that \"the term burnout is used so frequently that it has lost much of its original meaning. As originally used, burnout meant a mild degree of stress-induced unhappiness. The solutions ranged from a vacation to a sabbatical. Ultimately, it was used to describe everything from fatigue to a major depression and now seems to have become an alternative word for depression, but with a less serious significance\" (p.&nbsp;434).<ref name=\"Liu, P.M. 2003 pp. 433-457\"/> They also argue that burning out can trigger four distinct kinds of depression, each with their own recommended treatment. These are [[adjustment disorder]] with depressed mood, [[major depressive disorder]], [[dysthymia]], and [[bipolar disorder]].\n\nTamar Kakiashvili et al. however argued that while there are significant overlaps in symptoms between burnout and major depressive disorder (aka \"depression\"), there is much endocrine evidence to suggest that the biological basis of burnout is vastly different to typical depression. They argued that antidepressants should not be used by people with burnout as they make the underlying [[hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis]] dysfunction worse.<ref name=\"The medical perspective on burnout\">{{cite journal |last1=Kakiashvili |first1=Tamar |title=The medical perspective on burnout |journal=International Journal of Occupational Medicine and Environmental Health |date=March 2013 |volume=23 |issue=3 |pages=401\u2013412 |doi=10.2478/s13382-013-0093-3 |pmid=24018996 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Test !! [[Major depressive disorder]] !! [[Atypical depression]] !! [[PTSD]] !! [[Chronic Fatigue Syndrome]] !! Burnout\n|-\n| [[Cortisol awakening response]] || \u2191 || \u2193 <ref>{{cite journal |last1=O\u2019Keane |first1=Veronica |last2=Frodl |first2=Thomas |last3=Dinan |first3=Timothy G. |title=A review of Atypical depression in relation to the course of depression and changes in HPA axis organization |journal=Psychoneuroendocrinology |date=October 2012 |volume=37 |issue=10 |pages=1589\u20131599 |doi=10.1016/j.psyneuen.2012.03.009|pmid=22497986 }}</ref> || \u2193 || \u2193 <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nater |first1=Urs M. |last2=Maloney |first2=Elizabeth |last3=Boneva |first3=Roumiana S. |last4=Gurbaxani |first4=Brian M. |last5=Lin |first5=Jin-Mann |last6=Jones |first6=James F. |last7=Reeves |first7=William C. |last8=Heim |first8=Christine |title=Attenuated Morning Salivary Cortisol Concentrations in a Population-Based Study of Persons with Chronic Fatigue Syndrome and Well Controls |journal=The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology & Metabolism |date=March 2008 |volume=93 |issue=3 |pages=703\u2013709 |doi=10.1210/jc.2007-1747|pmid=18160468 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Papadopoulos |first1=Andrew S. |last2=Cleare |first2=Anthony J. |title=Hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis dysfunction in chronic fatigue syndrome |journal=Nature Reviews Endocrinology |date=January 2012 |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=22\u201332 |doi=10.1038/nrendo.2011.153 |pmid=21946893 |language=en |issn=1759-5037}}</ref>|| - or \u2193 \n|-\n| [[Adrenocorticotropic hormone]] (ACTH) || \u2191 ||  ||   || - <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scott |first1=Lucinda V. |last2=Medbak |first2=Sami |last3=Dinan |first3=Timothy G. |title=The low dose ACTH test in chronic fatigue syndrome and in health |journal=Clinical Endocrinology |date=4 January 2002 |volume=48 |issue=6 |pages=733\u2013737 |doi=10.1046/j.1365-2265.1998.00418.x |pmid=9713562 }}</ref> || - or \u2193 \n|-\n| [[Dehydroepiandrosterone sulphate]] (DHEA-S)|| \u2193 ||  ||\u2191 or \u2193 || \u2193 <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kuratsune |first1=H |last2=Yamaguti |first2=K |last3=Sawada |first3=M |last4=Kodate |first4=S |last5=Machii |first5=T |last6=Kanakura |first6=Y |last7=Kitani |first7=T |title=Dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate deficiency in chronic fatigue syndrome. |journal=International Journal of Molecular Medicine |date=1 January 1998 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=143\u20136 |doi=10.3892/ijmm.1.1.143 |pmid=9852212 }}</ref> || \u2191 \n|}<ref name=\"The medical perspective on burnout\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=MOMMERSTEEG |first1=P |last2=HEIJNEN |first2=C |last3=VERBRAAK |first3=M |last4=VANDOORNEN |first4=L |title=Clinical burnout is not reflected in the cortisol awakening response, the day-curve or the response to a low-dose dexamethasone suppression test |journal=Psychoneuroendocrinology |date=February 2006 |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=216\u2013225 |doi=10.1016/j.psyneuen.2005.07.003 |pmid=16150550 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sj\u00f6rs |first1=Anna |last2=Ljung |first2=Thomas |last3=Jonsdottir |first3=Ingibj\u00f6rg H |title=Long-term follow-up of cortisol awakening response in patients treated for stress-related exhaustion |journal=BMJ Open |date=10 July 2012 |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=e001091 |doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2012-001091 |pmid=22786949 |pmc=3400075 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=de Vente |first1=Wieke |last2=van Amsterdam |first2=Jan G. C. |last3=Olff |first3=Miranda |last4=Kamphuis |first4=Jan H. |last5=Emmelkamp |first5=Paul M. G. |title=Burnout Is Associated with Reduced Parasympathetic Activity and Reduced HPA Axis Responsiveness, Predominantly in Males |journal=BioMed Research International |date=October 2015 |url=https://www.hindawi.com/journals/bmri/2015/431725/ |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sonnentag |first1=Sabine |title=Burnout and functioning of the hypothalamus-pituitary-axis\u2014there are no simple answers |journal=Scandinavian Journal of Work, Environment & Health |date=2006 |volume=32 |issue=5 |pages=333\u2013337 |doi=10.5271/sjweh.1028 |pmid=17091200 |issn=0355-3140|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Oosterholt |first1=Bart G. |last2=Maes |first2=Joseph H.R. |last3=Van der Linden |first3=Dimitri |last4=Verbraak |first4=Marc J.P.M. |last5=Kompier |first5=Michiel A.J. |title=Burnout and cortisol: Evidence for a lower cortisol awakening response in both clinical and non-clinical burnout |journal=Journal of Psychosomatic Research |date=May 2015 |volume=78 |issue=5 |pages=445\u2013451 |doi=10.1016/j.jpsychores.2014.11.003|pmid=25433974 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Onen Sert\u00f6z |first1=Ozen |last2=Binbay |first2=I. Tolga |last3=Elbi Mete |first3=Hayriye |title=[The neurobiology of burnout: the hypothalamus-pituitary-adrenal gland axis and other findings] |journal=Turk Psikiyatri Dergisi = Turkish Journal of Psychiatry |date=2008 |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=318\u2013328 |issn=1300-2163|pmid=18791885 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Verhaeghe |first1=J. |last2=Van Den Eede |first2=F. |last3=Van Den Ameele |first3=H. |last4=Sabbe |first4=B. G. C. |title=[Neuro-endocrine correlates of burnout] |journal=Tijdschrift voor Psychiatrie |date=2012 |volume=54 |issue=6 |pages=517\u2013526 |issn=0303-7339|pmid=22753184 }}</ref>\n\nRobert Finlay-Jones made the case that what is generally considered \"depression\" is actually two separate conditions. In addition to the typical [[melancholic]] depression, there is a multi-millennia-old defined syndrome called \"[[acedia]]\" (which can be considered a [[phlegmatic]] depression). Those suffering from acedia experience some fear and sadness as the depressed do, but much less of it. Those suffering from acedia are more likely to have trouble doing anything useful than standard depression. But the main defining feature of acedia is an impairment of the senses. (This symptom is often ascribed to depression.<ref>https://www.discovermagazine.com/mind/how-depression-dulls-the-world-literally</ref>) Finlay-Jones believed a lack of work satisfaction could lead to both depression and acedia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Finlay-Jones |first1=Robert |title=Disgust with Life in General |journal=Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry |date=June 1983 |volume=17 |issue=2 |pages=149\u2013152 |doi=10.3109/00048678309159998 |pmid=6578787 }}</ref>\n\nIt has also been hypothesised that [[chronic fatigue syndrome]] is caused by burnout.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jameson |first1=David |title=Persistent burnout theory of chronic fatigue syndrome |date=27 February 2015 |url=https://peerj.com/preprints/860v1/ |publisher=PeerJ PrePrints |doi=10.7287/peerj.preprints.860v1 |language=en|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Van Houdenhove |first1=Boudewijn |last2=Van Den Eede |first2=Filip |last3=Luyten |first3=Patrick |title=Does hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis hypofunction in chronic fatigue syndrome reflect a 'crash' in the stress system? |journal=Medical Hypotheses |date=June 2009 |volume=72 |issue=6 |pages=701\u2013705 |doi=10.1016/j.mehy.2008.11.044 |pmid=19237251 |issn=1532-2777}}</ref> It is suggested that the \"burning out\" of the body's stress symptom (by any of a wide range of causes) can lead to chronic fatigue. \"Occupational burnout\" is known for its exhausting effect on sufferers. [[Overtraining]] syndrome, a similar but lesser exhausting condition to CFS has been conceptualised as [[adjustment disorder]], a common diagnosis for those burnt out.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=Clive Martin |last2=Tenenbaum |first2=Gershon |title=Adjustment Disorder: a new way of conceptualizing the overtraining syndrome |journal=International Review of Sport and Exercise Psychology |date=September 2009 |volume=2 |issue=2 |pages=181\u2013197 |doi=10.1080/17509840903110962 }}</ref>\n\n==Risk factors==\nEvidence suggests that the etiology of burnout is multifactorial, with dispositional factors playing an important, long-overlooked role.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Alarcon|first1 = G.|last2 = Eschleman|first2 = K. J.|last3 = Bowling|first3 = N. A.|year = 2009|title = Relationships between personality variables and burnout: A meta-analysis|url = |journal = Work & Stress|volume = 23|issue = 3|pages = 244\u2013263|doi = 10.1080/02678370903282600}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Swider|first1 = B. W.|last2 = Zimmerman|first2 = R. D.|year = 2010|title = Born to burnout: A meta-analytic path model of personality, job burnout, and work outcomes|url = |journal = Journal of Vocational Behavior|volume = 76|issue = 3|pages = 487\u2013506|doi = 10.1016/j.jvb.2010.01.003}}</ref> Cognitive dispositional factors implicated in depression have also been found to be implicated in burnout.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Bianchi, R.|author2=Schonfeld, I.S.|year=2016|title=Burnout is associated with a depressive cognitive style|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cc_pubs/318|journal=Personality and Individual Differences|volume=100|pages=1\u20135|doi=10.1016/j.paid.2016.01.008|via=}}</ref> One cause of burnout includes [[stressor]]s that a person is unable to cope with fully.<ref>Mustafa, O.M. (2015). Health behaviors and personality in burnout: A third dimension. ''Medical Education Online, 20'', doi:10.3402/meo.v20.28187. [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.3402/meo.v20.28187]</ref>\n\nBurnout is thought to occur when a mismatch is present between the nature of the job and the job the person is actually doing. A common indication of this mismatch is work overload, which sometimes involves a worker who survives a round of layoffs, but after the layoffs the worker finds that he or she is doing too much with too few resources. Overload may occur in the context of downsizing, which often does not narrow an organization's goals, but requires fewer employees to meet those goals.<ref name=\"Maslach972\">{{cite book|last=Maslach, C.|title=The Truth About Burnout: How Organizations Cause Personal Stress and What to Do About It|last2=Leiter, M.P.|publisher=Jossey-Bass|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[job demands-resources model]] has implications for burnout, as measured by the Oldenburg Burnout Inventory (OLBI). Physical and psychological job demands were concurrently associated with the exhaustion, as measured by the OLBI.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Demerouti|first1=Evangelia|last2=Bakker|first2=Arnold B.|last3=Nachreiner|first3=Friedhelm|last4=Schaufeli|first4=Wilmar B.|title=The job demands-resources model of burnout.|journal=Journal of Applied Psychology|date=2001|volume=86|issue=3|pages=499\u2013512|doi=10.1037/0021-9010.86.3.499}}</ref> Lack of job resources was associated with the disengagement component of the OLBI.\n\nMaslach, Schaufeli and Leiter identified six risk factors for burnout: mismatch in workload, mismatch in control, lack of appropriate awards, loss of a sense of positive connection with others in the workplace, perceived lack of fairness, and conflict between values.<ref name=\"Maslach01\"/>\n\n==Effects==\nSome research indicates that burnout is associated with reduced [[job performance]], coronary [[heart disease]],<ref>{{cite journal|author=Toker, S.|last2=Melamed, S.|last3=Berliner, S.|last4=Zeltser, D.|last5=Shapira, I.|year=2012|title=Burnout and risk of coronary heart disease: a prospective study of 8838 employees|url=|journal=Psychosomatic Medicine|volume=74|issue=8|pages=840\u2013847|doi=10.1097/PSY.0b013e31826c3174|pmid=23006431}}</ref> and [[mental health]] problems. Examples of emotional symptoms of occupational burnout include a lack of interest in the work being done, a decrease in work performance levels, feelings of helplessness, and trouble sleeping.<ref name=\"Cengage Learning\">{{cite book|last1=Aamodt|first1=Michael|title=Industrial/organizational psychology : an applied approach|date=2016|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-11842-3|edition=8th|location=Boston, MA|page=563}}</ref> With regard to mental health problems, research on dentists<ref name = \"Ahola\"/> and physicians<ref name = 'Wurm'/> suggests that what is meant by burnout is a depressive syndrome. Thus reduced job performance and cardiovascular risk could be related to burnout because of burnout's tie to depression. Behavioral signs of occupational burnout are demonstrated through cynicism within work relationships, such as coworkers, clients, and the organization.\n\nOther effects of burnout can manifest as lowered energy and productivity levels, with workers observed to be consistently late for work and feeling a sense of dread upon arriving. They can suffer decreased concentration, forgetfulness, increased frustration, or feelings of being overwhelmed. They may complain and feel negative, or feel apathetic and believe they have little impact on their coworkers and environment.<ref name=\"Cengage Learning\"/> Occupational burnout is also associated with absences, time missed from work, and thoughts of quitting.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite journal | last1 = Elliott | first1 = T. | last2 = Shewchuk | first2 = R. | last3 = Hagglund | first3 = K. | last4 = Rybarczyk | first4 = B. | last5 = Harkins | first5 = S. | year = 1996 | title = Occupational burnout, tolerance for stress, and coping among nurses in rehabilitation units | url = | journal = Rehabilitation Psychology | volume = 41 | issue = 4| pages = 267\u2013284 | doi=10.1037/0090-5550.41.4.267}}</ref>\n\nChronic burnout is also associated with cognitive impairments such as [[memory]] and [[attention]].<ref>{{cite journal|last = Sandstrom|first = A|author2 = Rhodin IN|author3 = Lundberg M|author4 = Olsson T|author5 = Nyberg L.|title = Impaired cognitive performance in patients with chronic burnout syndrome.|journal = Biological Psychology|year = 2005|volume = 69|issue = 3|pages = 271\u2013279|doi = 10.1016/j.biopsycho.2004.08.003|pmid = 15925030}}</ref> (See also [[Effects of stress on memory]].)\n\nThere is a growing amount of research suggesting that burnout can manifest differently between genders, with greater incidence of depersonalisation amongst men and higher emotional exhaustion among women.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Houkes|first=Inge|last2=Winants|first2=Yvonne|last3=Twellaar|first3=Mascha|last4=Verdonk|first4=Petra|date=2011-04-18|title=Development of burnout over time and the causal order of the three dimensions of burnout among male and female GPs. A three-wave panel study|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=Development+of+burnout+over+time+and+the+causal+order+of+the+three+dimensions+of+burnout+among+male+and+female+GPs.|journal=BMC Public Health|volume=11|pages=240|doi=10.1186/1471-2458-11-240|issn=1471-2458|pmc=3101180|pmid=21501467}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e-surgery.com/burnout-the-mens-health-crisis-we-arent-talking-about/|title=Burnout: The Men's Health Crisis We Aren't Talking About|last=Caufield|first=Madeleine|website=e-Surgery|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==Treatment and prevention==\nHealth condition treatment and prevention methods are often classified as \"primary prevention\" (stopping the condition occurring), \"secondary prevention\" (removing the condition that has occurred) and \"tertiary prevention\" (helping people live with the condition).\n\n===Primary prevention===\nMaslach believes that the only way to truly prevent burnout is through a combination of organizational change and education for the individual.<ref name=\"Maslach972\"/>\n\nMaslach and Leiter postulated that burnout occurs when there is a disconnection between the organization and the individual with regard to what they called the six areas of worklife: workload, control, reward, community, fairness, and values.<ref name=\"Maslach01\"/> Resolving these discrepancies requires integrated action on the part of both the individual and the organization.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" /> With regard to workload, assuring that a worker has adequate resources to meet demands as well as ensuring a satisfactory [[work\u2013life balance]] could help revitalize employees' energy.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" /> With regard to values, clearly stated ethical organizational values are important for ensuring employee commitment.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" /> Supportive leadership and relationships with colleagues are also helpful.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" />\n\nOne approach for addressing these discrepancies focuses specifically on the fairness area. In one study employees met weekly to discuss and attempt to resolve perceived inequities in their job.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = van Dierendonck|first1 = D.|last2 = Schaufeli|first2 = W. B.|last3 = Buunk|first3 = B. P.|year = 1998|title = The evaluation of an individual burnout intervention program: the role of in- equity and social support|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/bfd953e2f5dd6d311fe74f720f17ac9956996b11|journal = J. Appl. Psychol.|volume = 83|issue = 3|pages = 392\u2013407|doi = 10.1037/0021-9010.83.3.392}}</ref> The intervention was associated with decreases in exhaustion over time but not cynicism or inefficacy, suggesting that a broader approach is required.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" />\n\nH\u00e4tinen et al. suggest \"improving job-person fit by focusing attention on the relationship between the person and the job situation, rather than either of these in isolation, seems to be the most promising way of dealing with burnout.\".<ref>https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/9e3c/708f34fa9f158f842a3fc74448ea0c65d2c7.pdf?_ga=2.12703093.333517712.1583537646-253097619.1583537646</ref> They also note that \"at the individual level, cognitive-behavioural strategies have the best potential for success.\"\n\nBurnout prevention programs have traditionally focused on [[cognitive-behavioral therapy]] (CBT), [[cognitive restructuring]], didactic [[stress management]], and relaxation. CBT, [[relaxation technique]]s (including physical techniques and mental techniques), and schedule changes are the best-supported techniques for reducing or preventing burnout in a health-care setting. Mindfulness therapy has been shown to be an effective preventative for occupational burnout in medical practitioners.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scheepers|first=Ren\u00e9e A.|last2=Emke|first2=Helga|last3=Epstein|first3=Ronald M.|last4=Lombarts|first4=Kiki M. J. M. H.|date=2019-12-22|title=The impact of mindfulness-based interventions on doctors' well-being and performance: A systematic review|journal=Medical Education|volume=54|issue=2|pages=138\u2013149|doi=10.1111/medu.14020|issn=1365-2923|pmid=31868262|pmc=7003865}}</ref> Combining both organizational and individual-level activities may be the most beneficial approach to reducing symptoms. A Cochrane review, however, reported that evidence for the efficacy of CBT in healthcare workers is of low quality, indicating that it is no better than alternative interventions.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\"/>\n\nFor the purpose of preventing occupational burnout, various stress management interventions have been shown to help improve employee health and well-being in the workplace and lower stress levels. Training employees in ways to manage stress in the workplace have also been shown to be effective in preventing burnout.<ref>{{cite book|author=William D. McLaurine|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uRU3tG29VfUC&lpg=PA92&dq=job%20burnout%20prevention&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A correlational study of job burnout and organizational commitment among correctional officers|publisher= Capella University. School of Psychology|page= 92|isbn=9780549438144}}</ref> One study suggests that social-cognitive processes such as [[organizational commitment|commitment]] to work, [[self-efficacy]], learned resourcefulness, and [[hope]] may insulate individuals from experiencing occupational burnout.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Increasing a worker's [[Job control (workplace)|control over his or her job]] is another intervention has been shown to help counteract exhaustion and [[cynicism (contemporary)|cynicism]] in the workplace.<ref name=\"H\u00e4tinen-2007\" />\n\nAdditional prevention methods include: starting the day with a relaxing ritual; yoga; adopting healthy eating, exercising, and sleeping habits; setting boundaries; taking breaks from technology; nourishing one's creative side, and learning how to manage stress.<ref name=\"pat\">{{cite web |url=http://health.usnews.com/health-care/for-better/articles/2017-02-27/politically-active-4-tips-for-incorporating-self-care |title=Politically Active? 4 Tips for Incorporating Self-Care, US News |date=27 February 2017 |work=US News |accessdate=5 March 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.helpguide.org/mental/stress_signs.htm|title=Stress Symptoms, Signs, & Causes: The Effects of Stress Overload and What You Can Do About It|last=Smith, M.|last2=Segal, R.|year=2014|website=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927114835/http://www.helpguide.org/mental/stress_signs.htm|archivedate=27 September 2014|accessdate=31 March 2014|last3=Segal, J.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grensman|first=Astrid|last2=Acharya|first2=Bikash Dev|last3=W\u00e4ndell|first3=Per|last4=Nilsson|first4=Gunnar H.|last5=Falkenberg|first5=Torkel|last6=Sundin|first6=\u00d6rjan|last7=Werner|first7=Sigbritt|date=2018-03-06|title=Effect of traditional yoga, mindfulness\u2013based cognitive therapy, and cognitive behavioral therapy, on health related quality of life: a randomized controlled trial on patients on sick leave because of burnout|journal=BMC Complementary and Alternative Medicine|volume=18|issue=1|pages=80|doi=10.1186/s12906-018-2141-9|issn=1472-6882|pmc=5839058|pmid=29510704}}</ref>\n\nBarry A. Farber suggests strategies like setting more achievable goals, focusing on the value of the work, and finding better ways of doing the job, can all be helpful ways of helping the stressed. People who don't mind the stress but want more reward can benefit from reassessing their [[work-life balance]] and implementing stress reduction techniques like meditation and exercise. Others with low stress, but are underwhelmed and bored with work, can benefit from seeking greater challenge.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Farber |first1=Barry A. |title=Tailoring Treatment Strategies for Different Types of Burnout |journal=Journal of Clinical Psychology |date=May 2000 |volume=56 |issue=5|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1097-4679(200005)56:5<675::AID-JCLP8>3.0.CO;2-D }}</ref>\n\nThijs Launspach is his 2019 book \"Werken met Millennials\" (\"Working with [[Millennial]]s\") argues that that society is making ever higher demands, and that this is an important consideration when addressing prevention. The book particularly focuses on why so many Milliennials are at home suffering from burnout.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thijslaunspach.nl/ | title=Thijs Launspach &#124; psycholoog, schrijver, advies}}</ref>\n\nSee also [[Occupational stress]], [[Caregiver stress]], [[Stress management]].\n\n===Secondary and tertiary prevention (aka treatment)===\nH\u00e4tinen et al. list a number of common treatments, including [[medicine|treatment of any outstanding medical conditions]], [[stress management]], [[time management]], [[management of depression|depression treatment]], [[psychotherapies]], ergonomic improvement and other physiological and [[occupational therapy]], [[physical exercise]] and [[Relaxation (psychology)|relaxation]]. They have found that is more effective to have a greater focus on \"group discussions on work related issues\", and discussion about \"work and private life interface\" and other personal needs with psychologists and workplace representatives.<ref name=\"H\u00e4tinen-2007\">{{cite journal | last1 = H\u00e4tinen | first1 = M. | last2 = Kinnunen | first2 = U. | last3 = Pekkonen | first3 = M. | last4 = Kalimo | first4 = R. | year = 2007 | title = Comparing two burnout interventions: Perceived job control mediates decreases in burnout | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/9e3c708f34fa9f158f842a3fc74448ea0c65d2c7| journal = International Journal of Stress Management | volume = 14 | issue = 3| pages = 227\u2013248 | doi=10.1037/1072-5245.14.3.227}}</ref>\n\nJac JL van der Klink and Frank JH van Dijk suggest [[stress inoculation training]], [[cognitive restructuring]], [[systematic desensitisation|graded activity]] and \"time contingency\" (progressing based on a timeline rather than patient's comfort) are effective methods of treatment.<ref name=\"jstor.org\"/>\n\nKakiashvili et al. say that \"medical treatment of burnout is mostly symptomatic: it involves measures to prevent and treat the symptoms.\" They say the use of [[anxiolytics]] and [[sedatives]] to treat burnout related stress is effective, but does nothing to change the sources of stress. They say the poor sleep often caused by burnout (and the subsequent fatigue) is best treated with [[hypnotics]] and CBT (within which they include \"sleep hygiene, education, relaxation training, stimulus control, and cognitive therapy\"). They advise against the use of [[antidepressants]] as they worsen the [[hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis]] dysfunction at the core of burnout. They also believe \"vitamins and minerals are crucial in addressing adrenal and HPA axis dysfunction\", noting the importance of specific nutrients.<ref name=\"The medical perspective on burnout\"/>\n\n[[Light therapy]] (similar to that used for [[Seasonal Affective Disorder]]) may be effective.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meesters |first1=Y. |title=Burnout and light treatment |journal=Stress & Health |date=February 2010 |volume=26 |issue=1|pages=13\u201320 |doi=10.1002/smi.1250 }}</ref>\n\nBurnout also often causes a decline in the ability to update information in working memory. This is not easily treated with CBT.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Oosterholt |first1=Bart G |title=Burned out cognition \u2014 cognitive functioning of burnout patients before and after a period with psychological treatment |journal=Scandinavian Journal of Work, Environment & Health |date=July 2012 |volume=38 |issue=4 |pages=358\u2013369 |jstor=41508903 |doi=10.5271/sjweh.3256 |pmid=22025205 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nOne reason it is difficult to treat the three standard symptoms of burnout (exhaustion, cynicism, and inefficacy), is because they respond to the same preventive or treatment activities in different ways.<ref name=\"H\u00e4tinen-2007\"/>\n\nExhaustion is more easily treated than cynicism and professional inefficacy, which tend to be more resistant to treatment. Research suggests that intervention actually may worsen the professional efficacy of a person who originally exhibited low professional efficacy.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Van Dierendonck | first1 = D. | last2 = Schaufeli | first2 = W. B. | last3 = Buunk | first3 = B. P. | year = 1998 | title = The evaluation of an individual burnout intervention program: The role of inequity and social support | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/bfd953e2f5dd6d311fe74f720f17ac9956996b11| journal = Journal of Applied Psychology | volume = 83 | issue = 3| pages = 392\u2013407 | doi=10.1037/0021-9010.83.3.392}}</ref>\n\nEmployee rehabilitation is a tertiary preventive intervention which means the strategies used in rehabilitation are meant to alleviate burnout symptoms in individuals who are already affected without curing them.<ref name=\"H\u00e4tinen-2007\" /> Such rehabilitation of the working population includes multidisciplinary activities with the intent of maintaining and improving employees' working ability and ensuring a supply of skilled and capable labor in society.\n\nSee also [[Management of depression]], [[Treatments for PTSD]] and [[Chronic fatigue syndrome treatment]].\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Compassion fatigue]]\n* [[Counterproductive work behavior]]\n* [[Employee engagement]]\n* [[Meditation]]\n* [[Spoon theory]]\n* [[Writer's block]]\n* [[Emotional exhaustion]]\n\n'''Stress and the workplace:'''\n* [[Workplace stress]]\n* [[Caregiver stress]]\n* [[Industrial and organizational psychology]] \n* [[Occupational health psychology]] \n* [[Perceived organizational support]] \n* [[Perceived psychological contract violation]]\n* [[Work\u2013life balance]]\n\n'''Medical:'''\n* [[Stress (biology)|Stress]]\n* [[Hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis]]\n* [[Depression (mood)|Depression]]\n* [[Adjustment disorder]]\n* [[Acute stress disorder]]\n* [[Posttraumatic stress disorder]]\n* [[Chronic fatigue syndrome]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Bianchi | first1 = R. | last2 = Schonfeld | first2 = I.S. | last3 = Laurent | first3 = E. | year = 2014 | title = Is burnout a depressive disorder? A reexamination with special focus on atypical depression | url = https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1316&context=cc_pubs| journal = International Journal of Stress Management | volume = 21 | issue = 4| pages = 307\u2013324 | doi = 10.1037/a0037906 }}\n* Caputo, Janette S. (1991). ''Stress and Burnout in Library Service'', Phoenix, AZ: Oryx Press.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Cordes | first1 = C. | last2 = Dougherty | first2 = T. | year = 1996 | title = A review and integration of research on job burnout | url = | journal = Academy of Management Review | volume = 18 | issue = 4| pages = 621\u2013656 | doi = 10.5465/AMR.1993.9402210153 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Freudenberger | first1 = Herbert J | year = 1974 | title = Staff burnout | url = | journal = Journal of Social Issues | volume = 30 | issue = | pages = 159\u2013165 | doi = 10.1111/j.1540-4560.1974.tb00706.x }}\n* Freudenberger, Herbert J.  (1980). Burn-Out: The High Cost of High Achievement. Anchor Press\n* Freudenberger, Herbert J.  and North, Gail. (1985). Women's Burnout: How to Spot It, How to Reverse It, and How to Prevent It, Doubleday\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Heinemann | first1 = L.V. | last2 = Heinemann | first2 = T. | year = 2017 | title = Burnout Research: Emergence and Scientific Investigation of a Contested Diagnosis | url = | journal = Sage Open | volume = | issue = | pages = | doi = 10.1177/2158244017697154 | doi-access = free }}\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Kristensen|first1 = T.S.|last2 = Borritz|first2 = M.|last3 = Villadsen|first3 = E.|last4 = Christensen|first4 = K.B.|year = 2005|title = The Copenhagen Burnout Inventory: A new tool for the assessment of burnout|url = |journal = Work & Stress|volume = 19|issue = 3|pages = 192\u2013207|doi = 10.1080/02678370500297720}}\n* Maslach, C., Jackson, S. E, & Leiter, M. P. MBI: The Maslach Burnout Inventory: Manual. Palo Alto: Consulting Psychologists Press, 1996.\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Maslach|first1 = C.|last2 = Leiter|first2 = M. P.|year = 2008|title = Early predictors of job burnout and engagement|url = |journal = Journal of Applied Psychology|volume = 93|issue = 3|pages = 498\u2013512|doi = 10.1037/0021-9010.93.3.498|pmid = 18457483|citeseerx = 10.1.1.607.4751}}\n* Maslach, C. & Leiter, M. P. (1997). The truth about burnout. San Francisco: Jossey Bass.\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Maslach|first1 = C.|last2 = Schaufeli|first2 = W. B.|last3 = Leiter|first3 = M. P.|year = 2001|title = Job burnout|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5fc3eecc1afad1365bc8469ab5c39477e8c26146|journal = Annual Review of Psychology|volume = 52|issue = |pages = 397\u2013422|doi = 10.1146/annurev.psych.52.1.397|pmid = 11148311}}\n* Ray, Bernice (2002). ''An assessment of burnout in academic librarians in America using the Maslach Burnout Inventor.'' New Brunswick, NJ: Rutgers University Press.\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Shaufeli|first1 = W. B.|last2 = Leiter|first2 = M. P.|last3 = Maslach|first3 = C.|year = 2009|title = Burnout: Thirty-five years of research and practice|url = |journal = Career Development International|volume = 14|issue = 3|pages = 204\u2013220|doi = 10.1108/13620430910966406}}\n* Shaw, Craig S. (1992). A Scientific Solution To Librarian Burnout. In ''New Library World Year, 93''(5).\n* Shirom, A. & Melamed, S. (2005). Does burnout affect physical health? A review of the evidence. In A.S.G. Antoniou & C.L. Cooper (Eds.), Research companion to organizational health psychology (pp.&nbsp;599\u2013622). Cheltenham, UK: Edward Elgar. \n* {{cite journal |last1 = van Dierendonck|first1 = D.|last2 = Schaufeli|first2 = W. B.|last3 = Buunk|first3 = B. P.|year = 1998|title = The evaluation of an individual burnout intervention program: the role of in- equity and social support|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/bfd953e2f5dd6d311fe74f720f17ac9956996b11|journal = J. Appl. Psychol.|volume = 83|issue = 3|pages = 392\u2013407|doi = 10.1037/0021-9010.83.3.392}}\n* Wang, Yang; Ramos, Aaron; Wu, Hui; Liu, Li; Yang, Xiaoshi; Wang, Jiana; Wang, Lie (2014-09-26).\"Relationship between occupational stress and burnout among Chinese teachers: a cross-sectional survey in Liaoning, China\". <nowiki>''</nowiki>International Archives of Occupational and Environmental Health<nowiki>''</nowiki> <nowiki>'''</nowiki>88<nowiki>'''</nowiki> (5): 589\u2013597. {{doi|10.1007/s00420-014-0987-9}}. {{ISSN|0340-0131}}\n* Warr, Peter. (1999). ''Psychology at Work'', 4th ed. London: Penguin.\n<!--\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Rosch | first1 = PJ | year = 1998 | title = Reminiscences of Hans Selye and the birth of \"Stress\" | url = | journal = Stress Medicine | volume = 14 | issue = | pages = 1\u20136 | doi=10.1002/(sici)1099-1700(199801)14:1<1::aid-smi777>3.3.co;2-n}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Rosch | first1 = PJ. Hans Selye | year = 1999 | title = | url = | journal = International Journal of Emergency Mental Health | volume = 1 | issue = | pages = 59\u201366 }}\n-->\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| ICD10 = {{ICD10|Z|73|0|z|70}}, {{ICD10|F|43|8}}\n}}\n{{Aspects of occupations}}\n\n[[Category:Human resource management]]\n[[Category:Stress]]\n[[Category:Organizational theory]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Workplace]]\n[[Category:Motivation]]\n[[Category:Organizational behavior]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Occupational burning}}\n{{short description|Type of psychological stress}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Occupational burn-out\n| synonyms        = Burn-out\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n| image           = File:Headache-1557872 960 720.jpg\n| image_size      = 300px\n| caption         = A person who is experiencing [[psychological stress]]\n}}\n\nAccording to the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO), '''occupational burnout''' is a [[syndrome]] resulting from chronic [[Occupational stress|work-related stress]], with symptoms characterized by \"feelings of energy depletion or exhaustion; increased mental distance from one\u2019s job, or feelings of negativism or cynicism related to one's job; and reduced professional efficacy.\"<ref name=\"WHO-2019\" /> While burnout influences [[health]] and may be a reason for people contacting [[health service]]s, it is not itself classified by the WHO as a [[medical condition]].<ref name=\"WHO-2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mental_health/evidence/burn-out/en/|title=Burn-out an \"occupational phenomenon\": International Classification of Diseases|website=WHO|date=28 May 2019|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, [[Herbert Freudenberger]] became the first researcher to publish in a psychology-related journal a paper that used the term \"burnout.\" The paper was based on his observations of the volunteer staff (including himself) at a free clinic for drug addicts.<ref name=\"staffburnout1\">{{cite journal|author=Freudenberger, H.J.|year=1974|title=Staff burnout|journal=Journal of Social Issues|volume= 30|pages=159\u2013165|doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1974.tb00706.x}}</ref> He characterized burnout by a set of symptoms that includes exhaustion resulting from work's excessive demands as well as physical symptoms such as headaches and sleeplessness, \"quickness to anger,\" and closed thinking. He observed that the burned-out worker \"looks, acts, and seems depressed.\" After the publication of Freudenberger's original paper, interest in occupational burnout grew. Because the phrase \"burnt-out\" was part of the title of a 1961 [[Graham Greene]] novel ''[[A Burnt-Out Case]]'', which dealt with a doctor working in the Belgian Congo with patients who had leprosy, the phrase may have been in use outside the psychology literature before Freudenberger employed it.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Burnt-Out Case|last=Greene|first=Graham|publisher=William Heinemann Ltd|year=1961|isbn=978-0140185393|pages=cover title}}</ref> (Wolfgang Kaskcha has written on the early documentation of the subject).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kaschka |first1=Wolfgang P |title=Burnout: A Fashionable Diagnosis |journal=Deutsch Arzteblatt International |date=Nov 2011 |volume=108 |issue=46 |pages=781\u2013787 |doi=10.3238/arztebl.2011.0781 |pmid=22163259 |pmc=3230825 }}</ref>\n\n[[Christina Maslach]] described burnout in terms of emotional exhaustion, depersonalization (treating clients/students and colleagues in a cynical way), and reduced feelings of work-related personal accomplishment.<ref name=\"Maslach\">{{cite web|author1=Maslach, C.|author2=Jackson, S.E|author3=Leiter, M.P.|year=1996|title=MBI: The Maslach Burnout Inventory: Manual|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/277816643|journal=|location=Palo Alto|publisher=Consulting Psychologists Press|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite journal|last1=Ruotsalainen|first1=JH|last2=Verbeek|first2=JH|last3=Marin\u00e9|first3=A|last4=Serra|first4=C|title=Preventing occupational stress in healthcare workers.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=7 April 2015|issue=4|pages=CD002892|pmid=25847433|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD002892.pub5|pmc=6718215}}</ref> In 1981, Maslach and Susan Jackson published the first widely used instrument for assessing burnout, the [[Maslach Burnout Inventory]].<ref name = \"Maslach2\"/> Originally focused on the human service professions (e.g., teachers, social workers),<ref name = \"Maslach2\"/> its application broadened to many other occupations.<ref name = \"Maslach\"/> The WHO adopted a conceptualization of burnout that is consistent with Maslach's.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n\n=== Classification ===\nBurnout is not recognized as a distinct disorder in the current revision (dating from 2013) of the [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]] (DSM-5).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vahia|first=Vihang N.|title=Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders 5: A quick glance|journal=Indian Journal of Psychiatry|volume=55|issue=3|pages=220\u2013223|doi=10.4103/0019-5545.117131|issn=0019-5545|pmc=3777342|pmid=24082241|year=2013}}</ref> It's definitions for [[Adjustment disorder|Adjustment Disorders]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Boudoukha |first1=A.H. |last2=Hautekeete |first2=M. |last3=Abdelaoui |first3=S. |last4=Groux |first4=W. |last5=Garay |first5=D. |title=Burnout et victimisations\u00a0: effets des agressions des personnes d\u00e9tenues envers les personnels de surveillance |journal=L'Enc\u00e9phale |date=September 2011 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=284\u2013292 |doi=10.1016/j.encep.2010.08.006 |pmid=21981889 |url=https://europepmc.org/article/med/21981889 |quote=\"Burnout doesn't appear per se in any international classification of mental disorders: clinicians often use the diagnosis of adjustment disorder\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=H\u00f6schl |first1=C. |title=2394 \u2013 Burnout is a myth |journal=European Psychiatry |date=January 2013 |volume=28 |issue=Supplement 1 |page=1 |doi=10.1016/S0924-9338(13)77215-8 }}</ref><ref name=\"Liu, P.M. 2003 pp. 433-457\">Liu, P.M., & Van Liew, D.A. (2003). Depression and burnout. In J.P. Kahn and A.M. Langlieb (Eds.), ''Mental health and productivity in the workplace: A handbook for organizations and clinician'' (pp. 433-457). San Francisco: Jossey-Bass.</ref> and [[Psychological trauma|Unspecified Trauma- and Stressor-Related Disorder]] cover many cases of the condition however.\n\nThe [[Royal Dutch Medical Association]] treats \"burnout\" as a defined subtype of [[adjustment disorder]],<ref name=\"jstor.org\">{{cite journal |last1=van der Klink |first1=Jac JL |last2=van Dijk |first2=Frank JH |title=Dutch practice guidelines for managing adjustment disorders in occupational and primary health care |journal=Scandinavian Journal of Work, Environment & Health |date=2003 |volume=29 |issue=6 |pages=478\u2013487 |doi=10.5271/sjweh.756 |jstor=40967326 |pmid=14712856 |issn=0355-3140|doi-access=free }}</ref> in The Netherlands it is included in handbooks and medical staff are trained in its diagnosis and treatment.<ref name=\"Burnout: 35 years of research and p\">{{cite journal |last1=Schaufeli |first1=W.B. |title=Burnout: 35 years of research and practice |journal=Career Development International |date=June 2009 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=204\u2013220 |doi=10.1108/13620430910966406 }}</ref>\n\nRegarding the [[International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems]] (ICD), the ICD-10 edition (current 1994-2021) classifies \"burn-out\" as a type of non-medical life-management difficulty under code Z73.0.<ref>ICD-10: International Classification of Diseases, Z73. Geneva: World Health Organization, 2015.</ref> It is considered to be one of the \"factors influencing health status and contact with health services\" and \"should not be used\" for \"primary mortality coding\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/XXI |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref> It is also considered one of the \"problems related to life-management difficulty\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/Z73 |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref> The condition is only further defined as being a \"state of [[emotional exhaustion|vital exhaustion]]\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/Z73.0 |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ICD-10 also contains a medical condition category of \"F43.8 Other reactions to severe stress\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/F43.8 |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref> (sometimes known as [[neurasthenia]]), which some (including the [[Swedish National Board of Health and Welfare]]) believe defines the more serious cases of burnout. Swedish sufferers of severe burnout are treated as having this medical condition.<ref name=\"Burnout: 35 years of research and p\"/> This category is in the same group as [[adjustment disorder]] and [[posttraumatic stress disorder]], other conditions caused by excessive stress that continue once the stressors have been removed.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse10/2019/en#/F43 |title = ICD-10 Version:2019}}</ref>\n\nA new version of the ICD, ICD-11, was released in June 2018, for first use in January 2022.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/18-06-2018-who-releases-new-international-classification-of-diseases-(icd-11) | title=WHO releases new International Classification of Diseases (ICD 11)}}</ref> It has an entry coded and titled \"QD85 Burn-out\". This describes the condition thusly:\n\n<blockquote>Burn-out is a syndrome conceptualized as resulting from chronic workplace stress that has not been successfully managed. It is characterized by three dimensions: 1) feelings of energy depletion or exhaustion; 2) increased mental distance from one\u2019s job, or feelings of negativism or cynicism related to one's job; and 3) reduced professional efficacy. Burn-out refers specifically to phenomena in the occupational context and should not be applied to describe experiences in other areas of life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://id.who.int/icd/entity/129180281 |title=QD85 Burn-out  |website=icd.who.int|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis condition is classified under \"Problems associated with employment or unemployment\" in the section on \"Factors influencing health status or contact with health services.\" The section is devoted to reasons other than recognized diseases or health conditions for which people contact health services.<ref name=WHO-2019/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://id.who.int/icd/entity/1249056269|title=24. Factors influencing health status or contact with health services |website=icd.who.int|access-date=2019-05-28|quote=Categories in this chapter are provided for occasions when circumstances other than a disease, injury or external cause classifiable elsewhere are recorded as \"diagnoses\" or \"problems.\" This can arise... When some circumstance or problem is present which influences the person's health status but is not in itself a current illness or injury. Such circumstance or problem may be elicited during population surveys, when the person may or may not be currently sick, or be recorded as additional information to be borne in mind when the person is receiving care for some illness or injury.}}</ref> In a statement made in May 2019, the WHO said \"Burn-out is included in the 11th Revision of the International Classification of Diseases (ICD-11) as an occupational phenomenon. It is not classified as a medical condition.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.who.int/mental_health/evidence/burn-out/en/ |title = WHO &#124; Burn-out an \"occupational phenomenon\": International Classification of Diseases}}</ref>\n\nThe ICD's browser and coding tool both attach the term \"caregiver burnout\" to category \"QF27 Difficulty or need for assistance at home and no other household member able to render care\".<ref>http://id.who.int/icd/entity/757911124</ref><ref>https://icd.who.int/ct11/icd11_mms/en/release and search for \"burnout\"</ref> This acknowledges that burnout can occur in this context.\n\nThe ICD-11 also has the medical condition \"6B4Y Other specified disorders specifically associated with stress\",<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://icd.who.int/browse11/l-m/en#/http%3a%2f%2fid.who.int%2ficd%2fentity%2f991786158%2fmms%2fother |title = ICD-11 - Mortality and Morbidity Statistics}}</ref> which is the equivalent of the ICD-10's F43.8.\n\nThe [[American Psychiatric Association]] says \"it is estimated that 2 out of 5 psychiatrists have professional burnout,\" and believes that \"addressing this problem has become one of the most pressing issues for medicine.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Well-being and Burnout |url=https://www.psychiatry.org/psychiatrists/practice/well-being-and-burnout |website=www.psychiatry.org}}</ref>\n\n=== Instruments ===\nIn 1981, Maslach and Jackson developed the first widely used instrument for assessing burnout, namely, the [[Maslach Burnout Inventory]] (MBI).<ref name=\"Maslach2\">{{cite journal|author1=Maslach, C.|author2=Jackson, S.E.|year=1981|title=The measurement of experienced burnout|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/96095aa76b740b97bd958019b93b4c0d9ada0fea|journal=Journal of Occupational Behavior|volume=2|issue=2|pages=99\u2013113|doi=10.1002/job.4030020205|via=}}</ref> Consistent with Maslach's conceptualization, the MBI operationalizes burnout as a three-dimensional syndrome consisting of emotional exhaustion, depersonalization, and reduced personal accomplishment.<ref name = \"Maslach2\"/><ref name = \"Maslach\"/> Other researchers have argued that burnout should be limited to fatigue and exhaustion.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Kristensen|first1 = T.S.|last2 = Borritz|first2 = M.|last3 = Villadsen|first3 = E.|last4 = Christensen|first4 = K.B.|year = 2005|title = The Copenhagen Burnout Inventory: A new tool for the assessment of burnout|url = |journal = Work & Stress|volume = 19|issue = 3|pages = 192\u2013207|doi = 10.1080/02678370500297720}}</ref> Exhaustion is considered to be burnout's core.<ref name=\"Maslach01\"/><ref>Schonfeld, I.S., Verkuilen, J. & Bianchi, R. (2019). An exploratory structural equation modelling bi-factor analytic approach to uncovering what burnout, depression, and anxiety scales measure. ''Psychological Assessment''. https://doi.org/10.1037/pas0000721</ref>\n\nThere are, however, other conceptualizations of burnout that differ from the conceptualization adopted by the WHO. Shirom and Melamed with their Shirom-Melamed Burnout Measure conceptualize burnout in terms of physical exhaustion, cognitive weariness, and emotional exhaustion;<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Shirom, A.|author2=Melamed, S.|year=2006|title=A comparison of the construct validity of two burnout measures in two groups of professionals|url=|journal=International Journal of Stress Management|volume=13|issue=2|pages=176\u2013200|doi=10.1037/1072-5245.13.2.176}},</ref><ref>Toker, S., Melamed, S., Berliner, S., Zeltser, D., & Shapira, I. (2012). Burnout and risk of coronary heart disease: A prospective study of 8838 employees. Psychosomatic Medicine, 74, 840\u2013847. https://doi.org/10.1097/PSY.0b013e31826c3174</ref> however, an examination of Shirom and Melamed's emotional exhaustion subscale indicates that the subscale looks more like a measure of Maslach's<ref name=\"Maslach01\">{{cite journal|last1 = Maslach|first1 = C.|last2 = Schaufeli|first2 = W. B.|last3 = Leiter|first3 = M. P.|editor = S. T. Fiske |editor2=D. L. Schacter |editor3=C. Zahn-Waxler|year = 2001|title = Job burnout|journal = Annual Review of Psychology|volume = 52|pages = 397\u2013422|doi = 10.1146/annurev.psych.52.1.397|pmid = 11148311|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5fc3eecc1afad1365bc8469ab5c39477e8c26146}}</ref> concept of depersonalization.<ref>Toker, S., Melamed, S., Berliner, S., Zeltser, D., & Shapira, I. (2012). Burnout and risk of coronary heart disease: A prospective study of 8838 employees. ''Psychosomatic Medicine, 74'', 840\u2013847</ref> Demerouti and Bakker (with their Oldenburg Burnout Inventory) conceptualize burnout in terms of exhaustion and disengagement.<ref>Demerouti, E., Bakker, A.B., Vardakou, I., & Kantas, A. (2003). The convergent validity of two burnout instruments: A multitrait-multimethod analysis. ''European Journal of Psychological Assessment, 19'', 12-23</ref> There are other conceptualizations as well that are embodied in these instruments: the Copenhagen Burnout Inventory,<ref name=\"Kristensen\">Kristensen, T.S.; Borritz, M.; Villadsen, E.; Christensen, K.B. (2005). \"The Copenhagen Burnout Inventory: A new tool for the assessment of burnout\". Work & Stress. 19 (3): 192\u2013207. doi:10.1080/02678370500297720</ref> the Hamburg Burnout Inventory,<ref name=\"Wurm\">Wurm, W., Vogel, K., Holl, A., Ebner, C., Bayer, D., M\u00f6rkl, S., \u2026 Hofmann, P. (2016). Depression-Burnout Overlap in Physicians. ''Plos One, 11'', e0149913.</ref> Malach-Pines's Burnout Measure,<ref>Malach-Pines, A. (2005). The Burnout Measure, Short Version. ''International Journal of Stress Management, 12''(1), 78\u201388.</ref> and more. Kristensen et al.<ref name=\"Kristensen\" /> and Malach-Pines (who also published as Pines)<ref>Pines, A. M. (1987). Marriage burnout. ''Psychotherapy in Private Practice,''\n5'', 31\u201344.''</ref> advanced the view that burnout can also occur in non-work roles such as that of spouse.\n\nThe ''Utrecht Work Engagement Scale'' (UWES), was released by Wilmar Schaufeli and Arnold Bakker in 1999. It measures vigour, dedication and absorption; positive counterparts to the values measured by the BMI.<ref>https://www.wilmarschaufeli.nl/publications/Schaufeli/Test%20Manuals/Test_manual_UWES_English.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2010, researchers from [[Mayo Clinic]] used portions of the MBI, along with other comprehensive assessments, to develop the [[Well-Being Index]], a brief nine-item self-assessment tool designed to measure burnout and other dimensions of distress in health care workers specifically.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dyrbye|first=Liselotte N.|last2=Szydlo|first2=Daniel W.|last3=Downing|first3=Steven M.|last4=Sloan|first4=Jeff A.|last5=Shanafelt|first5=Tait D.|date=2010-01-27|title=Development and preliminary psychometric properties of a well-being index for medical students|journal=BMC Medical Education|volume=10|issue=1|pages=8|doi=10.1186/1472-6920-10-8|issn=1472-6920|pmc=2823603|pmid=20105312}}</ref>\n\nThe core of all of these conceptualizations, including that of Freudenberger, is exhaustion. Alternatively, burnout is also now seen as involving the full array of [[Depression (mood)|depressive]] symptoms (e.g., low [[Mood (psychology)|mood]], [[Cognitive psychology|cognitive]] alterations, [[Sleep disorder|sleep disturbance]]).<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Bianchi, R.|author2=Schonfeld, I.S.|author3=Laurent, E.|year=2015|title=Burnout-depression overlap: A review|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1318&context=cc_pubs|journal=Clinical Psychology Review|volume=36|pages=28\u201341|doi=10.1016/j.cpr.2015.01.004|pmid=25638755|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bianchi | first1 = R. | last2 = Schonfeld | first2 = I. S. | last3 = Vandel | first3 = P. | last4 = Laurent | first4 = E. | year = 2017 | title = On the depressive nature of the \"burnout syndrome\": A clarification | url = https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1537&context=gc_pubs| journal = European Psychiatry | volume = 41 | issue = | pages = 109\u2013110 | doi = 10.1016/j.eurpsy.2016.10.008 | pmid = 28135592 }}</ref> Marked differences in understanding of what constitutes burnout have highlighted the need for [[Definition#In medicine|consensus definition]].<ref name=Rotenstein2018/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Heinemann | first1 = L.V. | last2 = Heinemann | first2 = T. | year = 2017 | title = Burnout Research: Emergence and Scientific Investigation of a Contested Diagnosis | journal = Sage Open | volume = | issue = | pages = | doi = 10.1177/2158244017697154 | pmid = | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\n=== Subtypes ===\nIn 1991, Barry A. Farber proposed that there are three types of burnout:\n* \"wearout\" and \"brown-out\", where someone gives up having had too much stress and/or too little reward\n* \"classic/frenetic burnout\", where someone works harder and harder, trying to resolve the stressful situation and/or seek suitable reward for their work\n* \"underchallenged burnout\", where someone has low stress, but the work is unrewarding.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Farber |first1=Barry A. |title=Crisis in education: stress and burnout in the American teacher |date=1991 |publisher=Jossey-Bass |location=San Francisco}}</ref>\n\n====Caregiver burnout====\n{{Main|Caregiver stress}}\n\nBodies such as the US government's [[Centres for Disease Control and Prevention]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Dealing With Diabetes Burnout |url=https://www.cdc.gov/diabetes/library/spotlights/diabetes-burnout.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |language=en-us |date=12 August 2019}}</ref> the [[American Diabetes Association]]<ref>{{cite book |title=Diabetes burnout : what to do when you can't take it anymore |publisher=American Diabetes Association |isbn=1580400337 |date=1999}}</ref> and ''Diabetes Singapore''<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Diabetes Burnout? |url=https://www.moneyfm893.sg/whats-on/what-is-diabetes-burnout/ |website=MONEY FM 89.3 |date=5 December 2019}}</ref> identify and promote the phenomenon of \"diabetes burnout\". This relates to the self-care of people with diabetes, particularly those with type-2 diabetes. \"Diabetes burnout speaks to the physical and emotional exhaustion that people with diabetes experience when they have to deal with caring for themselves on a day-to-day basis. When you have to do so many things to stay in control then it does take a toll on your emotions... Once they get frustrated, some of them give up and stop (maintaining) a healthy diet, taking their medications regularly, going for exercises and this will result in poor diabetes control.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Diabetes Burnout? |url=https://www.moneyfm893.sg/whats-on/what-is-diabetes-burnout/ |website=MONEY FM 89.3 |date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Autistic burnout====\n\"Autistic burnout\" is a term used to describe burnout when it occurs in people with [[Autistic Spectrum Disorder]] (ASD).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://aaspire.org/projects/autistic-burnout/pilot-study-on-autistic-burnout-and-suicidal-behavior/ |title = Pilot study on autistic burnout and suicidal behavior \u2013 AASPIRE}}</ref> In this population, in addition to the typical symptoms it can cause \"autistic regression\", an increase of autistic symptoms. It is \"regression\" in the sense that the afflicted has typically had a similarly high level of symptoms in the distant past, and the burnout is perceived to be regressing them to this earlier state. Such burnout sometimes leads to permanent disability or suicidal behaviour. It need not be caused by workplace stress, but can also be caused by the stress of social interaction or other sources.<ref>https://www.seattlechildrens.org/globalassets/documents/health-and-safety/autism/autism_206_raymaker_slides.pdf, https://www.facebook.com/seattlechildrens/videos/vl.948687718589668/380037906042266/?type=1</ref><ref>https://www.goodtherapy/blog/autistic-burnout-an-often-misunderstood-element-of-autism-080620197</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1108/AIA-10-2018-0042| title=Helping autistic women thrive| year=2019| last1=Zener| first1=Dori| journal=Advances in Autism| volume=5| issue=3| pages=143\u2013156}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1186/s13229-020-0313-1|pmid = 31969977|title = Behavioral effects of multiple-dose oxytocin treatment in autism: A randomized, placebo-controlled trial with long-term follow-up|year = 2020|last1 = Bernaerts|first1 = Sylvie|last2 = Boets|first2 = Bart|last3 = Bosmans|first3 = Guy|last4 = Steyaert|first4 = Jean|last5 = Alaerts|first5 = Kaat|journal = Molecular Autism|volume = 11|pages = 6|pmc = 6964112}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DZwfujkNBGk</ref> [[Spoon theory]] is sometimes used to understand people in this situation.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Distinction Between Avoidance Behaviours, Social Fatigue and Burn out |url=http://functionallegacymindset.com.au/a-distinction-between-avoidance-behaviours-social-fatigue-and-burn-out/ |website=Functional Legacy Mindset}}</ref>\n\n=== Relationship with other conditions ===\nA growing body of evidence suggests that burnout is etiologically, clinically, and [[nosology|nosologically]] similar to [[Major depressive disorder|depression]].<ref>Bianchi, E., Schonfeld, I.S., & Laurent, E. (2018). Burnout syndrome and depression. Y.-K. Kim (Ed.), ''Understanding depression: Volume 2. Clinical manifestations, diagnosis and treatment'' (pp.187-202). Singapore: Springer. doi:10.1007/978-981-10-6577-4_14</ref><ref name = \"Ahola\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ahola | first1 = K. | last2 = Hakanen | first2 = J. | last3 = Perhoniemi | first3 = R. | last4 = Mutanen | first4 = P. | year = 2014 | title = Relationship between burnout and depressive symptoms: A study using the person-centred approach | url = | journal = Burnout Research | volume = 1 | issue = 1| pages = 29\u201337 | doi=10.1016/j.burn.2014.03.003| doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|author1=Bianchi, R.|author2=Laurent, E.|year=2015|title=Emotional information processing in depression and burnout: An eye-tracking study|url=|journal=European Archives of Psychiatry and Clinical Neuroscience|volume=265|issue=1|pages=27\u201334|doi=10.1007/s00406-014-0549-x|pmid=25297694}}</ref><ref name=\"Bianchi, R. 2014\">{{cite journal | last1 = Bianchi | first1 = R. | last2 = Schonfeld | first2 = I. S. | last3 = Laurent | first3 = E. | year = 2014 | title = Is burnout a depressive disorder? A re-examination with special focus on atypical depression | url = https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1316&context=cc_pubs| journal = International Journal of Stress Management | volume = 21 | issue = 4 | pages = 307\u2013324 | doi=10.1037/a0037906}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite journal|author1=Bianchi, R.|author2=Schonfeld, I. S.|author3=Laurent, E.|year=2014|title=Is burnout separable from depression in cluster analysis? A longitudinal study|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cc_pubs/323|journal=Social Psychiatry and Psychiatric Epidemiology|volume=50|issue=6|pages=1005\u20131111|doi=10.1007/s00127-014-0996-8|pmid=25527209|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Hintsa-et-al\">{{cite journal|author1=Hintsa, T.|author2=Elovainio, M.|author3=Jokela, M.|author4=Ahola, K.|author5=Virtanen, M.|author6=Pirkola, S.|year=2016|title=Is there an independent association between burnout and increased allostatic load? Testing the contribution of psychological distress and depression|url=|journal=Journal of Health Psychology|volume=16|issue=8|pages=576\u2013586|doi=10.1177/1359105314559619|pmid=25476575|hdl=10138/224473|hdl-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"Schonfeld\">{{cite journal|author1=Schonfeld, I.S.|author2=Bianchi, R.|year=2016|title=Burnout and depression: Two entities or one|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/gc_pubs/257|journal=Journal of Clinical Psychology|volume=72|issue=1|pages=22\u201337|doi=10.1002/jclp.22229|pmid=26451877|via=}}</ref> In a study that directly compared depressive symptoms in burned out workers and clinically depressed patients, no diagnostically significant differences were found between the two groups; burned out workers reported as many depressive symptoms as clinically depressed patients.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bianchi | first1 = R. | last2 = Boffy | first2 = C. | last3 = Hingray | first3 = C. | last4 = Truchot | first4 = D. | last5 = Laurent | first5 = E. | year = 2013 | title = Comparative symptomatology of burnout and depression | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7539920d9b6d84b27ad305101765447dd07390e6| journal = Journal of Health Psychology | volume = 18 | issue = 6| pages = 782\u2013787 | doi=10.1177/1359105313481079| pmid = 23520355 }}</ref> Moreover, a study by Bianchi, Schonfeld, and Laurent (2014) showed that about 90% of workers with full-blown burnout meet diagnostic criteria for depression.<ref name=\"Bianchi, R. 2014\"/> The view that burnout is a form of depression has found support in several recent studies.<ref name = \"Ahola\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"Hintsa-et-al\"/><ref name=\"Schonfeld\"/><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Wurm, W.|author2=Vogel, K.|author3=Holl, A.|author4=Ebner, C.|author5=Bayer, D.|author6=M\u00f6rkl, S.|author7=Hofmann, P.|year=2016|title=Depression-burnout overlap in physicians|url=|journal=PLOS One|volume=11|issue=e0149913|pages=e0149913|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1149913W|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0149913|pmc=4773131|pmid=26930395}}</ref> Some authors have recommended that the nosological concept of burnout be revised or even abandoned entirely given that it is not a distinct disorder and that there is no agreement on burnout diagnostic criteria.<ref name=Rotenstein2018>{{Cite journal|last=Rotenstein|first=Lisa S.|last2=Torre|first2=Matthew|last3=Ramos|first3=Marco A.|last4=Rosales|first4=Rachael C.|last5=Guille|first5=Constance|last6=Sen|first6=Srijan|last7=Mata|first7=Douglas A.|date=September 18, 2018|title=Prevalence of Burnout Among Physicians: A Systematic Review|journal=JAMA|volume=320|issue=11|pages=1131\u20131150|doi=10.1001/jama.2018.12777|issn=1538-3598|pmc=6233645|pmid=30326495}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schwenk|first=Thomas L.|last2=Gold|first2=Katherine J.|date=September 18, 2018|title=Physician Burnout-A Serious Symptom, But of What?|journal=JAMA|volume=320|issue=11|pages=1109\u20131110|doi=10.1001/jama.2018.11703|issn=1538-3598|pmid=30422283}}</ref>\n\n[[Postpartum depression]] is a form of depression recognised by the DSM that differs mainly from major depressive disorder in that it has a specific trigger.\n\nLiu and van Liew wrote that \"the term burnout is used so frequently that it has lost much of its original meaning. As originally used, burnout meant a mild degree of stress-induced unhappiness. The solutions ranged from a vacation to a sabbatical. Ultimately, it was used to describe everything from fatigue to a major depression and now seems to have become an alternative word for depression, but with a less serious significance\" (p.&nbsp;434).<ref name=\"Liu, P.M. 2003 pp. 433-457\"/> They also argue that burning out can trigger four distinct kinds of depression, each with their own recommended treatment. These are [[adjustment disorder]] with depressed mood, [[major depressive disorder]], [[dysthymia]], and [[bipolar disorder]].\n\nTamar Kakiashvili et al. however argued that while there are significant overlaps in symptoms between burnout and major depressive disorder (aka \"depression\"), there is much endocrine evidence to suggest that the biological basis of burnout is vastly different to typical depression. They argued that antidepressants should not be used by people with burnout as they make the underlying [[hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis]] dysfunction worse.<ref name=\"The medical perspective on burnout\">{{cite journal |last1=Kakiashvili |first1=Tamar |title=The medical perspective on burnout |journal=International Journal of Occupational Medicine and Environmental Health |date=March 2013 |volume=23 |issue=3 |pages=401\u2013412 |doi=10.2478/s13382-013-0093-3 |pmid=24018996 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Test !! [[Major depressive disorder]] !! [[Atypical depression]] !! [[PTSD]] !! [[Chronic Fatigue Syndrome]] !! Burnout\n|-\n| [[Cortisol awakening response]] || \u2191 || \u2193 <ref>{{cite journal |last1=O\u2019Keane |first1=Veronica |last2=Frodl |first2=Thomas |last3=Dinan |first3=Timothy G. |title=A review of Atypical depression in relation to the course of depression and changes in HPA axis organization |journal=Psychoneuroendocrinology |date=October 2012 |volume=37 |issue=10 |pages=1589\u20131599 |doi=10.1016/j.psyneuen.2012.03.009|pmid=22497986 }}</ref> || \u2193 || \u2193 <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nater |first1=Urs M. |last2=Maloney |first2=Elizabeth |last3=Boneva |first3=Roumiana S. |last4=Gurbaxani |first4=Brian M. |last5=Lin |first5=Jin-Mann |last6=Jones |first6=James F. |last7=Reeves |first7=William C. |last8=Heim |first8=Christine |title=Attenuated Morning Salivary Cortisol Concentrations in a Population-Based Study of Persons with Chronic Fatigue Syndrome and Well Controls |journal=The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology & Metabolism |date=March 2008 |volume=93 |issue=3 |pages=703\u2013709 |doi=10.1210/jc.2007-1747|pmid=18160468 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Papadopoulos |first1=Andrew S. |last2=Cleare |first2=Anthony J. |title=Hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis dysfunction in chronic fatigue syndrome |journal=Nature Reviews Endocrinology |date=January 2012 |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=22\u201332 |doi=10.1038/nrendo.2011.153 |pmid=21946893 |language=en |issn=1759-5037}}</ref>|| - or \u2193 \n|-\n| [[Adrenocorticotropic hormone]] (ACTH) || \u2191 ||  ||   || - <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scott |first1=Lucinda V. |last2=Medbak |first2=Sami |last3=Dinan |first3=Timothy G. |title=The low dose ACTH test in chronic fatigue syndrome and in health |journal=Clinical Endocrinology |date=4 January 2002 |volume=48 |issue=6 |pages=733\u2013737 |doi=10.1046/j.1365-2265.1998.00418.x |pmid=9713562 }}</ref> || - or \u2193 \n|-\n| [[Dehydroepiandrosterone sulphate]] (DHEA-S)|| \u2193 ||  ||\u2191 or \u2193 || \u2193 <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kuratsune |first1=H |last2=Yamaguti |first2=K |last3=Sawada |first3=M |last4=Kodate |first4=S |last5=Machii |first5=T |last6=Kanakura |first6=Y |last7=Kitani |first7=T |title=Dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate deficiency in chronic fatigue syndrome. |journal=International Journal of Molecular Medicine |date=1 January 1998 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=143\u20136 |doi=10.3892/ijmm.1.1.143 |pmid=9852212 }}</ref> || \u2191 \n|}<ref name=\"The medical perspective on burnout\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=MOMMERSTEEG |first1=P |last2=HEIJNEN |first2=C |last3=VERBRAAK |first3=M |last4=VANDOORNEN |first4=L |title=Clinical burnout is not reflected in the cortisol awakening response, the day-curve or the response to a low-dose dexamethasone suppression test |journal=Psychoneuroendocrinology |date=February 2006 |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=216\u2013225 |doi=10.1016/j.psyneuen.2005.07.003 |pmid=16150550 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sj\u00f6rs |first1=Anna |last2=Ljung |first2=Thomas |last3=Jonsdottir |first3=Ingibj\u00f6rg H |title=Long-term follow-up of cortisol awakening response in patients treated for stress-related exhaustion |journal=BMJ Open |date=10 July 2012 |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=e001091 |doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2012-001091 |pmid=22786949 |pmc=3400075 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=de Vente |first1=Wieke |last2=van Amsterdam |first2=Jan G. C. |last3=Olff |first3=Miranda |last4=Kamphuis |first4=Jan H. |last5=Emmelkamp |first5=Paul M. G. |title=Burnout Is Associated with Reduced Parasympathetic Activity and Reduced HPA Axis Responsiveness, Predominantly in Males |journal=BioMed Research International |date=October 2015 |url=https://www.hindawi.com/journals/bmri/2015/431725/ |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sonnentag |first1=Sabine |title=Burnout and functioning of the hypothalamus-pituitary-axis\u2014there are no simple answers |journal=Scandinavian Journal of Work, Environment & Health |date=2006 |volume=32 |issue=5 |pages=333\u2013337 |doi=10.5271/sjweh.1028 |pmid=17091200 |issn=0355-3140|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Oosterholt |first1=Bart G. |last2=Maes |first2=Joseph H.R. |last3=Van der Linden |first3=Dimitri |last4=Verbraak |first4=Marc J.P.M. |last5=Kompier |first5=Michiel A.J. |title=Burnout and cortisol: Evidence for a lower cortisol awakening response in both clinical and non-clinical burnout |journal=Journal of Psychosomatic Research |date=May 2015 |volume=78 |issue=5 |pages=445\u2013451 |doi=10.1016/j.jpsychores.2014.11.003|pmid=25433974 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Onen Sert\u00f6z |first1=Ozen |last2=Binbay |first2=I. Tolga |last3=Elbi Mete |first3=Hayriye |title=[The neurobiology of burnout: the hypothalamus-pituitary-adrenal gland axis and other findings] |journal=Turk Psikiyatri Dergisi = Turkish Journal of Psychiatry |date=2008 |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=318\u2013328 |issn=1300-2163|pmid=18791885 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Verhaeghe |first1=J. |last2=Van Den Eede |first2=F. |last3=Van Den Ameele |first3=H. |last4=Sabbe |first4=B. G. C. |title=[Neuro-endocrine correlates of burnout] |journal=Tijdschrift voor Psychiatrie |date=2012 |volume=54 |issue=6 |pages=517\u2013526 |issn=0303-7339|pmid=22753184 }}</ref>\n\nRobert Finlay-Jones made the case that what is generally considered \"depression\" is actually two separate conditions. In addition to the typical [[melancholic]] depression, there is a multi-millennia-old defined syndrome called \"[[acedia]]\" (which can be considered a [[phlegmatic]] depression). Those suffering from acedia experience some fear and sadness as the depressed do, but much less of it. Those suffering from acedia are more likely to have trouble doing anything useful than standard depression. But the main defining feature of acedia is an impairment of the senses. (This symptom is often ascribed to depression.<ref>https://www.discovermagazine.com/mind/how-depression-dulls-the-world-literally</ref>) Finlay-Jones believed a lack of work satisfaction could lead to both depression and acedia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Finlay-Jones |first1=Robert |title=Disgust with Life in General |journal=Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry |date=June 1983 |volume=17 |issue=2 |pages=149\u2013152 |doi=10.3109/00048678309159998 |pmid=6578787 }}</ref>\n\nIt has also been hypothesised that [[chronic fatigue syndrome]] is caused by burnout.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jameson |first1=David |title=Persistent burnout theory of chronic fatigue syndrome |date=27 February 2015 |url=https://peerj.com/preprints/860v1/ |publisher=PeerJ PrePrints |doi=10.7287/peerj.preprints.860v1 |language=en|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Van Houdenhove |first1=Boudewijn |last2=Van Den Eede |first2=Filip |last3=Luyten |first3=Patrick |title=Does hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis hypofunction in chronic fatigue syndrome reflect a 'crash' in the stress system? |journal=Medical Hypotheses |date=June 2009 |volume=72 |issue=6 |pages=701\u2013705 |doi=10.1016/j.mehy.2008.11.044 |pmid=19237251 |issn=1532-2777}}</ref> It is suggested that the \"burning out\" of the body's stress symptom (by any of a wide range of causes) can lead to chronic fatigue. \"Occupational burnout\" is known for its exhausting effect on sufferers. [[Overtraining]] syndrome, a similar but lesser exhausting condition to CFS has been conceptualised as [[adjustment disorder]], a common diagnosis for those burnt out.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=Clive Martin |last2=Tenenbaum |first2=Gershon |title=Adjustment Disorder: a new way of conceptualizing the overtraining syndrome |journal=International Review of Sport and Exercise Psychology |date=September 2009 |volume=2 |issue=2 |pages=181\u2013197 |doi=10.1080/17509840903110962 }}</ref>\n\n==Risk factors==\nEvidence suggests that the etiology of burnout is multifactorial, with dispositional factors playing an important, long-overlooked role.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Alarcon|first1 = G.|last2 = Eschleman|first2 = K. J.|last3 = Bowling|first3 = N. A.|year = 2009|title = Relationships between personality variables and burnout: A meta-analysis|url = |journal = Work & Stress|volume = 23|issue = 3|pages = 244\u2013263|doi = 10.1080/02678370903282600}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Swider|first1 = B. W.|last2 = Zimmerman|first2 = R. D.|year = 2010|title = Born to burnout: A meta-analytic path model of personality, job burnout, and work outcomes|url = |journal = Journal of Vocational Behavior|volume = 76|issue = 3|pages = 487\u2013506|doi = 10.1016/j.jvb.2010.01.003}}</ref> Cognitive dispositional factors implicated in depression have also been found to be implicated in burnout.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Bianchi, R.|author2=Schonfeld, I.S.|year=2016|title=Burnout is associated with a depressive cognitive style|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cc_pubs/318|journal=Personality and Individual Differences|volume=100|pages=1\u20135|doi=10.1016/j.paid.2016.01.008|via=}}</ref> One cause of burnout includes [[stressor]]s that a person is unable to cope with fully.<ref>Mustafa, O.M. (2015). Health behaviors and personality in burnout: A third dimension. ''Medical Education Online, 20'', doi:10.3402/meo.v20.28187. [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.3402/meo.v20.28187]</ref>\n\nBurnout is thought to occur when a mismatch is present between the nature of the job and the job the person is actually doing. A common indication of this mismatch is work overload, which sometimes involves a worker who survives a round of layoffs, but after the layoffs the worker finds that he or she is doing too much with too few resources. Overload may occur in the context of downsizing, which often does not narrow an organization's goals, but requires fewer employees to meet those goals.<ref name=\"Maslach972\">{{cite book|last=Maslach, C.|title=The Truth About Burnout: How Organizations Cause Personal Stress and What to Do About It|last2=Leiter, M.P.|publisher=Jossey-Bass|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[job demands-resources model]] has implications for burnout, as measured by the Oldenburg Burnout Inventory (OLBI). Physical and psychological job demands were concurrently associated with the exhaustion, as measured by the OLBI.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Demerouti|first1=Evangelia|last2=Bakker|first2=Arnold B.|last3=Nachreiner|first3=Friedhelm|last4=Schaufeli|first4=Wilmar B.|title=The job demands-resources model of burnout.|journal=Journal of Applied Psychology|date=2001|volume=86|issue=3|pages=499\u2013512|doi=10.1037/0021-9010.86.3.499}}</ref> Lack of job resources was associated with the disengagement component of the OLBI.\n\nMaslach, Schaufeli and Leiter identified six risk factors for burnout: mismatch in workload, mismatch in control, lack of appropriate awards, loss of a sense of positive connection with others in the workplace, perceived lack of fairness, and conflict between values.<ref name=\"Maslach01\"/>\n\n==Effects==\nSome research indicates that burnout is associated with reduced [[job performance]], coronary [[heart disease]],<ref>{{cite journal|author=Toker, S.|last2=Melamed, S.|last3=Berliner, S.|last4=Zeltser, D.|last5=Shapira, I.|year=2012|title=Burnout and risk of coronary heart disease: a prospective study of 8838 employees|url=|journal=Psychosomatic Medicine|volume=74|issue=8|pages=840\u2013847|doi=10.1097/PSY.0b013e31826c3174|pmid=23006431}}</ref> and [[mental health]] problems. Examples of emotional symptoms of occupational burnout include a lack of interest in the work being done, a decrease in work performance levels, feelings of helplessness, and trouble sleeping.<ref name=\"Cengage Learning\">{{cite book|last1=Aamodt|first1=Michael|title=Industrial/organizational psychology : an applied approach|date=2016|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-11842-3|edition=8th|location=Boston, MA|page=563}}</ref> With regard to mental health problems, research on dentists<ref name = \"Ahola\"/> and physicians<ref name = 'Wurm'/> suggests that what is meant by burnout is a depressive syndrome. Thus reduced job performance and cardiovascular risk could be related to burnout because of burnout's tie to depression. Behavioral signs of occupational burnout are demonstrated through cynicism within work relationships, such as coworkers, clients, and the organization.\n\nOther effects of burnout can manifest as lowered energy and productivity levels, with workers observed to be consistently late for work and feeling a sense of dread upon arriving. They can suffer decreased concentration, forgetfulness, increased frustration, or feelings of being overwhelmed. They may complain and feel negative, or feel apathetic and believe they have little impact on their coworkers and environment.<ref name=\"Cengage Learning\"/> Occupational burnout is also associated with absences, time missed from work, and thoughts of quitting.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite journal | last1 = Elliott | first1 = T. | last2 = Shewchuk | first2 = R. | last3 = Hagglund | first3 = K. | last4 = Rybarczyk | first4 = B. | last5 = Harkins | first5 = S. | year = 1996 | title = Occupational burnout, tolerance for stress, and coping among nurses in rehabilitation units | url = | journal = Rehabilitation Psychology | volume = 41 | issue = 4| pages = 267\u2013284 | doi=10.1037/0090-5550.41.4.267}}</ref>\n\nChronic burnout is also associated with cognitive impairments such as [[memory]] and [[attention]].<ref>{{cite journal|last = Sandstrom|first = A|author2 = Rhodin IN|author3 = Lundberg M|author4 = Olsson T|author5 = Nyberg L.|title = Impaired cognitive performance in patients with chronic burnout syndrome.|journal = Biological Psychology|year = 2005|volume = 69|issue = 3|pages = 271\u2013279|doi = 10.1016/j.biopsycho.2004.08.003|pmid = 15925030}}</ref> (See also [[Effects of stress on memory]].)\n\nThere is a growing amount of research suggesting that burnout can manifest differently between genders, with greater incidence of depersonalisation amongst men and higher emotional exhaustion among women.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Houkes|first=Inge|last2=Winants|first2=Yvonne|last3=Twellaar|first3=Mascha|last4=Verdonk|first4=Petra|date=2011-04-18|title=Development of burnout over time and the causal order of the three dimensions of burnout among male and female GPs. A three-wave panel study|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=Development+of+burnout+over+time+and+the+causal+order+of+the+three+dimensions+of+burnout+among+male+and+female+GPs.|journal=BMC Public Health|volume=11|pages=240|doi=10.1186/1471-2458-11-240|issn=1471-2458|pmc=3101180|pmid=21501467}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e-surgery.com/burnout-the-mens-health-crisis-we-arent-talking-about/|title=Burnout: The Men's Health Crisis We Aren't Talking About|last=Caufield|first=Madeleine|website=e-Surgery|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==Treatment and prevention==\nHealth condition treatment and prevention methods are often classified as \"primary prevention\" (stopping the condition occurring), \"secondary prevention\" (removing the condition that has occurred) and \"tertiary prevention\" (helping people live with the condition).\n\n===Primary prevention===\nMaslach believes that the only way to truly prevent burnout is through a combination of organizational change and education for the individual.<ref name=\"Maslach972\"/>\n\nMaslach and Leiter postulated that burnout occurs when there is a disconnection between the organization and the individual with regard to what they called the six areas of worklife: workload, control, reward, community, fairness, and values.<ref name=\"Maslach01\"/> Resolving these discrepancies requires integrated action on the part of both the individual and the organization.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" /> With regard to workload, assuring that a worker has adequate resources to meet demands as well as ensuring a satisfactory [[work\u2013life balance]] could help revitalize employees' energy.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" /> With regard to values, clearly stated ethical organizational values are important for ensuring employee commitment.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" /> Supportive leadership and relationships with colleagues are also helpful.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" />\n\nOne approach for addressing these discrepancies focuses specifically on the fairness area. In one study employees met weekly to discuss and attempt to resolve perceived inequities in their job.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = van Dierendonck|first1 = D.|last2 = Schaufeli|first2 = W. B.|last3 = Buunk|first3 = B. P.|year = 1998|title = The evaluation of an individual burnout intervention program: the role of in- equity and social support|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/bfd953e2f5dd6d311fe74f720f17ac9956996b11|journal = J. Appl. Psychol.|volume = 83|issue = 3|pages = 392\u2013407|doi = 10.1037/0021-9010.83.3.392}}</ref> The intervention was associated with decreases in exhaustion over time but not cynicism or inefficacy, suggesting that a broader approach is required.<ref name=\"Maslach01\" />\n\nH\u00e4tinen et al. suggest \"improving job-person fit by focusing attention on the relationship between the person and the job situation, rather than either of these in isolation, seems to be the most promising way of dealing with burnout.\".<ref>https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/9e3c/708f34fa9f158f842a3fc74448ea0c65d2c7.pdf?_ga=2.12703093.333517712.1583537646-253097619.1583537646</ref> They also note that \"at the individual level, cognitive-behavioural strategies have the best potential for success.\"\n\nBurnout prevention programs have traditionally focused on [[cognitive-behavioral therapy]] (CBT), [[cognitive restructuring]], didactic [[stress management]], and relaxation. CBT, [[relaxation technique]]s (including physical techniques and mental techniques), and schedule changes are the best-supported techniques for reducing or preventing burnout in a health-care setting. Mindfulness therapy has been shown to be an effective preventative for occupational burnout in medical practitioners.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scheepers|first=Ren\u00e9e A.|last2=Emke|first2=Helga|last3=Epstein|first3=Ronald M.|last4=Lombarts|first4=Kiki M. J. M. H.|date=2019-12-22|title=The impact of mindfulness-based interventions on doctors' well-being and performance: A systematic review|journal=Medical Education|volume=54|issue=2|pages=138\u2013149|doi=10.1111/medu.14020|issn=1365-2923|pmid=31868262|pmc=7003865}}</ref> Combining both organizational and individual-level activities may be the most beneficial approach to reducing symptoms. A Cochrane review, however, reported that evidence for the efficacy of CBT in healthcare workers is of low quality, indicating that it is no better than alternative interventions.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\"/>\n\nFor the purpose of preventing occupational burnout, various stress management interventions have been shown to help improve employee health and well-being in the workplace and lower stress levels. Training employees in ways to manage stress in the workplace have also been shown to be effective in preventing burnout.<ref>{{cite book|author=William D. McLaurine|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uRU3tG29VfUC&lpg=PA92&dq=job%20burnout%20prevention&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A correlational study of job burnout and organizational commitment among correctional officers|publisher= Capella University. School of Psychology|page= 92|isbn=9780549438144}}</ref> One study suggests that social-cognitive processes such as [[organizational commitment|commitment]] to work, [[self-efficacy]], learned resourcefulness, and [[hope]] may insulate individuals from experiencing occupational burnout.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Increasing a worker's [[Job control (workplace)|control over his or her job]] is another intervention has been shown to help counteract exhaustion and [[cynicism (contemporary)|cynicism]] in the workplace.<ref name=\"H\u00e4tinen-2007\" />\n\nAdditional prevention methods include: starting the day with a relaxing ritual; yoga; adopting healthy eating, exercising, and sleeping habits; setting boundaries; taking breaks from technology; nourishing one's creative side, and learning how to manage stress.<ref name=\"pat\">{{cite web |url=http://health.usnews.com/health-care/for-better/articles/2017-02-27/politically-active-4-tips-for-incorporating-self-care |title=Politically Active? 4 Tips for Incorporating Self-Care, US News |date=27 February 2017 |work=US News |accessdate=5 March 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.helpguide.org/mental/stress_signs.htm|title=Stress Symptoms, Signs, & Causes: The Effects of Stress Overload and What You Can Do About It|last=Smith, M.|last2=Segal, R.|year=2014|website=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927114835/http://www.helpguide.org/mental/stress_signs.htm|archivedate=27 September 2014|accessdate=31 March 2014|last3=Segal, J.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grensman|first=Astrid|last2=Acharya|first2=Bikash Dev|last3=W\u00e4ndell|first3=Per|last4=Nilsson|first4=Gunnar H.|last5=Falkenberg|first5=Torkel|last6=Sundin|first6=\u00d6rjan|last7=Werner|first7=Sigbritt|date=2018-03-06|title=Effect of traditional yoga, mindfulness\u2013based cognitive therapy, and cognitive behavioral therapy, on health related quality of life: a randomized controlled trial on patients on sick leave because of burnout|journal=BMC Complementary and Alternative Medicine|volume=18|issue=1|pages=80|doi=10.1186/s12906-018-2141-9|issn=1472-6882|pmc=5839058|pmid=29510704}}</ref>\n\nBarry A. Farber suggests strategies like setting more achievable goals, focusing on the value of the work, and finding better ways of doing the job, can all be helpful ways of helping the stressed. People who don't mind the stress but want more reward can benefit from reassessing their [[work-life balance]] and implementing stress reduction techniques like meditation and exercise. Others with low stress, but are underwhelmed and bored with work, can benefit from seeking greater challenge.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Farber |first1=Barry A. |title=Tailoring Treatment Strategies for Different Types of Burnout |journal=Journal of Clinical Psychology |date=May 2000 |volume=56 |issue=5|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1097-4679(200005)56:5<675::AID-JCLP8>3.0.CO;2-D }}</ref>\n\nThijs Launspach is his 2019 book \"Werken met Millennials\" (\"Working with [[Millennial]]s\") argues that that society is making ever higher demands, and that this is an important consideration when addressing prevention. The book particularly focuses on why so many Milliennials are at home suffering from burnout.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thijslaunspach.nl/ | title=Thijs Launspach &#124; psycholoog, schrijver, advies}}</ref>\n\nSee also [[Occupational stress]], [[Caregiver stress]], [[Stress management]].\n\n===Secondary and tertiary prevention (aka treatment)===\nH\u00e4tinen et al. list a number of common treatments, including [[medicine|treatment of any outstanding medical conditions]], [[stress management]], [[time management]], [[management of depression|depression treatment]], [[psychotherapies]], ergonomic improvement and other physiological and [[occupational therapy]], [[physical exercise]] and [[relaxation]]. They have found that is more effective to have a greater focus on \"group discussions on work related issues\", and discussion about \"work and private life interface\" and other personal needs with psychologists and workplace representatives.<ref name=\"H\u00e4tinen-2007\">{{cite journal | last1 = H\u00e4tinen | first1 = M. | last2 = Kinnunen | first2 = U. | last3 = Pekkonen | first3 = M. | last4 = Kalimo | first4 = R. | year = 2007 | title = Comparing two burnout interventions: Perceived job control mediates decreases in burnout | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/9e3c708f34fa9f158f842a3fc74448ea0c65d2c7| journal = International Journal of Stress Management | volume = 14 | issue = 3| pages = 227\u2013248 | doi=10.1037/1072-5245.14.3.227}}</ref>\n\nJac JL van der Klink and Frank JH van Dijk suggest [[stress inoculation training]], [[cognitive restructuring]], [[systematic desensitisation|graded activity]] and \"time contingency\" (progressing based on a timeline rather than patient's comfort) are effective methods of treatment.<ref name=\"jstor.org\"/>\n\nKakiashvili et al. say that \"medical treatment of burnout is mostly symptomatic: it involves measures to prevent and treat the symptoms.\" They say the use of [[anxiolytics]] and [[sedatives]] to treat burnout related stress is effective, but does nothing to change the sources of stress. They say the poor sleep often caused by burnout (and the subsequent fatigue) is best treated with [[hypnotics]] and CBT (within which they include \"sleep hygiene, education, relaxation training, stimulus control, and cognitive therapy\"). They advise against the use of [[antidepressants]] as they worsen the [[hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis]] dysfunction at the core of burnout. They also believe \"vitamins and minerals are crucial in addressing adrenal and HPA axis dysfunction\", noting the importance of specific nutrients.<ref name=\"The medical perspective on burnout\"/>\n\n[[Light therapy]] (similar to that used for [[Seasonal Affective Disorder]]) may be effective.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meesters |first1=Y. |title=Burnout and light treatment |journal=Stress & Health |date=February 2010 |volume=26 |issue=1|pages=13\u201320 |doi=10.1002/smi.1250 }}</ref>\n\nBurnout also often causes a decline in the ability to update information in working memory. This is not easily treated with CBT.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Oosterholt |first1=Bart G |title=Burned out cognition \u2014 cognitive functioning of burnout patients before and after a period with psychological treatment |journal=Scandinavian Journal of Work, Environment & Health |date=July 2012 |volume=38 |issue=4 |pages=358\u2013369 |jstor=41508903 |doi=10.5271/sjweh.3256 |pmid=22025205 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nOne reason it is difficult to treat the three standard symptoms of burnout (exhaustion, cynicism, and inefficacy), is because they respond to the same preventive or treatment activities in different ways.<ref name=\"H\u00e4tinen-2007\"/>\n\nExhaustion is more easily treated than cynicism and professional inefficacy, which tend to be more resistant to treatment. Research suggests that intervention actually may worsen the professional efficacy of a person who originally exhibited low professional efficacy.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Van Dierendonck | first1 = D. | last2 = Schaufeli | first2 = W. B. | last3 = Buunk | first3 = B. P. | year = 1998 | title = The evaluation of an individual burnout intervention program: The role of inequity and social support | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/bfd953e2f5dd6d311fe74f720f17ac9956996b11| journal = Journal of Applied Psychology | volume = 83 | issue = 3| pages = 392\u2013407 | doi=10.1037/0021-9010.83.3.392}}</ref>\n\nEmployee rehabilitation is a tertiary preventive intervention which means the strategies used in rehabilitation are meant to alleviate burnout symptoms in individuals who are already affected without curing them.<ref name=\"H\u00e4tinen-2007\" /> Such rehabilitation of the working population includes multidisciplinary activities with the intent of maintaining and improving employees' working ability and ensuring a supply of skilled and capable labor in society.\n\nSee also [[Management of depression]], [[Treatments for PTSD]] and [[Chronic fatigue syndrome treatment]].\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Compassion fatigue]]\n* [[Counterproductive work behavior]]\n* [[Employee engagement]]\n* [[Meditation]]\n* [[Spoon theory]]\n* [[Writer's block]]\n* [[Emotional exhaustion]]\n\n'''Stress and the workplace:'''\n* [[Workplace stress]]\n* [[Caregiver stress]]\n* [[Industrial and organizational psychology]] \n* [[Occupational health psychology]] \n* [[Perceived organizational support]] \n* [[Perceived psychological contract violation]]\n* [[Work\u2013life balance]]\n\n'''Medical:'''\n* [[Stress (biology)|Stress]]\n* [[Hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis]]\n* [[Depression (mood)|Depression]]\n* [[Adjustment disorder]]\n* [[Acute stress disorder]]\n* [[Posttraumatic stress disorder]]\n* [[Chronic fatigue syndrome]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Bianchi | first1 = R. | last2 = Schonfeld | first2 = I.S. | last3 = Laurent | first3 = E. | year = 2014 | title = Is burnout a depressive disorder? A reexamination with special focus on atypical depression | url = https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1316&context=cc_pubs| journal = International Journal of Stress Management | volume = 21 | issue = 4| pages = 307\u2013324 | doi = 10.1037/a0037906 }}\n* Caputo, Janette S. (1991). ''Stress and Burnout in Library Service'', Phoenix, AZ: Oryx Press.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Cordes | first1 = C. | last2 = Dougherty | first2 = T. | year = 1996 | title = A review and integration of research on job burnout | url = | journal = Academy of Management Review | volume = 18 | issue = 4| pages = 621\u2013656 | doi = 10.5465/AMR.1993.9402210153 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Freudenberger | first1 = Herbert J | year = 1974 | title = Staff burnout | url = | journal = Journal of Social Issues | volume = 30 | issue = | pages = 159\u2013165 | doi = 10.1111/j.1540-4560.1974.tb00706.x }}\n* Freudenberger, Herbert J.  (1980). Burn-Out: The High Cost of High Achievement. Anchor Press\n* Freudenberger, Herbert J.  and North, Gail. (1985). Women's Burnout: How to Spot It, How to Reverse It, and How to Prevent It, Doubleday\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Heinemann | first1 = L.V. | last2 = Heinemann | first2 = T. | year = 2017 | title = Burnout Research: Emergence and Scientific Investigation of a Contested Diagnosis | url = | journal = Sage Open | volume = | issue = | pages = | doi = 10.1177/2158244017697154 | doi-access = free }}\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Kristensen|first1 = T.S.|last2 = Borritz|first2 = M.|last3 = Villadsen|first3 = E.|last4 = Christensen|first4 = K.B.|year = 2005|title = The Copenhagen Burnout Inventory: A new tool for the assessment of burnout|url = |journal = Work & Stress|volume = 19|issue = 3|pages = 192\u2013207|doi = 10.1080/02678370500297720}}\n* Maslach, C., Jackson, S. E, & Leiter, M. P. MBI: The Maslach Burnout Inventory: Manual. Palo Alto: Consulting Psychologists Press, 1996.\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Maslach|first1 = C.|last2 = Leiter|first2 = M. P.|year = 2008|title = Early predictors of job burnout and engagement|url = |journal = Journal of Applied Psychology|volume = 93|issue = 3|pages = 498\u2013512|doi = 10.1037/0021-9010.93.3.498|pmid = 18457483|citeseerx = 10.1.1.607.4751}}\n* Maslach, C. & Leiter, M. P. (1997). The truth about burnout. San Francisco: Jossey Bass.\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Maslach|first1 = C.|last2 = Schaufeli|first2 = W. B.|last3 = Leiter|first3 = M. P.|year = 2001|title = Job burnout|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5fc3eecc1afad1365bc8469ab5c39477e8c26146|journal = Annual Review of Psychology|volume = 52|issue = |pages = 397\u2013422|doi = 10.1146/annurev.psych.52.1.397|pmid = 11148311}}\n* Ray, Bernice (2002). ''An assessment of burnout in academic librarians in America using the Maslach Burnout Inventor.'' New Brunswick, NJ: Rutgers University Press.\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Shaufeli|first1 = W. B.|last2 = Leiter|first2 = M. P.|last3 = Maslach|first3 = C.|year = 2009|title = Burnout: Thirty-five years of research and practice|url = |journal = Career Development International|volume = 14|issue = 3|pages = 204\u2013220|doi = 10.1108/13620430910966406}}\n* Shaw, Craig S. (1992). A Scientific Solution To Librarian Burnout. In ''New Library World Year, 93''(5).\n* Shirom, A. & Melamed, S. (2005). Does burnout affect physical health? A review of the evidence. In A.S.G. Antoniou & C.L. Cooper (Eds.), Research companion to organizational health psychology (pp.&nbsp;599\u2013622). Cheltenham, UK: Edward Elgar. \n* {{cite journal |last1 = van Dierendonck|first1 = D.|last2 = Schaufeli|first2 = W. B.|last3 = Buunk|first3 = B. P.|year = 1998|title = The evaluation of an individual burnout intervention program: the role of in- equity and social support|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/bfd953e2f5dd6d311fe74f720f17ac9956996b11|journal = J. Appl. Psychol.|volume = 83|issue = 3|pages = 392\u2013407|doi = 10.1037/0021-9010.83.3.392}}\n* Wang, Yang; Ramos, Aaron; Wu, Hui; Liu, Li; Yang, Xiaoshi; Wang, Jiana; Wang, Lie (2014-09-26).\"Relationship between occupational stress and burnout among Chinese teachers: a cross-sectional survey in Liaoning, China\". <nowiki>''</nowiki>International Archives of Occupational and Environmental Health<nowiki>''</nowiki> <nowiki>'''</nowiki>88<nowiki>'''</nowiki> (5): 589\u2013597. {{doi|10.1007/s00420-014-0987-9}}. {{ISSN|0340-0131}}\n* Warr, Peter. (1999). ''Psychology at Work'', 4th ed. London: Penguin.\n<!--\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Rosch | first1 = PJ | year = 1998 | title = Reminiscences of Hans Selye and the birth of \"Stress\" | url = | journal = Stress Medicine | volume = 14 | issue = | pages = 1\u20136 | doi=10.1002/(sici)1099-1700(199801)14:1<1::aid-smi777>3.3.co;2-n}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Rosch | first1 = PJ. Hans Selye | year = 1999 | title = | url = | journal = International Journal of Emergency Mental Health | volume = 1 | issue = | pages = 59\u201366 }}\n-->\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| ICD10 = {{ICD10|Z|73|0|z|70}}, {{ICD10|F|43|8}}\n}}\n{{Aspects of occupations}}\n\n[[Category:Human resource management]]\n[[Category:Stress]]\n[[Category:Organizational theory]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Workplace]]\n[[Category:Motivation]]\n[[Category:Organizational behavior]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRelaxation(link changed toRelaxation (psychology)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occupational_burnout"}
{"title_page": "Jarrod Croker", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Jarrod Croker\n|fullname       = Jarrod Keith Croker\n|image          = Jarrod Croker Canberra.jpg\n|image_size     = 290\n|caption        = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1990|9|11|df=yes}}\n|birth_place    = [[Goulburn, New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n|height         = {{convert|184|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|93|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|position       = {{rlp|WG|CE}}\n|club1          = [[Canberra Raiders]]\n|year1start     = 2009\n|year1end       = present\n|appearances1   = 258\n|tries1         = 127\n|goals1         = 748\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 2008\n|teamA          = {{nowrap|[[Prime Minister's XIII]]}}\n|yearAstart     = 2014\n|yearAend       = 15\n|appearancesA   = 2\n|triesA         = 1\n|goalsA         = 2\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 8\n|teamB          = [[NRL All Stars team|NRL All Stars]]\n|yearBstart     = 2015\n|yearBend       = \n|appearancesB   = 1\n|triesB         = 0\n|goalsB         = 1\n|fieldgoalsB    = 0\n|pointsB        = 2\n|teamC          = [[Country New South Wales rugby league team|NSW Country]]\n|yearCstart     = 2015\n|yearCend       = 16\n|appearancesC   = 2\n|triesC         = 1\n|goalsC         = 5\n|fieldgoalsC    = 0\n|pointsC        = 14\n|teamD          = [[NRL All Stars team|World All Stars]]\n|yearDstart     = 2016\n|yearDend       = 17 \n|appearancesD   = 2\n|triesD         = 0\n|goalsD         = 0\n|fieldgoalsD    = 0\n|pointsD        = 0\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/jarrod-croker/summary.html|title=Jarrod Croker|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=12 February 2016|publisher=Rugby League Project|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n|updated        = 7 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Jarrod Keith Croker''' (born 11 September 1990) is an [[Australian]] professional [[rugby league]] footballer who is the captain and [[Goal (sport)#Rugby football|goal]]-kicking {{rlp|ce}} for the [[Canberra Raiders]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]. \n\nHe has played his entire career to date with the [[Canberra Raiders|Canberra]], with whom he became the [[2012 NRL season|2012]], [[2015 NRL season|2015]] and [[2016 NRL season|2016]] top point-scorer. Croker is a [[Country New South Wales rugby league team|Country Origin]], [[Prime Minister's XIII]], [[NRL All Stars team|NRL All Stars]] and [[NRL All Stars team|World All Stars]] representative. In 2016, Croker won the Dally M Captain of the year award. Croker is the Canberra Raiders top try scorer and highest point-scorer in their history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raiders.com.au/about/records.html|title=Raiders Records|website=Raiders.com.au|date=2017|accessdate=2017-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nCroker was born in [[Goulburn, New South Wales]] Australia. He is distantly related to former Canberra, [[New South Wales rugby league team|NSW]] and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] player [[Jason Croker]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/sport/croker-senses-new-raiders-dynasty/story-e6frg7mf-1225924279409|title=Croker senses new Raiders dynasty|last=Read|first=Brent|date=16 September 2010|work=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nCroker played his junior football for the Goulburn Stockmen before signing with the [[Canberra Raiders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goulburnpost.com.au/story/2925587/from-boys-to-men-and-stockmen-to-raiders/|title=From boys to men, and Stockmen to Raiders|author=CHRIS CLARKE|date=5 March 2015|work=Goulburn Post|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHe played for the New South Wales Schoolboys and Australian Schoolboys representative teams in 2007 before being selected for the New South Wales under-18s in 2008. Croker was part of the Canberra team that won the inaugural [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|National Youth Competition]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/NewsViews/LatestNews/NewsArticle/tabid/10874/newsId/54268/Default.aspx|title=Jarrod Croker: Interview|date=30 March 2009|work=www.nrl.com|publisher=[[National Rugby League]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> He played at centre and was involved in the try that won the Raiders the match 28-24 in golden point extra time.<ref>{{cite news|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/news/raiders-win-inaugural-toyota-cup/2008/10/05/1223145158102.html|title=Raiders win inaugural Toyota Cup|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\nCroker broke into Canberra's first-grade side in 2009, making his debut in round 2 against the [[Sydney Roosters]].<ref name=\"Raiders profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.raiders.com.au/default.aspx?s=nrl-player-profile-display&id=1204 |title=Jarrod Croker - Canberra Raiders |work=raiders.com.au |publisher=[[Canberra Raiders]] |accessdate=18 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716140209/http://www.raiders.com.au/default.aspx?s=nrl-player-profile-display&id=1204 |archivedate=16 July 2011 }}</ref> In round 3, against the [[Parramatta Eels]], Croker scored his first NRL try in the Raiders 16-18 loss at [[Parramatta Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-03-28/eels-scrounge-ugly-win-over-raiders/1633816|title=Eels scrounge 'ugly' win over Raiders|author=Adrian Crawford|work=ABC News|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He went on to make 21 appearances in his rookie season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/nrl/raiders-re-sign-gun-rookie/story-e6frfgbo-1225769174032|title=Raiders re-sign gun rookie|date=3 September 2009|work=[[Herald Sun]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> and was the Raiders highest try scorer with 12 tries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi00MjAtNC0tLS0tLTEzNTgxLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLQ==|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=26 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 3 September, Croker re-signed with the Raiders to the end of the 2012 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,26021246-5018866,00.html|title=Rookie Jarrod Croker signs new two-year deal with Canberra Raiders|date=3 September 2009|work=foxsports.com.au|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\nCroker was again a regular in Canberra's 2010 side, making 25 appearances as Canberra finished 7th and made the NRL finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/nrl/player?playerid=109861&teamid=3416|title=Jarrod Croker - Profile|work=[[Herald Sun]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> However, it was a missed penalty goal from Croker that ended the Raiders' season. In a sudden-death finals match against the [[Wests Tigers]], in front of a home crowd of 26,476, he pushed wide a 30-metre kick that would have tied the match at 26&ndash;26.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/croker-leads-canberra-in-mourning-glory-missed-20100918-15h2f.html|title=Croker leads Canberra in mourning glory missed|last=Proszenko|first=Adam|date=19 September 2010|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> Canberra's coach [[David Furner]]&mdash;himself a former Raiders goalkicker&mdash;defended Croker, arguing his goalkicking form had won a number of matches for the team during the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/sport/jarrod-croker-left-kicking-himself-after-penalty-sails-wide/story-e6frg7mf-1225925665497|title=Jarrod Croker left kicking himself after penalty sails wide|last=Read|first=Brent|date=18 September 2010|work=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> Days later, Croker was selected for [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia's]] train-on squad for the [[2010 Rugby League Four Nations|Four Nations]] tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/sport/rugby-league/australian-callup-helps-drown-crokers-sorrows/1946991.aspx |title=Australian call-up helps drown Croker's sorrows |last=Dutton |first=Chris |date=21 September 2010 |work=[[The Canberra Times]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |accessdate=21 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922000759/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/sport/rugby-league/australian-callup-helps-drown-crokers-sorrows/1946991.aspx |archivedate=22 September 2010 }}</ref> Croker played in all of the Raiders 26 matches and was the club's highest point scorer with 5 tries and 53 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi03MzgtNC0tLS0tLTEzNTgxLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLQ==|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=26 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\nOn 6 August, Croker re-signed with the Raiders until the end of the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerotackle.com/jarrod-croker-raider-2013-3399/#AStEXkBApzWSLefZ.97|title=Jarrod Croker a Raider until 2013|work=Zero Tackle|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He finished the [[2011 NRL season|season]] as the Raiders highest point scorer with 9 tries and 53 goals in 23 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi04MTktNC0tLS0tLTEzNTgxLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLQ==|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=26 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\n[[File:Jarrod Croker.jpg|thumb|right|Croker playing for the [[Canberra Raiders|Raiders]] in 2012]]\nCroker was the NRL's leading points scorer in 2012 with a total of 226 points, scoring 16 tries and  kicking 81 goals in 25 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/rl/scorers/2012_sc.html|title=Rugby League Tables / 2012 Point Scorers|work=afltables.com}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nIn round 3, against the Roosters, Croker played his 100th NRL match in the Raiders 24-22 win, kicking the winning goal after scoring his second try in the final minutes of the match at [[Canberra Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/canberra-raiders-steal-game-from-sydney-roosters-in-brilliant-comeback/story-fn2mcuj6-1226614423558|title=Canberra Raiders steal game from Sydney Roosters in brilliant comeback|date=11 March 2016|work=Fox Sports|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 13 April, he re-signed with the Raiders to the end of the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite news| work= Daily Telegraph| title=Star centre Jarrod Croker re-signs with Canberra Raiders until the end of 2015| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/star-centre-jarrod-croker-re-signs-with-canberra-raiders-until-end-of-2015/story-e6frexr0-1226618905071}}</ref> In round 25, against the [[New Zealand Warriors]], Croker scored his first hat trick of tries and also scored all of the club's points in the Raiders 50-16 loss at [[Mt Smart Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/warriors-mesmerise-sorry-raiders-with-hattricks-20130831-2sy0z.html|title=Warriors mesmerise sorry Raiders with hat-tricks|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He finished the [[2013 NRL season|season]] as the Raiders highest point with 9 tries and 52 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi0xNjI5LTQtLS0tLS0xMzU4MS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0=|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=25 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nIn February, Croker played in the Raiders [[2014 NRL Auckland Nines|Auckland Nines]] team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/squads-auckland-nines/|title=SQUADS FOR AUCKLAND NINES|work=Rugby League Week|accessdate=11 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115214258/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/squads-auckland-nines/|archivedate=15 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In round 24, against the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]], Croker surpassed club legend [[Mal Meninga]]\u2019s 864 club career points, taking him to third highest point scorer for the Raiders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/jarrod-croker-on-track-to-rewrite-canberra-raiders-records-20140829-109vu8.html|title=Jarrod Croker on track to re-write Canberra Raiders records|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He finished the [[2014 NRL season|year]] as the highest point scorer and try scorer for the Raiders, scoring 18 tries and scoring 202 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi0xNjQ0LTQtLS0tLS0xMzU4MS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0=|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=26 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 5 September, Croker re-signed with the Raiders until the end of the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/breaking-news/canberra-raiders-finally-get-a-break-with-the-resigning-of-rising-local-junior-jarrod-croker/news-story/0c70c13ece850285dc82aabf37b1b118|title=Canberra Raiders finally get a break with re-signing of rising local junior Jarrod Croker|date=11 March 2016|work=Fox Sports|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He was named as the 2014 Meninga Medallist for Raiders\u2019 best and fairest player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/canberra-raiders-centre-jarrod-croker-claims-mal-meninga-medal-20140910-10exq5.html|title=Canberra Raiders centre Jarrod Croker claims Mal Meninga medal|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 October, Croker played for the [[Prime Minister's XIII]] team against [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], filling in for Raiders teammate [[Jack Wighton]] on the interchange bench after he was a late scratching.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/raiders-star-jarrod-croker-expects-brutal-initiation-for-prime-ministers-xiii-20141011-11450e.html|title=Raiders star Jarrod Croker expects brutal initiation for Prime Minister's XIII|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/pms-xiii-defeat-valiant-png/tabid/10874/newsid/82486/default.aspx|title=PM's XIII defeat valiant PNG|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 19 December, Croker was named by coach Ricky Stuart as the new captain for the Canberra Raiders following the departure of [[Terry Campese]] to [[Hull Kingston Rovers]] in the [[Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/breaking-news/nrl-2015-canberra-captain-jarrod-croker-leads-raiders-into-future/news-story/b7bb7b08025395e7afe3bcbda011cc8c|title=Canberra captain Jarrod Croker leads Raiders into future|date=11 March 2016|work=Fox Sports|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/croker-named-raiders-captain/tabid/10874/newsid/83319/default.aspx|title=Croker named Raiders captain|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nIn the pre-season, Croker was captain of the Raiders [[2015 NRL Auckland Nines|Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/raiders-unveil-2015-nines-squad/|title=RAIDERS UNVEIL 2015 NINES SQUAD|work=Rugby League Week|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 13 February 2015, Croker played at centre for [[NRL All Stars team|NRL All Stars]] against the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]], kicking a goal in the 20-6 loss at [[Robina Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/2015-all-stars-teams-revealed/tabid/10874/newsid/83420/default.aspx|title=2015 All Stars teams revealed|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/indigenous-all-stars-leave-it-late/tabid/10874/newsid/83833/default.aspx|title=Indigenous All Stars leave it late|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 3 May 2015, Croker played for [[Country New South Wales rugby league team|Country Origin]] against [[City New South Wales rugby league team|City Origin]], scoring a try in the 34-22 win at [[Wagga Wagga, New South Wales|Wagga Wagga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/country-overcome-city-in-seesawing-affair/tabid/10874/newsid/85906/default.aspx|title=Country overcome City in seesawing affair|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> In round 10, against the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]], Croker played in 150th NRL match in the Raiders 32-18 loss at [[WIN Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/be-there-to-celebrate-jarrod-crokers-150th/tabid/10874/newsid/86186/default.aspx|title=Be there to celebrate Jarrod Croker's 150th|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/halves-star-in-dragons-win/tabid/10874/newsid/86305/default.aspx|title=Halves star in Dragons win|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> In round 13, against the [[Newcastle Knights]], Croker notched a 1000 career points in the Raiders 44-22 win at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goulburnpost.com.au/story/3130472/croker-passes-1000-points-for-raiders/|title=Croker passes 1000 points for Raiders|author=DARRYL FERNANCE|date=7 June 2015|work=Goulburn Post|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> At the end of the season, Croker was the NRL's top point scorer with 236 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/croker-lands-nrl-top-pointscorer-title/tabid/10874/newsid/89549/default.aspx|title=Croker lands NRL top pointscorer title|work=NRL.com}}</ref> On 26 September, Croker played for the Prime Minister's XIII against Papua New Guinea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/merrin-to-lead-prime-ministers-xiii/tabid/10874/newsid/89831/default.aspx|title=Merrin to lead Prime Minister's XIII|work=NRL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nIn February 2016, Croker was named in the Raiders [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2016/02/03/2016-downer-nrl-auckland-nines-official-squads/</ref> On 13 February 2016, Croker played for the [[World All Stars]] against the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]], playing at centre in the 12-8 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/teams-named-for-nrl-all-stars-match/tabid/10874/newsid/91188/default.aspx |title=Teams named for NRL All Stars match |website=NRL.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/world-all-stars-defeat-indigenous-all-stars-128-at-suncorp-stadium/news-story/034a63c6602597828b4b9a5ce72f986e |title=World All-Stars Defeat Indigenous All-Stars 12-8 at Suncorp Stadium |website=Dailytelegraph.com.au |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref> On 8 May 2016, Croker again represented Country Origin against City Origin, kicking 5 goals in the 44-30 loss in [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/young-city-side-stun-country/tabid/10874/newsid/95694/default.aspx |title=Young City side stun Country |website=NRL.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref> In Round 10 against the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]], Croker became the highest ever point scorer for the Raiders in the 16-12 golden point loss at [[Jubilee Oval]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/rugby-league/canberra-raiders/jarrod-croker-eyes-canberra-raiders-record-but-beating-dragons-comes-first-20160511-gosaeo.html |title=Jarrod Croker eyes Canberra Raiders record, but beating Dragons comes first |website=Canberratimes.com.au |date=2016-05-11 |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/intercept-hands-dragons-golden-win/tabid/10874/newsid/95846/default.aspx |title=Intercept hands Dragons golden win |website=NRL.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref> At the end of the season, Croker picked up the Provan Summons award as well as Dally M Captain of the Year and season's leading point scorer in a year were the Raiders fell one game short of the Grand Final.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rugby League |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/rugby-league/canberra-raiders/dally-m-medal-ricky-stuart-jarrod-croker-and-joey-leiluas-pain-eased-with-awards-20160928-grqmaq.html |title=Dally M Medal: Ricky Stuart, Jarrod Croker and Joey Leilua's pain eased with awards |website=Canberratimes.com.au |date=2016-09-28 |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/croker-declares-fitness-after-cleaning-up-at-dally-ms/tabid/10874/newsid/101834/default.aspx |title=Croker declares fitness after cleaning up at Dally Ms |website=NRL.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref> Croker played in all of the Raiders 27 matches, scoring 18 tries and kicking 112 goals in the [[2016 NRL season]]. After the season ended, Croker was named the [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|Four Nations]] train-on squad but later dropped out due to a knee injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/raiders-centres-jarrod-croker-joey-leilua-in-doubt-for-kangaroos-selection-with-injury/news-story/d35d03a234d08aa23df633096f3fa934 |title=Raiders Centres Jarrod Croker, Joey Leilua in Doubt for Kangaroos Selection with Injury |website=Heraldsun.com.au |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOn 10 February 2017, Croker played for the [[World All Stars]] against the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]] in the [[2017 All Stars match]], playing at centre in the 34-8 loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/live-updates-of-nrl-all-stars-at-hunter-stadium-in-newcastle/news-story/d137d71a228da375f0d48a0d0ed1bdaf|title=Rough start for Nine\u2019s new footy host|publisher=|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> In Round 5 against the [[Parramatta Eels]] in the 30-18 win at [[Canberra Stadium]], Croker became the third player to score 100 tries for Canberra,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/rl/teams/canberra/canberra_sc.html|title=Rugby League Tables / Canberra Point Scorers|publisher=}}</ref> after [[Jason Croker]] and [[Brett Mullins]], and the fifth player to score 100 tries and kick 500 goals in Australian first grade rugby league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/rl/scorers/overall_sc1.html|title=Rugby League Tables / Point Scorers (1908-2017)|publisher=}}</ref> He also became only the seventh player after [[Terry Lamb]] ([[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury-Bankstown]]), [[Greg Alexander]] ([[Penrith Panthers|Penrith]]), [[Ryan Girdler]] (Penrith), [[Hazem El Masri]] (Canterbury-Bankstown), [[Darren Lockyer]] ([[Brisbane Broncos|Brisbane]]) and [[Luke Burt]] ([[Parramatta Eels|Parramatta]]) to score 100 tries and over 1,000 points for a single club. In Round 11 against the [[Parramatta Eels]], Croker played his 200th NRL career match in the Raiders 22-16 win at [[ANZ Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/teams/raiders/blake-austin-jarrod-croker-to-join-youngest-to-play-200th-game-unbelievable-rep-snub/news-story/35d29f3f3c36cba4c83d25e6c7720373|title=Jarrod Croker 200th NRL Canberra Raiders game, Blake Austin column, NSW Blues Origin - Fox Sports|website=www.foxsports.com.au|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/stuart-asked-raiders-to-do-it-for-croker/tabid/10874/newsid/107021/default.aspx|title=Stuart asked Raiders to 'do it for Croker'|date=20 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> On 10 August 2017, Croker extended his contract with the Raiders to the end of the 2020 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-canberra-raiders-resign-captain-jarrod-croker-until-the-end-of-2020-20170809-gxs8x0.html|title=NRL: Canberra Raiders re-sign captain Jarrod Croker until the end of 2020|first=Caden|last=Helmers|date=9 August 2017|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2017/08/10/jarrod-croker-re-signs-with-raiders/|title=Jarrod Croker re-signs with Raiders|date=10 August 2017|publisher=|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> Croker finished the [[2017 NRL season]] with him scoring 9 tries and kicking 77 goals for the Raiders.\n\n===2018===\nIn Round 18 against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]], Croker suffered a season ending knee injury in the Raiders 38-12 win at [[Canberra Stadium]].<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/how-do-the-raiders-fill-jarrod-croker-s-headgear-20180714-p4zrii.html</ref> Croker finished the [[2018 NRL season]] with him playing in 17 matches, scoring 7 and kicking 63 goals for the Raiders.\n\n===2019===\nOn 13 February 2019, after being the solo captain for the Raiders for the past 4 years, coach Ricky Stuart appointed hooker [[Josh Hodgson]] as co-captain alongside Croker for the season.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/02/13/pressure-on-jarrod-croker-after-josh-hodgson-promoted-to-canberra-raiders-co-captaincy/</ref> Croker made his return from injury in Round 1 against the [[Gold Coast Titans]], kicking 4 goals in the 21-0 win at [[Robina Stadium]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/03/17/canberra-raiders-too-slick-for-gold-coast-titans-in-the-wet/</ref>\n\nIn Round 17 against St George, Croker became Canberra's all-time leading try scorer with 120 tries surpassing [[Jason Croker]] in a 36-14 victory at [[WIN Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/07/14/cotric-sent-off-for-dangerous-throw-on-lafai/|title=Cotric sent off for dangerous throw on Lafai as Raiders down Dragons|website=www.nrl.com}}</ref>\nIn Round 22 against Melbourne, Croker scored 2 tries as Canberra came from 18-0 down at halftime to win the match 22-18 at [[AAMI Park]].  It was the first time since 2015 that Melbourne had lost 2 games in a row at their home stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/08/17/raiders-pull-off-incredible-comeback-to-stun-storm-in-melbourne/|title=Incredible Raiders comeback stuns Storm in Melbourne|website=NRL}}</ref>\n\nCanberra finished the 2019 regular season in 4th place on the table and qualified for the finals.  The club would then go on to qualify for their first grand final in 25 years.  Croker captained Canberra in the [[2019 NRL Grand Final]] as they were defeated 14-8 by the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[ANZ Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-roosters-and-raiders-hits-and-misses-20191006-p52y53.html/|title=NRL grand final player ratings: Roosters and Raiders hits and misses|website=SMH}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/nrl/grand-final-ricky-stuart-reaction-canberra-raiders-six-again-jack-wighton/ae39b639-d375-4608-89a6-af6285c3d635/|title=How Ricky Stuart reacted to grand final 'six-again' refereeing shocker|website=WWOS}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n=== Domestic ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Club\n!Season\n!App\n!T\n!G\n!GK %\n!FG\n!Pts\n|-\n| rowspan=\"11\" |{{Leagueicon|Canberra|16}} [[Canberra Raiders]]\n|[[2009 Canberra Raiders season|2009]]\n|21\n|12\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|48\n|-\n|[[2010 Canberra Raiders season|2010]]\n|26\n|5\n|53\n|84.1%\n| -\n|126\n|-\n|[[2011 Canberra Raiders season|2011]]\n|23\n|9\n|59\n|78.7%\n| -\n|154\n|-\n|[[2012 NRL season|2012]]\n|25\n|16\n|81\n|74.3%\n| -\n|226\n|-\n|[[2013 Canberra Raiders season|2013]]\n|21\n|8\n|52\n|85.3%\n| -\n|138\n|-\n|[[2014 Canberra Raiders season|2014]]\n|24\n|18\n|65\n|84.4%\n| -\n|202\n|-\n|[[2015 Canberra Raiders season|2