egory:Country New South Wales Origin rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:NRL All Stars players]]\n[[Category:Prime Minister's XIII players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league centres]]\n[[Category:People from Goulburn, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Jarrod Croker\n|fullname       = Jarrod Keith Croker\n|image          = Jarrod Croker Canberra.jpg\n|image_size     = 290\n|caption        = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1990|9|11|df=yes}}\n|birth_place    = [[Goulburn, New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n|height         = {{convert|184|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|93|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|position       = {{rlp|CE|WG}}\n|club1          = [[Canberra Raiders]]\n|year1start     = 2009\n|year1end       = present\n|appearances1   = 258\n|tries1         = 127\n|goals1         = 748\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 2008\n|teamA          = {{nowrap|[[Prime Minister's XIII]]}}\n|yearAstart     = 2014\n|yearAend       = 15\n|appearancesA   = 2\n|triesA         = 1\n|goalsA         = 2\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 8\n|teamB          = [[NRL All Stars team|NRL All Stars]]\n|yearBstart     = 2015\n|yearBend       = \n|appearancesB   = 1\n|triesB         = 0\n|goalsB         = 1\n|fieldgoalsB    = 0\n|pointsB        = 2\n|teamC          = [[Country New South Wales rugby league team|NSW Country]]\n|yearCstart     = 2015\n|yearCend       = 16\n|appearancesC   = 2\n|triesC         = 1\n|goalsC         = 5\n|fieldgoalsC    = 0\n|pointsC        = 14\n|teamD          = [[NRL All Stars team|World All Stars]]\n|yearDstart     = 2016\n|yearDend       = 17 \n|appearancesD   = 2\n|triesD         = 0\n|goalsD         = 0\n|fieldgoalsD    = 0\n|pointsD        = 0\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/jarrod-croker/summary.html|title=Jarrod Croker|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=12 February 2016|publisher=Rugby League Project|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n|updated        = 7 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Jarrod Keith Croker''' (born 11 September 1990) is an [[Australian]] professional [[rugby league]] footballer who is the captain and [[Goal (sport)#Rugby football|goal]]-kicking {{rlp|ce}} for the [[Canberra Raiders]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]. \n\nHe has played his entire career to date with the [[Canberra Raiders|Canberra]], with whom he became the [[2012 NRL season|2012]], [[2015 NRL season|2015]] and [[2016 NRL season|2016]] top point-scorer. Croker is a [[Country New South Wales rugby league team|Country Origin]], [[Prime Minister's XIII]], [[NRL All Stars team|NRL All Stars]] and [[NRL All Stars team|World All Stars]] representative. In 2016, Croker won the Dally M Captain of the year award. Croker is the Canberra Raiders top try scorer and highest point-scorer in their history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raiders.com.au/about/records.html|title=Raiders Records|website=Raiders.com.au|date=2017|accessdate=2017-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nCroker was born in [[Goulburn, New South Wales]] Australia. He is distantly related to former Canberra, [[New South Wales rugby league team|NSW]] and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] player [[Jason Croker]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/sport/croker-senses-new-raiders-dynasty/story-e6frg7mf-1225924279409|title=Croker senses new Raiders dynasty|last=Read|first=Brent|date=16 September 2010|work=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nCroker played his junior football for the Goulburn Stockmen before signing with the [[Canberra Raiders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goulburnpost.com.au/story/2925587/from-boys-to-men-and-stockmen-to-raiders/|title=From boys to men, and Stockmen to Raiders|author=CHRIS CLARKE|date=5 March 2015|work=Goulburn Post|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHe played for the New South Wales Schoolboys and Australian Schoolboys representative teams in 2007 before being selected for the New South Wales under-18s in 2008. Croker was part of the Canberra team that won the inaugural [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|National Youth Competition]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/NewsViews/LatestNews/NewsArticle/tabid/10874/newsId/54268/Default.aspx|title=Jarrod Croker: Interview|date=30 March 2009|work=www.nrl.com|publisher=[[National Rugby League]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> He played at centre and was involved in the try that won the Raiders the match 28-24 in golden point extra time.<ref>{{cite news|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/news/raiders-win-inaugural-toyota-cup/2008/10/05/1223145158102.html|title=Raiders win inaugural Toyota Cup|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\nCroker broke into Canberra's first-grade side in 2009, making his debut in round 2 against the [[Sydney Roosters]].<ref name=\"Raiders profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.raiders.com.au/default.aspx?s=nrl-player-profile-display&id=1204 |title=Jarrod Croker - Canberra Raiders |work=raiders.com.au |publisher=[[Canberra Raiders]] |accessdate=18 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716140209/http://www.raiders.com.au/default.aspx?s=nrl-player-profile-display&id=1204 |archivedate=16 July 2011 }}</ref> In round 3, against the [[Parramatta Eels]], Croker scored his first NRL try in the Raiders 16-18 loss at [[Parramatta Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-03-28/eels-scrounge-ugly-win-over-raiders/1633816|title=Eels scrounge 'ugly' win over Raiders|author=Adrian Crawford|work=ABC News|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He went on to make 21 appearances in his rookie season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/nrl/raiders-re-sign-gun-rookie/story-e6frfgbo-1225769174032|title=Raiders re-sign gun rookie|date=3 September 2009|work=[[Herald Sun]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> and was the Raiders highest try scorer with 12 tries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi00MjAtNC0tLS0tLTEzNTgxLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLQ==|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=26 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 3 September, Croker re-signed with the Raiders to the end of the 2012 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,26021246-5018866,00.html|title=Rookie Jarrod Croker signs new two-year deal with Canberra Raiders|date=3 September 2009|work=foxsports.com.au|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\nCroker was again a regular in Canberra's 2010 side, making 25 appearances as Canberra finished 7th and made the NRL finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/nrl/player?playerid=109861&teamid=3416|title=Jarrod Croker - Profile|work=[[Herald Sun]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> However, it was a missed penalty goal from Croker that ended the Raiders' season. In a sudden-death finals match against the [[Wests Tigers]], in front of a home crowd of 26,476, he pushed wide a 30-metre kick that would have tied the match at 26&ndash;26.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/croker-leads-canberra-in-mourning-glory-missed-20100918-15h2f.html|title=Croker leads Canberra in mourning glory missed|last=Proszenko|first=Adam|date=19 September 2010|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> Canberra's coach [[David Furner]]&mdash;himself a former Raiders goalkicker&mdash;defended Croker, arguing his goalkicking form had won a number of matches for the team during the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/sport/jarrod-croker-left-kicking-himself-after-penalty-sails-wide/story-e6frg7mf-1225925665497|title=Jarrod Croker left kicking himself after penalty sails wide|last=Read|first=Brent|date=18 September 2010|work=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> Days later, Croker was selected for [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia's]] train-on squad for the [[2010 Rugby League Four Nations|Four Nations]] tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/sport/rugby-league/australian-callup-helps-drown-crokers-sorrows/1946991.aspx |title=Australian call-up helps drown Croker's sorrows |last=Dutton |first=Chris |date=21 September 2010 |work=[[The Canberra Times]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |accessdate=21 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922000759/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/sport/rugby-league/australian-callup-helps-drown-crokers-sorrows/1946991.aspx |archivedate=22 September 2010 }}</ref> Croker played in all of the Raiders 26 matches and was the club's highest point scorer with 5 tries and 53 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi03MzgtNC0tLS0tLTEzNTgxLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLQ==|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=26 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\nOn 6 August, Croker re-signed with the Raiders until the end of the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerotackle.com/jarrod-croker-raider-2013-3399/#AStEXkBApzWSLefZ.97|title=Jarrod Croker a Raider until 2013|work=Zero Tackle|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He finished the [[2011 NRL season|season]] as the Raiders highest point scorer with 9 tries and 53 goals in 23 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi04MTktNC0tLS0tLTEzNTgxLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLQ==|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=26 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\n[[File:Jarrod Croker.jpg|thumb|right|Croker playing for the [[Canberra Raiders|Raiders]] in 2012]]\nCroker was the NRL's leading points scorer in 2012 with a total of 226 points, scoring 16 tries and  kicking 81 goals in 25 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/rl/scorers/2012_sc.html|title=Rugby League Tables / 2012 Point Scorers|work=afltables.com}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nIn round 3, against the Roosters, Croker played his 100th NRL match in the Raiders 24-22 win, kicking the winning goal after scoring his second try in the final minutes of the match at [[Canberra Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/canberra-raiders-steal-game-from-sydney-roosters-in-brilliant-comeback/story-fn2mcuj6-1226614423558|title=Canberra Raiders steal game from Sydney Roosters in brilliant comeback|date=11 March 2016|work=Fox Sports|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 13 April, he re-signed with the Raiders to the end of the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite news| work= Daily Telegraph| title=Star centre Jarrod Croker re-signs with Canberra Raiders until the end of 2015| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/star-centre-jarrod-croker-re-signs-with-canberra-raiders-until-end-of-2015/story-e6frexr0-1226618905071}}</ref> In round 25, against the [[New Zealand Warriors]], Croker scored his first hat trick of tries and also scored all of the club's points in the Raiders 50-16 loss at [[Mt Smart Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/warriors-mesmerise-sorry-raiders-with-hattricks-20130831-2sy0z.html|title=Warriors mesmerise sorry Raiders with hat-tricks|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He finished the [[2013 NRL season|season]] as the Raiders highest point with 9 tries and 52 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi0xNjI5LTQtLS0tLS0xMzU4MS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0=|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=25 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nIn February, Croker played in the Raiders [[2014 NRL Auckland Nines|Auckland Nines]] team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/squads-auckland-nines/|title=SQUADS FOR AUCKLAND NINES|work=Rugby League Week|accessdate=11 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115214258/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/squads-auckland-nines/|archivedate=15 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In round 24, against the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]], Croker surpassed club legend [[Mal Meninga]]\u2019s 864 club career points, taking him to third highest point scorer for the Raiders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/jarrod-croker-on-track-to-rewrite-canberra-raiders-records-20140829-109vu8.html|title=Jarrod Croker on track to re-write Canberra Raiders records|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He finished the [[2014 NRL season|year]] as the highest point scorer and try scorer for the Raiders, scoring 18 tries and scoring 202 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/Mi0xNjQ0LTQtLS0tLS0xMzU4MS0tLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0=|title=Custom Match List|author=Shawn Dollin and Andrew Ferguson|date=26 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 5 September, Croker re-signed with the Raiders until the end of the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/breaking-news/canberra-raiders-finally-get-a-break-with-the-resigning-of-rising-local-junior-jarrod-croker/news-story/0c70c13ece850285dc82aabf37b1b118|title=Canberra Raiders finally get a break with re-signing of rising local junior Jarrod Croker|date=11 March 2016|work=Fox Sports|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> He was named as the 2014 Meninga Medallist for Raiders\u2019 best and fairest player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/canberra-raiders-centre-jarrod-croker-claims-mal-meninga-medal-20140910-10exq5.html|title=Canberra Raiders centre Jarrod Croker claims Mal Meninga medal|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 October, Croker played for the [[Prime Minister's XIII]] team against [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], filling in for Raiders teammate [[Jack Wighton]] on the interchange bench after he was a late scratching.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/raiders-star-jarrod-croker-expects-brutal-initiation-for-prime-ministers-xiii-20141011-11450e.html|title=Raiders star Jarrod Croker expects brutal initiation for Prime Minister's XIII|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/pms-xiii-defeat-valiant-png/tabid/10874/newsid/82486/default.aspx|title=PM's XIII defeat valiant PNG|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 19 December, Croker was named by coach Ricky Stuart as the new captain for the Canberra Raiders following the departure of [[Terry Campese]] to [[Hull Kingston Rovers]] in the [[Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/breaking-news/nrl-2015-canberra-captain-jarrod-croker-leads-raiders-into-future/news-story/b7bb7b08025395e7afe3bcbda011cc8c|title=Canberra captain Jarrod Croker leads Raiders into future|date=11 March 2016|work=Fox Sports|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/croker-named-raiders-captain/tabid/10874/newsid/83319/default.aspx|title=Croker named Raiders captain|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nIn the pre-season, Croker was captain of the Raiders [[2015 NRL Auckland Nines|Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/raiders-unveil-2015-nines-squad/|title=RAIDERS UNVEIL 2015 NINES SQUAD|work=Rugby League Week|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 13 February 2015, Croker played at centre for [[NRL All Stars team|NRL All Stars]] against the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]], kicking a goal in the 20-6 loss at [[Robina Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/2015-all-stars-teams-revealed/tabid/10874/newsid/83420/default.aspx|title=2015 All Stars teams revealed|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/indigenous-all-stars-leave-it-late/tabid/10874/newsid/83833/default.aspx|title=Indigenous All Stars leave it late|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> On 3 May 2015, Croker played for [[Country New South Wales rugby league team|Country Origin]] against [[City New South Wales rugby league team|City Origin]], scoring a try in the 34-22 win at [[Wagga Wagga, New South Wales|Wagga Wagga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/country-overcome-city-in-seesawing-affair/tabid/10874/newsid/85906/default.aspx|title=Country overcome City in seesawing affair|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> In round 10, against the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]], Croker played in 150th NRL match in the Raiders 32-18 loss at [[WIN Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/be-there-to-celebrate-jarrod-crokers-150th/tabid/10874/newsid/86186/default.aspx|title=Be there to celebrate Jarrod Croker's 150th|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/halves-star-in-dragons-win/tabid/10874/newsid/86305/default.aspx|title=Halves star in Dragons win|work=NRL.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> In round 13, against the [[Newcastle Knights]], Croker notched a 1000 career points in the Raiders 44-22 win at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goulburnpost.com.au/story/3130472/croker-passes-1000-points-for-raiders/|title=Croker passes 1000 points for Raiders|author=DARRYL FERNANCE|date=7 June 2015|work=Goulburn Post|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> At the end of the season, Croker was the NRL's top point scorer with 236 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/croker-lands-nrl-top-pointscorer-title/tabid/10874/newsid/89549/default.aspx|title=Croker lands NRL top pointscorer title|work=NRL.com}}</ref> On 26 September, Croker played for the Prime Minister's XIII against Papua New Guinea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/merrin-to-lead-prime-ministers-xiii/tabid/10874/newsid/89831/default.aspx|title=Merrin to lead Prime Minister's XIII|work=NRL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nIn February 2016, Croker was named in the Raiders [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2016/02/03/2016-downer-nrl-auckland-nines-official-squads/</ref> On 13 February 2016, Croker played for the [[World All Stars]] against the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]], playing at centre in the 12-8 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/teams-named-for-nrl-all-stars-match/tabid/10874/newsid/91188/default.aspx |title=Teams named for NRL All Stars match |website=NRL.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/world-all-stars-defeat-indigenous-all-stars-128-at-suncorp-stadium/news-story/034a63c6602597828b4b9a5ce72f986e |title=World All-Stars Defeat Indigenous All-Stars 12-8 at Suncorp Stadium |website=Dailytelegraph.com.au |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref> On 8 May 2016, Croker again represented Country Origin against City Origin, kicking 5 goals in the 44-30 loss in [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/young-city-side-stun-country/tabid/10874/newsid/95694/default.aspx |title=Young City side stun Country |website=NRL.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref> In Round 10 against the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]], Croker became the highest ever point scorer for the Raiders in the 16-12 golden point loss at [[Jubilee Oval]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/rugby-league/canberra-raiders/jarrod-croker-eyes-canberra-raiders-record-but-beating-dragons-comes-first-20160511-gosaeo.html |title=Jarrod Croker eyes Canberra Raiders record, but beating Dragons comes first |website=Canberratimes.com.au |date=2016-05-11 |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/intercept-hands-dragons-golden-win/tabid/10874/newsid/95846/default.aspx |title=Intercept hands Dragons golden win |website=NRL.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref> At the end of the season, Croker picked up the Provan Summons award as well as Dally M Captain of the Year and season's leading point scorer in a year were the Raiders fell one game short of the Grand Final.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rugby League |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/rugby-league/canberra-raiders/dally-m-medal-ricky-stuart-jarrod-croker-and-joey-leiluas-pain-eased-with-awards-20160928-grqmaq.html |title=Dally M Medal: Ricky Stuart, Jarrod Croker and Joey Leilua's pain eased with awards |website=Canberratimes.com.au |date=2016-09-28 |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/croker-declares-fitness-after-cleaning-up-at-dally-ms/tabid/10874/newsid/101834/default.aspx |title=Croker declares fitness after cleaning up at Dally Ms |website=NRL.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref> Croker played in all of the Raiders 27 matches, scoring 18 tries and kicking 112 goals in the [[2016 NRL season]]. After the season ended, Croker was named the [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|Four Nations]] train-on squad but later dropped out due to a knee injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/raiders-centres-jarrod-croker-joey-leilua-in-doubt-for-kangaroos-selection-with-injury/news-story/d35d03a234d08aa23df633096f3fa934 |title=Raiders Centres Jarrod Croker, Joey Leilua in Doubt for Kangaroos Selection with Injury |website=Heraldsun.com.au |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOn 10 February 2017, Croker played for the [[World All Stars]] against the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]] in the [[2017 All Stars match]], playing at centre in the 34-8 loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/live-updates-of-nrl-all-stars-at-hunter-stadium-in-newcastle/news-story/d137d71a228da375f0d48a0d0ed1bdaf|title=Rough start for Nine\u2019s new footy host|publisher=|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> In Round 5 against the [[Parramatta Eels]] in the 30-18 win at [[Canberra Stadium]], Croker became the third player to score 100 tries for Canberra,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/rl/teams/canberra/canberra_sc.html|title=Rugby League Tables / Canberra Point Scorers|publisher=}}</ref> after [[Jason Croker]] and [[Brett Mullins]], and the fifth player to score 100 tries and kick 500 goals in Australian first grade rugby league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/rl/scorers/overall_sc1.html|title=Rugby League Tables / Point Scorers (1908-2017)|publisher=}}</ref> He also became only the seventh player after [[Terry Lamb]] ([[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury-Bankstown]]), [[Greg Alexander]] ([[Penrith Panthers|Penrith]]), [[Ryan Girdler]] (Penrith), [[Hazem El Masri]] (Canterbury-Bankstown), [[Darren Lockyer]] ([[Brisbane Broncos|Brisbane]]) and [[Luke Burt]] ([[Parramatta Eels|Parramatta]]) to score 100 tries and over 1,000 points for a single club. In Round 11 against the [[Parramatta Eels]], Croker played his 200th NRL career match in the Raiders 22-16 win at [[ANZ Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/teams/raiders/blake-austin-jarrod-croker-to-join-youngest-to-play-200th-game-unbelievable-rep-snub/news-story/35d29f3f3c36cba4c83d25e6c7720373|title=Jarrod Croker 200th NRL Canberra Raiders game, Blake Austin column, NSW Blues Origin - Fox Sports|website=www.foxsports.com.au|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/stuart-asked-raiders-to-do-it-for-croker/tabid/10874/newsid/107021/default.aspx|title=Stuart asked Raiders to 'do it for Croker'|date=20 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> On 10 August 2017, Croker extended his contract with the Raiders to the end of the 2020 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-canberra-raiders-resign-captain-jarrod-croker-until-the-end-of-2020-20170809-gxs8x0.html|title=NRL: Canberra Raiders re-sign captain Jarrod Croker until the end of 2020|first=Caden|last=Helmers|date=9 August 2017|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2017/08/10/jarrod-croker-re-signs-with-raiders/|title=Jarrod Croker re-signs with Raiders|date=10 August 2017|publisher=|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> Croker finished the [[2017 NRL season]] with him scoring 9 tries and kicking 77 goals for the Raiders.\n\n===2018===\nIn Round 18 against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]], Croker suffered a season ending knee injury in the Raiders 38-12 win at [[Canberra Stadium]].<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/how-do-the-raiders-fill-jarrod-croker-s-headgear-20180714-p4zrii.html</ref> Croker finished the [[2018 NRL season]] with him playing in 17 matches, scoring 7 and kicking 63 goals for the Raiders.\n\n===2019===\nOn 13 February 2019, after being the solo captain for the Raiders for the past 4 years, coach Ricky Stuart appointed hooker [[Josh Hodgson]] as co-captain alongside Croker for the season.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/02/13/pressure-on-jarrod-croker-after-josh-hodgson-promoted-to-canberra-raiders-co-captaincy/</ref> Croker made his return from injury in Round 1 against the [[Gold Coast Titans]], kicking 4 goals in the 21-0 win at [[Robina Stadium]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/03/17/canberra-raiders-too-slick-for-gold-coast-titans-in-the-wet/</ref>\n\nIn Round 17 against St George, Croker became Canberra's all-time leading try scorer with 120 tries surpassing [[Jason Croker]] in a 36-14 victory at [[WIN Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/07/14/cotric-sent-off-for-dangerous-throw-on-lafai/|title=Cotric sent off for dangerous throw on Lafai as Raiders down Dragons|website=www.nrl.com}}</ref>\nIn Round 22 against Melbourne, Croker scored 2 tries as Canberra came from 18-0 down at halftime to win the match 22-18 at [[AAMI Park]].  It was the first time since 2015 that Melbourne had lost 2 games in a row at their home stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/08/17/raiders-pull-off-incredible-comeback-to-stun-storm-in-melbourne/|title=Incredible Raiders comeback stuns Storm in Melbourne|website=NRL}}</ref>\n\nCanberra finished the 2019 regular season in 4th place on the table and qualified for the finals.  The club would then go on to qualify for their first grand final in 25 years.  Croker captained Canberra in the [[2019 NRL Grand Final]] as they were defeated 14-8 by the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[ANZ Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-roosters-and-raiders-hits-and-misses-20191006-p52y53.html/|title=NRL grand final player ratings: Roosters and Raiders hits and misses|website=SMH}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/nrl/grand-final-ricky-stuart-reaction-canberra-raiders-six-again-jack-wighton/ae39b639-d375-4608-89a6-af6285c3d635/|title=How Ricky Stuart reacted to grand final 'six-again' refereeing shocker|website=WWOS}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n=== Domestic ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Club\n!Season\n!App\n!T\n!G\n!GK %\n!FG\n!Pts\n|-\n| rowspan=\"11\" |{{Leagueicon|Canberra|16}} [[Canberra Raiders]]\n|[[2009 Canberra Raiders season|2009]]\n|21\n|12\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|48\n|-\n|[[2010 Canberra Raiders season|2010]]\n|26\n|5\n|53\n|84.1%\n| -\n|126\n|-\n|[[2011 Canberra Raiders season|2011]]\n|23\n|9\n|59\n|78.7%\n| -\n|154\n|-\n|[[2012 NRL season|2012]]\n|25\n|16\n|81\n|74.3%\n| -\n|226\n|-\n|[[2013 Canberra Raiders season|2013]]\n|21\n|8\n|52\n|85.3%\n| -\n|138\n|-\n|[[2014 Canberra Raiders season|2014]]\n|24\n|18\n|65\n|84.4%\n| -\n|202\n|-\n|[[2015 Canberra Raiders season|2015]]\n|24\n|12\n|94\n|84.7%\n| -\n|236\n|-\n|[[2016 Canberra Raiders season|2016]]\n|27\n|18\n|112\n|81.2%\n| -\n|296\n|-\n|[[2017 Canberra Raiders season|2017]]\n|22\n|9\n|77\n|81.9%\n| -\n|190\n|-\n|[[2018 Canberra Raiders season|2018]]\n|17\n|7\n|63\n|77.8%\n| -\n|154\n|-\n|[[2019 Canberra Raiders season|2019]]\n|27\n|13\n|88\n|73.3%\n| -\n|228\n|-\n!Total\n!2009\u20132019\n!257\n!127\n!744\n!80.09%\n!0\n!1,996\n|}\n\n=== Representative ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Team\n!Season\n!App\n!T\n!G\n!GK %\n!FG\n!Pts\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{Leagueicon|Australia|16}} [[Prime Minister's XIII]]\n|[[Prime Minister's XIII|2014]]\n|1\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|-\n|[[Prime Minister's XIII|2015]]\n|1\n|1\n|2\n|100%\n| -\n|8\n|-\n|[[NRL All Stars team|NRL All Stars]]\n|[[2015 All Stars match|2015]]\n|1\n| -\n|1\n|100%\n| -\n|2\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{Leagueicon|Country|16}} [[Country New South Wales rugby league team|Country]]\n|[[City vs Country Origin|2015]]\n|1\n|1\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|4\n|-\n|[[City vs Country Origin|2016]]\n|1\n| -\n|5\n|100%\n| -\n|10\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[NRL All Stars team|World All Stars]]\n|[[2016 All Stars match|2016]]\n|1\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|-\n|[[2017 All Stars match|2017]]\n|1\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|-\n!Total\n!2014\u20132017\n!7\n!2\n!8\n!100%\n!-\n!24\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.raiders.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/canberra-raiders/jarrod-croker/ Canberra Raiders profile]\n*[http://www.raiders.com.au/team/profiles/jarrod-croker.html Raiders profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/telstrapremiership/playerstats/playerprofile/tabid/10898/clubid/2/playerid/724/seasonid/44/default.aspx NRL profile]\n\n{{Canberra Raiders Squad}}\n{{National Rugby League top points scorers}}\n{{Rugby league footballers with 2,000 NRL points}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Croker, Jarrod}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Canberra Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Country New South Wales Origin rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:NRL All Stars players]]\n[[Category:Prime Minister's XIII players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league centres]]\n[[Category:People from Goulburn, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Bbatt42", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jarrod_Croker"}
{"title_page": "Santiago (name)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Santiago (disambiguation)}}\n\nThere are more that 100,000 place called dan Diego wow what a fact'Santiago''', (also San Iago, San Tiago, Santyago, Sant-Yago, San Thiago) is a [[Spanish language|Spanish]] name that derives from the [[Hebrew]] name [[Jacob]] (''Ya'akov'') via \"Sant Iago\", \"Sant Yago\", \"Santo Iago\", or \"Santo Yago\", first used to denote [[James, son of Zebedee|Saint James the Great]], the brother of [[John the Apostle]].<ref name=\"Dutton\">New York, E. P. Dutton, 1957, OCLC 28087235; reprinted by the Univ. of California Press in 1965 (OCLC 477436336) and published in Spanish translation in 1958 with the somewhat different title of ''El camino de Santiago: las peregrinaciones al sepulcro del Ap\u00f3stol'', trans. Amando L\u00e1zaro Ros, Madrid, Aguilar, 1958, OCLC 432856567. Both the English original and the translation have been republished.</ref>  It was also the tradition that Saint James (Santiago) had travelled to the Iberian Peninsula during his life and was buried there. The name is also complicated in Spanish in that Jaime and Jacobo are modern versions of James.\n\nVariants of Santiago include Iago (a common [[Galician language]] name), and [[Thiago]] or Tiago (a common [[Portuguese language]] name). The common name James has many forms in [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberia]], including Xacobo or Xacobe (in Galician), Jaume, Xaume, Jaime, Jacobo, and Diego (in Spanish). Despite being a [[cognate]], [[San Diego (disambiguation)|San Diego]] does not refer to Saint James but to Saint [[Didacus of Alcal\u00e1]].\n\n\"Santi\" or \"San\" are the nicknames for Santiago, although \"[[Sandy (name)|Sandy]]\" is sometimes used in [[English-speaking world|English-speaking countries]].\n\n==People named Santiago==\n*Santiago, a [[Quechan]] or Yuma chief in the early 1850s\n*[[Santiago Amador]], Colombian road cyclist\n*[[Santiago Amodeo]], Film Director and screenwriter\n*[[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Yeste|Santiago Bernab\u00e9u]], former [[Real Madrid]] president\n** [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]], the stadium of [[Real Madrid]], named after [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Yeste]]\n*[[Santiago Botero]], Colombian cyclist\n*[[Santiago Cabrera]], Chilean actor\n*[[Santiago Calatrava]], Spanish architect\n*[[Santiago Ca\u00f1izares]], Spanish footballer\n*[[Santi Cazorla]], Spanish footballer\n*[[Santiago Espinal]] (born 1994), Dominican Republic professional baseball player\n*[[Santi Freixa]], Spanish field hockey player\n*[[Santiago Iglesias]], congressman from Puerto Rico\n*[[Santiago de Liniers]], French-born defender of Buenos Aires in 1806-1807 and later viceroy\n*[[Santiago Lorenzo]], Argentine decathlete\n*[[Santiago de Murcia]], Spanish baroque guitarist and composer\n*[[Santiago Palavecino]], Argentine boxer\n*[[Santiago de la Parte]], Spanish long-distance runner\n*[[Santiago Phelan]], Argentine rugby player and coach\n*[[Santiago Ram\u00f3n y Cajal]], Spanish histologist and physician\n*[[Santiago Rodriguez (pianist)|Santiago Rodriguez]], pianist and professor from Cuba\n*[[Santiago Schnell]], Venezuelan scientist\n*[[Santiago Solari]], Argentine footballer\n*[[Santiago de Le\u00f3n de Caracas]]\n\n==Fictional characters==\n* [[Santiago Mu\u00f1ez]], Mexican character in the ''Goal'' movie series\n* Santiago Nasar, protagonist of [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]'s novel ''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]''\n* Santiago Arnavisca, a [[Tom_Clancy's_Rainbow_Six#Members_within_the_video_and_computer_game_universe|character]] from the video game series ''Rainbow Six''\n* [[Santiago (The Vampire Chronicles)]], a character in Anne Rice's novel ''Interview with the Vampire''\n* Santiago, main character in Paulo Coelho's novel ''[[The Alchemist (novel)|The Alchemist]]''\n* Santiago, main character in Ernest Hemingway's novel ''[[The Old Man and the Sea]]''\n* Santiago Rivera, a character from the educational computer game series ''[[The ClueFinders]]''\n* Santiago Zavala, a character from ''[[Conversation in the Cathedral]]''\n* Santiago, main antagonist in ''[[Volver a Empezar (telenovela)|Volver a Empezar]]'', a 1994 Mexican [[telenovela]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Santiago (surname)]]\n* [[San Diego]]\n* [[Saint James (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santiago (Name)}}\n[[Category:Spanish masculine given names]]\n\n[[es:Santiago (nombre)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Santiago (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Santiago''', (also San Iago, San Tiago, Santyago, Sant-Yago, San Thiago) is a [[Spanish language|Spanish]] name that derives from the [[Hebrew]] name [[Jacob]] (''Ya'akov'') via \"Sant Iago\", \"Sant Yago\", \"Santo Iago\", or \"Santo Yago\", first used to denote [[James, son of Zebedee|Saint James the Great]], the brother of [[John the Apostle]].<ref name=\"Dutton\">New York, E. P. Dutton, 1957, OCLC 28087235; reprinted by the Univ. of California Press in 1965 (OCLC 477436336) and published in Spanish translation in 1958 with the somewhat different title of ''El camino de Santiago: las peregrinaciones al sepulcro del Ap\u00f3stol'', trans. Amando L\u00e1zaro Ros, Madrid, Aguilar, 1958, OCLC 432856567. Both the English original and the translation have been republished.</ref>  It was also the tradition that Saint James (Santiago) had travelled to the Iberian Peninsula during his life and was buried there. The name is also complicated in Spanish in that Jaime and Jacobo are modern versions of James.\n\nVariants of Santiago include Iago (a common [[Galician language]] name), and [[Thiago]] or Tiago (a common [[Portuguese language]] name). The common name James has many forms in [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberia]], including Xacobo or Xacobe (in Galician), Jaume, Xaume, Jaime, Jacobo, and Diego (in Spanish). Despite being a [[cognate]], [[San Diego (disambiguation)|San Diego]] does not refer to Saint James but to Saint [[Didacus of Alcal\u00e1]].\n\n\"Santi\" or \"San\" are the nicknames for Santiago, although \"[[Sandy (name)|Sandy]]\" is sometimes used in [[English-speaking world|English-speaking countries]].\n\n==People named Santiago==\n*Santiago, a [[Quechan]] or Yuma chief in the early 1850s\n*[[Santiago Amador]], Colombian road cyclist\n*[[Santiago Amodeo]], Film Director and screenwriter\n*[[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Yeste|Santiago Bernab\u00e9u]], former [[Real Madrid]] president\n** [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]], the stadium of [[Real Madrid]], named after [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Yeste]]\n*[[Santiago Botero]], Colombian cyclist\n*[[Santiago Cabrera]], Chilean actor\n*[[Santiago Calatrava]], Spanish architect\n*[[Santiago Ca\u00f1izares]], Spanish footballer\n*[[Santi Cazorla]], Spanish footballer\n*[[Santiago Espinal]] (born 1994), Dominican Republic professional baseball player\n*[[Santi Freixa]], Spanish field hockey player\n*[[Santiago Iglesias]], congressman from Puerto Rico\n*[[Santiago de Liniers]], French-born defender of Buenos Aires in 1806-1807 and later viceroy\n*[[Santiago Lorenzo]], Argentine decathlete\n*[[Santiago de Murcia]], Spanish baroque guitarist and composer\n*[[Santiago Palavecino]], Argentine boxer\n*[[Santiago de la Parte]], Spanish long-distance runner\n*[[Santiago Phelan]], Argentine rugby player and coach\n*[[Santiago Ram\u00f3n y Cajal]], Spanish histologist and physician\n*[[Santiago Rodriguez (pianist)|Santiago Rodriguez]], pianist and professor from Cuba\n*[[Santiago Schnell]], Venezuelan scientist\n*[[Santiago Solari]], Argentine footballer\n*[[Santiago de Le\u00f3n de Caracas]]\n\n==Fictional characters==\n* [[Santiago Mu\u00f1ez]], Mexican character in the ''Goal'' movie series\n* Santiago Nasar, protagonist of [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]'s novel ''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]''\n* Santiago Arnavisca, a [[Tom_Clancy's_Rainbow_Six#Members_within_the_video_and_computer_game_universe|character]] from the video game series ''Rainbow Six''\n* [[Santiago (The Vampire Chronicles)]], a character in Anne Rice's novel ''Interview with the Vampire''\n* Santiago, main character in Paulo Coelho's novel ''[[The Alchemist (novel)|The Alchemist]]''\n* Santiago, main character in Ernest Hemingway's novel ''[[The Old Man and the Sea]]''\n* Santiago Rivera, a character from the educational computer game series ''[[The ClueFinders]]''\n* Santiago Zavala, a character from ''[[Conversation in the Cathedral]]''\n* Santiago, main antagonist in ''[[Volver a Empezar (telenovela)|Volver a Empezar]]'', a 1994 Mexican [[telenovela]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Santiago (surname)]]\n* [[San Diego]]\n* [[Saint James (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santiago (Name)}}\n[[Category:Spanish masculine given names]]\n\n[[es:Santiago (nombre)]]\n", "name_user": "213.205.200.2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santiago_(name)"}
{"title_page": "Siege of G\u00fcns", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Siege of G\u00fcns (K\u0151szeg)\n| image= Belagerung von G\u00fcns.png\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=Edward Sch\u00f6n: Siege of G\u00fcns\n|partof=the [[Little War in Hungary]] within<br />[[Ottoman\u2013Habsburg wars]]<br />and the [[Ottoman wars in Europe]]\n|date=5 August 1532&nbsp;\u2013 30 August 1532<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\">Wheatcroft (2009), p. 59.</ref>\n|place=[[K\u0151szeg]], [[Kingdom of Hungary]] within [[Habsburg Monarchy]] (today's [[Hungary]])\n|result= The defenders prevented the Ottoman advance into Vienna\n|combatant1=[[File:Flag of the Habsburg Monarchy.svg|24px]] [[Habsburg Monarchy]]<br />\n*[[File:Coat of Arms of Hungary.svg|14px]] [[Kingdom of Hungary (1526\u20131867)|Kingdom of Hungary]]\n*[[File:CoA of the Kingdom of Croatia.svg|15px]] [[Kingdom of Croatia (Habsburg)|Kingdom of Croatia]]\n|combatant2=[[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1844).svg|24px]] [[Ottoman Empire]]\n|commander1=[[Nikola Juri\u0161i\u0107]]([[Wounded in action|WIA]])\n|commander2= [[Suleiman the Magnificent]]<br />\n[[Pargal\u0131 Ibrahim Pasha]]\n|strength1=700\u2013800<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\"/>\n|strength2=100,000<ref name=\"A Historical Encyclopedia151\">A Historical Encyclopedia (2011), p. 151</ref>\n|casualties1=Heavy<ref name=\"Vambery298\">Vambery, p. 298</ref>\n|casualties2=Moderate losses<ref name=\"Thompson442\">Thompson (1996), p. 442</ref>\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Little War in Hungary}}\nThe '''Siege of K\u0151szeg''' or in German sources: '''Siege of G\u00fcns''' ({{lang-tr| Ku\u015fatmas\u0131}}) was a siege of [[K\u0151szeg]] ({{lang-de|G\u00fcns}})<ref group=\"Note\">During [[Ottoman\u2013Habsburg wars]], the small border fort was called G\u00fcns since it was under Habsburg jurisdiction, today as a part of [[Hungary]] it is known as K\u0151szeg.</ref> in the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] within the [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg Empire]], that took place in 1532. In the siege, the defending forces of the Austrian [[Habsburg Monarchy]] under the leadership of [[Croats|Croatian]] [[Captain (land)|Captain]] [[Nikola Juri\u0161i\u0107]] ({{lang-hu|Mikl\u00f3s Jurisics}}), defended the small border fort of K\u0151szeg with only 700\u2013800 Croatian soldiers, with no cannons and few guns.<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\"/> The defenders prevented the advance of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] army of 100,000 toward [[Vienna]], under the leadership of [[Ottoman Sultan|Sultan]] [[Suleiman the Magnificent]] ({{lang-ota|\u0633\u0644\u064a\u0645\u0627\u0646}} ''S\u00fcleym\u0101n'') and [[Pargal\u0131 Ibrahim Pasha]].<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\"/><ref name=\"Turnbull51\">Turnbull (2003), p. 51.</ref>\n\nThe exact outcome is unknown, since there are two versions which differ, depending on the source. In the first version, Nikola Juri\u0161i\u0107 rejected the offer to surrender on favourable terms; in the second version, the city was offered terms for a nominal surrender. Suleiman, having been delayed nearly four weeks, withdrew at the arrival of the August rains,<ref name=\"Turnbull51\"/> and did not continue towards Vienna as he had intended, but turned homeward.<ref name=\"Vambery298\"/>\n\nSuleiman secured his possession in Hungary by conquering several other forts,<ref name=\"Akgunduz and Ozturk184\">Akgunduz and Ozturk (2011), p. 184.</ref> but after the Ottoman withdrawal, Habsburg Emperor [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] reoccupied some of the devastated territory. Following this, Suleiman and Ferdinand concluded a [[Treaty of Constantinople (1533)|1533 treaty of Constantinople]] that confirmed the right of [[John Z\u00e1polya]] as a king of all Hungary, but recognised Ferdinand's possession of some of the reoccupied territory.<ref name=\"Turnbull51-52\">Turnbull (2003), pp. 51\u201352.</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{See also|Ottoman\u2013Habsburg wars}}\n[[File:K\u0151szeg ostrom\u00e1nak eml\u00e9kt\u00e1bl\u00e1ja.jpg|thumb|right|Monument of the Siege of K\u0151szeg, located in the bourg of K\u0151szeg]]\nOn 29 August 1526, at the [[Battle of Moh\u00e1cs]], the [[Western Christianity|Christian]] forces led by [[Louis II of Hungary|King Louis II]] were defeated by [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces led by Sultan [[Suleiman the Magnificent]].<ref name=\"Turnbull49\">Turnbull (2003), p. 49</ref> Louis was killed in the battle, which resulted in the end of the independent [[Kingdom of Hungary]] as he died without an heir. Both the Kingdoms of Hungary and [[Kingdom of Croatia (Habsburg)|Croatia]] became disputed territories with claims from both the Habsburg and Ottoman empires. Habsburg Emperor [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]], who was a brother of [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor Charles V]], married the sister of Louis II<ref name=\"Turnbull, 49-51\">Turnbull (2003), pp. 49\u201351.</ref> and was elected King by the nobles of both Hungary and Croatia.<ref name=\"Corvisier and Childs289\">Corvisier and Childs (1994), p. 289</ref>{{refn|group=\"Note\"|In 1527, the Croatian nobles [[1527 election in Cetin|met in Cetin to elect Ferdinand as their king]].<ref>{{cite book | url = https://archive.org/stream/southernslavques00seto/southernslavques00seto_djvu.txt | author = R. W. Seton-Watson | title = The southern Slav question and the Habsburg Monarchy | page = 18 | isbn = | year = | accessdate = }}</ref>}}\n\nThe throne of Hungary became the subject of a dynastic dispute between Ferdinand and [[John Z\u00e1polya]] from [[Transylvania]], since Suleiman had promised to make Z\u00e1polya the ruler of all Hungary.<ref name=\"Turnbull, 55-56\">Turnbull (2003), pp. 55\u201356.</ref> During [[Hungarian campaign of 1527\u20131528]], Ferdinand captured [[Buda]] from John Z\u00e1polya in 1527, only to relinquish his hold on it in 1529 when an Ottoman counter-attack stripped Ferdinand of all his territorial gains during 1527 and 1528.<ref name=\"Turnbull, 49-51\"/> The [[siege of Vienna]] in 1529 was the first attempt by Suleiman the Magnificent to capture the Austrian capital. This siege signalled the pinnacle of Ottoman power and the maximum extent of Ottoman expansion in central Europe.<ref name=\"Turnbull, 49-51\"/>\n\n===Little War in Hungary===\n{{Main|Little War in Hungary}}\nFollowing Suleiman's unsuccessful Siege of Vienna in 1529, Ferdinand launched a counter-attack in 1530 to regain the initiative and avenge the destruction brought by Suleiman's 120,000 strong army. This campaign is usually considered as the start of the [[Little War in Hungary|Little War]], the period of a series of conflicts between the Habsburgs and the Ottoman Empire. An assault of Buda was driven off by [[John Z\u00e1polya]], the vassal King of Hungary, but Ferdinand was successful elsewhere, capturing [[Esztergom|Gran]] (Esztergom) and other forts along the Danube river, a vital strategic frontier.<ref name=\"Turnbull51\"/>\n\n==Campaign of 1532==\n{{See also|List of campaigns of Suleiman the Magnificent}}\nDuring the early period of the Little War in Hungary, Suleiman, as a response to Ferdinand's counter-attack in 1530, and as a part of his fifth [[List of campaigns of Suleiman the Magnificent|imperial campaign]]<ref name=\"Z\u00fcrcher38\">Z\u00fcrcher (1999), p. 38.</ref> ({{lang-ota|\u0633\u0641\u0631 \u0647\u0645\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646}}, ''Sefer-i hum\u0101y\u016bn''){{refn|group=\"Note\"|The Ottoman Turkish name for the imperial campaigns, according to [[Sami Frash\u00ebri|\u015eemseddin S\u00e2m\u00ee]] (Frash\u00ebri).<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=axw-AQAAIAAJ&pg=PT881&dq=%22+%D8%B3%D9%81%D8%B1+%D9%87%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%86%22&hl=en&ei=_Sb5TceLOMHqrAeWs4XwDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CE4Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%22%20%D8%B3%D9%81%D8%B1%20%D9%87%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%86%22&f=false | title =  ''Kam\u00fbs-\u00fcl \u00c2'l\u00e2m'' | author = Sami Frash\u00ebri}}</ref>}} in 1532, led a massive army of over 120,000 troops to besiege Vienna again. Due to Suleiman's rapid advances, Ferdinand feared the Christian forces would not be assembled in time to meet him.<ref name=\"Setton 364\">Setton (1984), p. 364.</ref> On 12 July, Suleiman wrote to Ferdinand from [[Osijek]] ({{lang-de|Esseg}}) in Slavonia, to assure him of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] advance.<ref name=\"Setton 364\"/> According to the letter, Suleiman's fifth campaign was primarily directed against [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]], and not personally against Ferdinand.<ref name=\"Setton 364\u2013365\">Setton (1984), pp. 364\u2013365.</ref> After Suleiman crossed the river [[Drava]] at Osijek, instead of taking the usual route for Vienna, he turned westwards into Ferdinand's Hungarian territory.<ref name=\"Turnbull51\"/> According to historian Andrew Wheatcroft, on the route for Vienna, the Ottoman army had briefly invested and captured seventeen fortified towns or castles.<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\"/> Ferdinand withdrew his army, leaving only 700 men with no cannons and a few guns to defend [[K\u0151szeg]].<ref name=\"Turnbull51\"/>\n\nHowever, in order to make decisive gains, the Ottomans had to take the city quickly, as a large Imperial army, raised in Germany, reinforced by Spanish troops and led by the Emperor Charles V himself was approaching in support of Ferdinand.<ref>''History of the Habsburg empire'', Jean B\u00e9renger</ref>\n\n===Siege===\n[[File:K\u0151szeg - Jurisics Castle.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial view of [[Jurisics Castle]] in K\u0151szeg]]\nLocated south of [[Sopron]], the small town of K\u0151szeg was only a few miles from the Austrian border.<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\"/> It was held by a task force commanded by the [[Croats|Croatian]] soldier and diplomat [[Nikola Juri\u0161i\u0107]].<ref name=\"Setton 365\">Setton (1984), p. 365.</ref> K\u0151szeg was not considered a place of importance.<ref name=\"Setton 365\"/> It was an insubstantial obstacle and many stronger places had yielded without a fight.<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\"/> The Grand Vizier of the Ottomans, [[Pargal\u0131 Ibrahim Pasha|Ibrahim Pasha]], did not realize how poorly defended K\u0151szeg was. After taking a few minor places, Suleiman came to join Ibrahim Pasha shortly afterwards, when the siege had already started.<ref name=\"Turnbull51\"/>\n\nThe Ottomans met stiff resistance at K\u0151szeg.<ref name=\"Setton 365\"/> Suleiman had hoped that the imperial army would come to relieve K\u0151szeg, affording him an opportunity for a larger engagement.<ref name=\"Setton 366\">Setton (1984), p. 366.</ref> However, during the Ottoman attacks on K\u0151szeg, the imperial army still formed up in [[Regensburg]].<ref name=\"Gregg169\">Gregg (2009), p. 169.</ref> The Ottomans continued with one attack after another; artillery fire brought down parts of the walls, but brought no surrender.<ref name=\"Setton 365\"/>{{refn|group=\"Note\"|According to a historian [[Paolo Giovio]], the siege of G\u00fcns failed because the Ottomans had not brought large siege guns, expecting to engage the Emperor in a field battle.<ref>Gregg (2009), pp. 168\u2013169.</ref>}} The Ottomans' mines were sapped by countermines.<ref name=\"Setton 365\"/> The layout of K\u0151szeg's walls made mining a feasible strategy, but even though several mines succeeded in blowing holes in the fortifications, the defenders held out.<ref name=\"Turnbull51\"/> For more than twenty-five days, without any artillery, Captain Nikola Juri\u0161i\u0107 and his garrison of 700 local Hungarian peasants and a few Croat soldiers held out against nineteen full-scale assaults and an incessant bombardment by the Ottomans.<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\"/>\n\nThere are two versions of the outcome. In the first version, Nikola Juri\u0161i\u0107 rejected the offer to surrender on favourable terms, and the Ottomans retreated.<ref name=\"Wheatcroft59\"/><ref name=\"Thompson442\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1goston and Alan Masters583\">\u00c1goston and Alan Masters (2009), p. 583</ref> In the second version, the city was offered terms for a nominal surrender. The only Ottomans who would be allowed to enter the castle would be a token force who would raise the [[Ottoman flag]].<ref name=\"Turnbull51\"/>\n\nIn both versions, Suleiman withdrew at the arrival of the August rains,<ref name=\"Turnbull51\"/> and returned homeward instead of continuing towards Vienna as previously planned.<ref name=\"Vambery298\"/> He had been delayed nearly four weeks, and during this time a powerful army had been collected in Vienna, which Suleiman did not intend to face.<ref name=\"Vambery298\"/> According to historian Paolo Giovio, Charles arrived with an imperial army at Vienna on 23 September, too late to fight the Ottomans because Suleiman had already withdrawn.<ref name=\"Zimmerman124\">Zimmerman (1995), p. 124</ref> By their defense of K\u0151szeg, Nikola Juri\u0161i\u0107 and his men had saved Vienna from a siege.<ref name=\"Vambery298\"/>{{refn|group=\"Note\"|According to \"A Historical Encyclopedia\", the dogged defense of K\u0151szeg convinced Suleiman to give up on besieging Vienna, which was much more fortified.<ref name=\"A Historical Encyclopedia151\"/>}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{See also|Treaty of Constantinople (1533)}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Statue of Nikola Jurisic in Senj, Croatia.JPG\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Statue of Nikola Jurisic in Koszeg, Hungary.JPG\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Statue of Nikola Juri\u0161i\u0107 in [[Senj]], [[Croatia]] (left) and in [[K\u0151szeg]], [[Hungary]] (right)\n}}\nAlthough he was stopped at K\u0151szeg and failed to conquer Vienna, Suleiman additionally secured his possession in Hungary by conquering several forts, since Ferdinand and Charles evaded an open field battle.<ref name=\"Akgunduz and Ozturk184\"/> Immediately after the Ottoman withdrawal, Ferdinand reoccupied devastated territory in Austria and Hungary.<ref name=\"Black26\">Black (1996), p. 26.</ref> Nevertheless, Suleiman concluded a [[Treaty of Constantinople (1533)|peace treaty]] with Ferdinand in 1533, in [[Constantinople]].<ref name=\"Turnbull51-52\"/> The treaty confirmed the right of [[John Z\u00e1polya]] as a king of all Hungary, but recognised Ferdinand's possession of that part of the country that enjoyed the status quo.<ref name=\"Turnbull51-52\"/>\n\nThis treaty did not satisfy Z\u00e1polya or Ferdinand, whose armies began to skirmish along the borders. After Z\u00e1polya's death in 1540, Suleiman annexed Hungary to the Ottoman realm.<ref name=\"Scott58-59\">Scott (2011), pp. 58\u201359.</ref> Although from 1529 to 1566 the borders of the Ottoman Empire moved further west, none of the campaigns after 1529 achieved the decisive victory that would secure the new Ottoman possessions.<ref name=\"Uyar and Erickson74\">Uyar and Erickson (2009), p. 74.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|War}}\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | last=\u00c1goston and Alan Masters | first=G\u00e1bor and Bruce | title=Encyclopedia of the Ottoman Empire | publisher=Infobase Publishing | location= | year=2009 | isbn=9780816062591}}\n* {{cite book | last1=Akgunduz | first1=Ahmed | last2=Ozturk | first2=Said | url= | title=Ottoman History: Misperceptions and Truths | location= | publisher=IUR Press | year=2011 | isbn=978-90-902610-8-9}}\n* {{cite book | last=Black | first=Jeremy | title=Cambridge illustrated atlas, warfare: Renaissance to revolution, 1492-1792 | publisher=Cambridge University Press | location= | year=1996 | isbn=978-0-521-47033-9}}\n* {{cite book | last1=Corvisier | first1=Andr\u00e9 | last2=Childs | first2=John | url=https://books.google.hr/books?id=nEQ7FUAdmc8C&dq=A+Dictionary+of+Military+History+and+the+Art+of+War,&source=gbs_navlinks_s | title=A dictionary of military history and the art of war | location